{"title_page": "Bioterrorism", "text_new": "[[File:NBC-Mask M-17.jpg|thumb|United States [[Airman]] wearing an [[M17 gas mask|M-17]] nuclear, biological, and chemical warfare mask and hood]]\n{{terrorism}}\n\n'''Bioterrorism''' is [[terrorism]] involving the intentional release or dissemination of [[biological agent]]s. These agents are [[bacteria]], [[virus]]es, insects, fungi, or [[toxin]]s, and may be in a naturally occurring or a human-modified form, in much the same way in [[biological warfare]]. Further, modern [[agribusiness]] is vulnerable to [[:Category:Anti-agriculture_weapons|anti-agricultural]] attacks by terrorists, and such attacks can seriously damage economy as well as [[consumer confidence]].<ref name=\"croodybook\">{{cite book |last1=Croddy |first1=Eric |last2=Perez-Armendariz |first2=Clarissa |last3=Hart |first3=John |title=Chemical and biological warfare : a comprehensive survey for the concerned citizen |date=2002 |publisher=Copernicus Books |isbn=0387950761 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/chemicalbiologic00crod/page/78 78-84] |url=https://archive.org/details/chemicalbiologic00crod/page/78 }}</ref> The later destructive activity is called '''agrobioterrorism''' and is subtype of [[agro-terrorism]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Roberge |first1=Lawrence F. |title=Agrobioterrorism |journal=Defense Against Biological Attacks: Volume II |date=2019 |pages=359\u2013383 |doi=10.1007/978-3-030-03071-1_16 |isbn=978-3-030-03070-4 |publisher=Springer International Publishing |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Definition==\nBioterrorism is the deliberate release of viruses, bacteria, toxins or other harmful agents to cause illness or death in people, animals, or plants.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bioterrorism {{!}} Anthrax {{!}} CDC|url=https://www.cdc.gov/anthrax/bioterrorism/index.html|website=www.cdc.gov|accessdate=25 October 2017|language=en-us}}</ref> These agents are typically found in nature, but could be mutated or altered to increase their ability to cause disease, make them resistant to current medicines, or to increase their ability to be spread into the environment. Biological agents can be spread through the air, water, or in food. Biological agents are attractive to [[Terrorism|terrorists]] because they are extremely difficult to detect and do not cause illness for several hours to several days. Some bioterrorism agents, like the [[smallpox virus]], can be spread from person to person and some, like [[anthrax]], cannot.<ref name=\"CDCBioterrorismOverview\">{{cite web|title=Bioterrorism Overview|url=http://www.bt.cdc.gov/bioterrorism/overview.asp|accessdate=2009-05-22|date=2008-02-12|publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303184927/http://www.bt.cdc.gov/bioterrorism/overview.asp|archivedate=2016-03-03}}</ref><ref>Preston, Richard (2002). ''The Demon in the Freezer'', Ballantine Books, New York. {{ISBN|9780345466631}}.</ref>\n\nBioterrorism may be favored because biological agents are relatively easy and inexpensive to obtain, can be easily disseminated, and can cause widespread fear and panic beyond the actual physical damage.<ref>Advantages of Biologics as Weapons Bioterrorism: A Threat to National Security or Public Health Defining Issue? MM&I 554 University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison and Wisconsin State Laboratory of Hygiene, September 30, 2008.</ref> Military leaders, however, have learned that, as a military asset, bioterrorism has some important limitations; it is difficult to use a bioweapon in a way that only affects the enemy and not friendly forces. A biological weapon is useful to terrorists mainly as a method of creating mass panic and disruption to a state or a country. However, technologists such as [[Bill Joy]] have warned of the potential power which genetic engineering might place in the hands of future bio-terrorists.<ref>{{citation|last=Joy|first=Bill|title=Why the Future Doesn't Need Us: How 21st Century Technologies Threaten to Make Humans an Endangered Species|date=2007-03-31|publisher=Random House|isbn=978-0-553-52835-0|title-link=Why the Future Doesn't Need Us}}</ref>\n\nThe use of agents that do not cause harm to humans, but disrupt the economy, have also been discussed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agpolicy.org/weekpdf/116.pdf|title=Bioterrorism - the high economic costs of an attack|date=October 2002}}</ref> One such pathogen is the [[foot-and-mouth disease]] (FMD) virus, which is capable of causing widespread economic damage and public concern (as witnessed in the [[2001 United Kingdom foot-and-mouth outbreak|2001]] and [[2007 United Kingdom foot-and-mouth outbreak|2007]] FMD outbreaks in the UK), while having almost no capacity to infect humans.\n\n==History==\n{{see also|History of biological warfare}}\n\nBy the time [[World War I]] began, attempts to use anthrax were directed at animal populations. This generally proved to be ineffective.\n\nShortly after the start of World War I, Germany launched a biological sabotage campaign in the United States, Russia, Romania, and France.<ref name=\"GregoryBWaggDMilitaryMedicine\">{{citation|last=Gregory|first=B|author2=Waag, D.|title=Military Medicine: Medical aspects of biological warfare|url=http://www.bordeninstitute.army.mil/published_volumes/biological_warfare/BW-ch06.pdf|accessdate=2009-05-22|year=1997|publisher=Office of the Surgeon General, Department of the Army|id=Library of Congress 97-22242|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090612003248/http://www.bordeninstitute.army.mil/published_volumes/biological_warfare/BW-ch06.pdf|archive-date=2009-06-12|url-status=dead}}</ref> At that time, [[Anton Dilger]] lived in Germany, but in 1915 he was sent to the United States carrying cultures of [[glanders]], a virulent disease of horses and mules. Dilger set up a laboratory in his home in [[Chevy Chase, Maryland|Chevy Chase]], Maryland. He used [[stevedore]]s working the docks in Baltimore to infect horses with [[glanders]] while they were waiting to be shipped to Britain. Dilger was under suspicion as being a German agent, but was never arrested. Dilger eventually fled to Madrid, Spain, where he died during the [[1918 flu pandemic|Influenza Pandemic of 1918]].<ref>{{citation|title=Experts Q & A|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/weapon/sfeature/qa.html|accessdate=2009-05-22|date=2006-12-15|publisher=Public Broadcasting Service}}</ref> In 1916, the Russians arrested a German agent with similar intentions. Germany and its allies infected French cavalry horses and many of Russia's mules and horses on the Eastern Front. These actions hindered artillery and troop movements, as well as supply convoys.<ref name=\"GregoryBWaggDMilitaryMedicine\" />\n \t\nIn 1972, police in [[Chicago]] arrested two college students, Allen Schwander and Stephen Pera, who had planned to poison the city's water supply with [[typhoid]] and other bacteria. Schwander had founded a terrorist group, \"R.I.S.E.\", while Pera collected and grew cultures from the hospital where he worked. The two men fled to [[Cuba]] after being released on bail. Schwander died of natural causes in 1974, while Pera returned to the U.S. in 1975 and was put on probation.<ref>W. Seth Carus, \"R.I.S.E.\", in ''Toxic Terror: Assessing Terrorist Use of Chemical and Biological Weapons'' (MIT Press, 2000), p.55, p.69</ref>\n\nIn 1980, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) announced the eradication of smallpox, a highly contagious and incurable disease. Although the disease has been eliminated in the wild, frozen stocks of smallpox virus are still maintained by the governments of the United States and Russia. Disastrous consequences are feared if rogue politicians or terrorists were to get hold of the smallpox strains. Since vaccination programs are now terminated, the world population is more susceptible to smallpox than ever before.\n\nIn [[Oregon]] in 1984, followers of the [[Rajneesh|Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh]] attempted to control a local [[election]] by [[1984 Rajneeshee bioterror attack|incapacitating the local population]]. This was done by infecting [[salad]] bars in 11 restaurants, produce in grocery stores, doorknobs, and other public domains with ''[[Salmonella typhimurium]]'' bacteria in the city of [[The Dalles]], [[Oregon]]. The attack infected 751 people with severe [[food poisoning]]. There were no fatalities. This incident was the first known bioterrorist attack in the United States in the 20th century.<ref>[http://www.medmicro.wisc.edu/undergraduate/courses/554/ppt/BT-PHproblem081030.ppt#363,15, Past U.S. Incidents of Food Bioterrorism. In Bioterrorism: A Threat to National Security or Public Health Defining Issue, University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison and the Wisconsin State Laboratory of Hygiene, MM&I 554, September 30, 2008]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> It was also the single largest bioterrorism attack on U.S. soil.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gizmodo.com.au/2016/11/the-largest-bioterrorism-attack-in-us-history-was-an-attempt-to-swing-an-election/|title=The Largest Bioterrorism Attack In US History Was An Attempt To Swing An Election|last=Novak|first=Matt|date=2016-11-03|work=Gizmodo|access-date=2016-12-02|via=}}</ref>\n \t\nIn June 1993, the religious group [[Aum Shinrikyo]] released anthrax in Tokyo. Eyewitnesses reported a foul odor. The attack was a failure, as it did not infect a single person. The reason for this is that the group used the vaccine strain of the bacterium. The spores recovered from the attack showed that they were identical to an anthrax vaccine strain given to animals at the time. These vaccine strains are missing the genes that cause a symptomatic response.<ref name=\"cdc.gov\">[http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/10/1/03-0238_article CDC-'''Bacillus anthracis''' Incident, Kameido, Tokyo, 1993]</ref>\n\nIn September and October 2001, several cases of [[2001 anthrax attacks|anthrax broke out]] in the [[United States]], apparently caused deliberately. Letters laced with infectious anthrax were concurrently delivered to news media offices and the U.S Congress, alongside an [[2001 anthrax attacks#Anthrax letter to Chile|ambiguously related case]] in [[Chile]]. The letters killed 5.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2008/CRIME/08/06/anthrax.case/index.html CNN]</ref>\n\n==Types of agents==\n{{Globalize|section|USA|2name=the United States|date=June 2012}}\nUnder current [[United States law]], [[bio-agents]] which have been declared by the [[U.S. Department of Health and Human Services]] or the [[U.S. Department of Agriculture]] to have the \"potential to pose a severe threat to public health and safety\" are officially defined as \"[[select agents]].\" The CDC categorizes these agents (A, B or C) and administers the [[Select Agent Program]], which regulates the laboratories which may possess, use, or transfer select agents within the United States. As with US attempts to categorize harmful recreational drugs, designer viruses are not yet categorized and avian H5N1 has been shown to achieve high mortality and human-communication in a laboratory setting.\n\n===Category A===\nThese high-priority agents pose a risk to national security, can be easily transmitted and disseminated, result in high mortality, have potential major public health impact, may cause public panic, or require special action for public health preparedness.\n\n* Tularemia or \"rabbit fever\":<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/tularemia/|title=CDC Tularemia - Emergency Preparedness & Response|publisher=|date=2019-02-21}}</ref> Tularemia has a very low fatality rate if treated, but can severely incapacitate. The disease is caused by the ''[[Francisella tularensis]]'' bacterium, and can be contracted through contact with [[fur]], inhalation, ingestion of contaminated water or insect bites. ''Francisella tularensis'' is very infectious. A small number of organisms (10\u201350 or so) can cause disease. If ''F. tularensis'' were used as a weapon, the bacteria would likely be made airborne for exposure by inhalation. People who inhale an infectious aerosol would generally experience severe respiratory illness, including life-threatening pneumonia and systemic infection, if they are not treated. The bacteria that cause tularemia occur widely in nature and could be isolated and grown in quantity in a laboratory, although manufacturing an effective aerosol weapon would require considerable sophistication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bt.cdc.gov/agent/tularemia/facts.asp|title=CDC Tularemia - Key Facts About Tularemia|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619165524/http://www.bt.cdc.gov/agent/tularemia/facts.asp|archivedate=2010-06-19}}</ref>\n* [[Anthrax disease|Anthrax]]: Anthrax is a non-contagious disease caused by the spore-forming bacterium ''Bacillus anthracis''. The ability of Anthrax to produce within small spores, or bacilli bacterium, makes it readily permeable to porous skin and can cause abrupt symptoms within 24 hours of exposure. The dispersal of this pathogen among densely populated areas is said to carry less than one percent mortality rate, for cutaneous exposure, to a ninety percent or higher mortality for untreated inhalational infections.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Adalja|first=Amesh A.|last2=Toner|first2=Eric|last3=Inglesby|first3=Thomas V.|date=2015-03-05|title=Clinical Management of Potential Bioterrorism-Related Conditions|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=372|issue=10|pages=954\u2013962|doi=10.1056/NEJMra1409755|issn=0028-4793|pmid=25738671}}</ref> An [[anthrax vaccines|anthrax vaccine]] does exist but requires many injections for stable use. When discovered early, anthrax can be cured by administering [[antibiotic]]s (such as [[ciprofloxacin]]).<ref>{{cite journal\n  |title = A Short Course of Antibiotic Treatment Is Effective in Preventing Death from Experimental Inhalational Anthrax after Discontinuing Antibiotics\n  |last1 = Vietri\n  |first1 = Nicholas J.\n  |last2 = Purcell\n  |first2 = Bret K.\n  |last3 = Tobery\n  |first3 = Steven A.\n  |last4 = Rasmussen\n  |first4 = Suzanne L.\n  |last5 = Leffel\n  |first5 = Elizabeth K.\n  |last6 = Twenhafel\n  |first6 = Nancy A.\n  |last7 = Ivins\n  |first7 = Bruce E.\n  |last8 = Kellogg\n  |first8 = Mark D.\n  |last9 = Webster\n  |first9 = Wendy M.\n  |last10 = Wright\n  |first10 = Mary E.\n  |last11 = Friedlander\n  |first11 = Arthur M.\n  |journal = [[The Journal of Infectious Diseases]]\n  |issn = 0022-1899\n  |volume = 199\n  |issue = 3\n  |year = 2009\n  |pages = 336\u201341\n  |jstor = 40254424\n  \n  \n  |doi=10.1086/596063\n|pmid = 19099484\n  |doi-access = free\n  }}</ref> Its first modern incidence in biological warfare were when Scandinavian \"freedom fighters\" supplied by the German General Staff used anthrax with unknown results against the Imperial Russian Army in Finland in 1916.<ref>Bisher, Jamie, \"During World War I, Terrorists Schemed to Use Anthrax in the Cause of Finnish Independence,\" Military History, August 2003, pp. 17\u201322.[https://web.archive.org/web/20091027151654/http://geocities.com/jamie_bisher/anthrax.htm Anthrax Sabotage in Finland]</ref> In 1993, the [[Aum Shinrikyo]] used anthrax in an unsuccessful attempt in Tokyo with zero fatalities.<ref name=\"cdc.gov\"/> Anthrax was used in a [[2001 anthrax attack|series of attacks]] by a microbiologist at the US Army Medical Research Institute of Infection Disease on the offices of several United States Senators in late 2001. The anthrax was in a powder form and it was delivered by the mail.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/eid/vol8no10/02-0330.htm|title=Emerging Infectious Diseases journal|publisher=|access-date=2017-09-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101015112554/http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/eid/vol8no10/02-0330.htm|archive-date=2010-10-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> This bioterrorist attack inevitably prompted seven cases of cutaneous anthrax and eleven cases of inhalation anthrax, with five leading to deaths. Additionally, an estimated 10 to 26 cases had prevented fatality through treatment supplied to over 30,000 individuals.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Clarke|first=S. C.|date=2005|title=Bacteria as potential tools in bioterrorism, with an emphasis on bacterial toxins|journal=British Journal of Biomedical Science|volume=62|issue=1|pages=40\u201346|issn=0967-4845|pmid=15816214|doi=10.1080/09674845.2005.11732685}}</ref> Anthrax is one of the few biological agents that federal employees have been vaccinated for. In the US an anthrax vaccine, [[Anthrax Vaccine Adsorbed]] (AVA) exists and requires five injections for stable use. Other [[anthrax vaccines]] also exist. The strain used in the 2001 anthrax attack was identical to the strain used by the [[USAMRIID]].<ref name=\"MacKenzie\">{{cite magazine |author=Debora MacKenzie |title=Anthrax attack bug 'identical' to army strain |magazine=New Scientist |accessdate=16 February 2013 |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn2265\n }}</ref>\n* [[Smallpox]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/smallpox/|title=CDC Smallpox Home|publisher=|date=2019-02-19}}</ref> Smallpox is a highly contagious [[virus]]. It is transmitted easily through the atmosphere and has a high [[mortality rate]] (20\u201340%). Smallpox was [[smallpox#Eradication|eradicated]] in the world in the 1970s, thanks to a worldwide vaccination program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/smallpox/prep/cdc-prep.asp|title=CDC Smallpox - What CDC Is Doing to Protect the Public From Smallpox|access-date=2018-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504090748/https://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/smallpox/prep/cdc-prep.asp|archive-date=2018-05-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, some virus samples are still available in Russian and American laboratories. Some believe that after the collapse of the Soviet Union, cultures of smallpox have become available in other countries. Although people born pre-1970 will have been vaccinated for smallpox under the WHO program, the effectiveness of vaccination is limited since the vaccine provides high level of immunity for only 3 to 5 years. Revaccination's protection lasts longer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smallpox.mil/messageMap/messageMapAll.asp?cID=57|title=IHB - The DoD Immunization Information and Training Portal|access-date=2009-05-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814032533/http://smallpox.mil/messageMap/messageMapAll.asp?cID=57|archive-date=2009-08-14|url-status=dead}}</ref> As a biological weapon smallpox is dangerous because of the highly contagious nature of both the infected and their pox. Also, the infrequency with which vaccines are administered among the general population since the eradication of the disease would leave most people unprotected in the event of an outbreak. Smallpox occurs only in humans, and has no external hosts or vectors.\n* [[Botulinum toxin]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/botulism/|title=CDC Botulism - Emergency Preparedness & Response|publisher=|date=2019-08-19}}</ref> The neurotoxin<ref>{{cite journal|title=BOTULINUM TOXIN | pmc=2856357 | pmid=20418969|doi=10.4103/0019-5154.60343|volume=55| issue=1 |year=2010|pages=8\u201314 | last1 = Nigam | first1 = PK | last2 = Nigam | first2 = A | journal=Indian Journal of Dermatology}}</ref> Botulinum is the deadliest toxin known to man, and is produced by the bacterium ''[[Clostridium botulinum]]''. Botulism causes death by [[respiratory failure]] and [[paralysis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/botulism/factsheet.asp|title=CDC - Facts About Botulism|access-date=2018-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703054124/https://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/botulism/factsheet.asp|archive-date=2017-07-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> Furthermore, the toxin is readily available worldwide due to its cosmetic applications in injections.\n*[[Bubonic plague]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/plague/|title=CDC Plague Information - Emergency Preparedness & Response|publisher=|date=2019-02-21}}</ref> Plague is a disease caused by the ''[[Yersinia pestis]]'' bacterium. Rodents are the normal host of plague, and the disease is transmitted to humans by [[flea]] bites and occasionally by [[Bioaerosol|aerosol]] in the form of [[pneumonic plague]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dvbid/plague/index.htm|title=CDC - 01 This Page Has Moved - CDC Plague Home Page - CDC Division of Vector-Borne Infectious Diseases (DVBID)|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519183229/http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dvbid/plague/index.htm|archivedate=2009-05-19}}</ref> The disease has a history of use in biological warfare dating back many centuries, and is considered a threat due to its ease of culture and ability to remain in circulation among local rodents for a long period of time. The weaponized threat comes mainly in the form of pneumonic plague (infection by inhalation)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bt.cdc.gov/agent/plague/faq.asp|title=CDC Plague - Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) About Plague|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090528004421/http://www.bt.cdc.gov/agent/plague/faq.asp|archivedate=2009-05-28}}</ref> It was the disease that caused the [[Black Death]] in Medieval Europe.\n* [[Viral hemorrhagic fever]]s:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/vhf/|title=CDC Viral Hemorrhagic Fevers - Emergency Preparedness & Response|publisher=|date=2019-05-16}}</ref> This includes hemorrhagic fevers caused by members of the family ''[[Filoviridae]]'' ([[Marburg virus]] and [[Ebola virus]]), and by the family ''[[Arenaviridae]]'' (for example [[Lassa virus]] and [[Machupo virus]]). [[Ebola virus disease]], in particular, has caused high [[fatality rate]]s ranging from 25\u201390% with a 50% average. No cure currently exists, although vaccines are in development. The Soviet Union investigated the use of filoviruses for biological warfare, and the [[Aum Shinrikyo]] group unsuccessfully attempted to obtain cultures of Ebola virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/5/4/99-0409_article|title=Aum Shinrikyo: Once and Future Threat? |publisher=|date=1999-08-04}}</ref> Death from Ebola virus disease is commonly due to [[multiple organ failure]] and [[hypovolemic shock]]. Marburg virus was first discovered in [[Marburg]], Germany. No treatments currently exist aside from supportive care. The arenaviruses have a somewhat reduced case-fatality rate compared to disease caused by filoviruses, but are more widely distributed, chiefly in central [[Africa]] and [[South America]].\n\n===Category B===\nCategory B agents are moderately easy to disseminate and have low mortality rates.\n\n* [[Brucellosis]] ([[Brucella|''Brucella'' species]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/brucellosis/|title=CDC Brucellosis - Emergency Preparedness & Response|publisher=|date=2019-05-16}}</ref>\n* Epsilon toxin of ''[[Clostridium perfringens]]''\n* Food safety threats (for example, ''[[Salmonella]] species'', [[Escherichia coli O157:H7|''E coli'' O157:H7]], ''[[Shigella]]'', [[Staphylococcus aureus]]'')\n* [[Glanders]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/nczved/dfbmd/disease_listing/glanders_gi.html |title=CDC Glanders |access-date=2017-09-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100209041042/http://www.cdc.gov/nczved/dfbmd/disease_listing/glanders_gi.html |archive-date=2010-02-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref> (''[[Burkholderia mallei]]'')\n* [[Melioidosis]] (''[[Burkholderia pseudomallei]]'')<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/nczved/dfbmd/disease_listing/melioidosis_gi.html |title=CDC Melioidosis |access-date=2017-09-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211092041/http://www.cdc.gov/nczved/dfbmd/disease_listing/melioidosis_gi.html |archive-date=2010-02-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/nczved/dfbmd/disease_listing/melioidosis_gi.html#2 |title=CDC Why has melioidosis become a current issue? |access-date=2017-09-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211092041/http://www.cdc.gov/nczved/dfbmd/disease_listing/melioidosis_gi.html#2 |archive-date=2010-02-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Psittacosis]] (''[[Chlamydia psittaci]]'')\n* [[Q fever]] (''[[Coxiella burnetii]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/qfever/|title=CDC Q Fever - Emergency Preparedness and Response|publisher=|date=2019-01-15}}</ref>\n* [[Ricin]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/ricin/|title=CDC Ricin - Emergency Preparedness & Response|publisher=|date=2019-05-16}}</ref> toxin from ''[[Castor oil plant|Ricinus communis]]'' ([[castor bean]]s)\n* [[Abrin]] toxin from ''[[Abrus precatorius]]'' ([[Rosary pea]]s)\n* [[Staphylococcus|Staphylococcal]] enterotoxin B\n* [[Typhus]] (''[[Rickettsia prowazekii]]'')\n* Viral [[encephalitis]] ([[alphavirus]]es, for example,: [[Venezuelan equine encephalitis virus|Venezuelan equine encephalitis]], [[Eastern equine encephalitis virus|eastern equine encephalitis]], [[Western equine encephalitis virus|western equine encephalitis]])\n* Water supply threats (for example, ''[[Vibrio cholerae]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webmd.com/a-to-z-guides/cholera-11156|title=Cholera|work=WebMD}}</ref> ''[[Cryptosporidium parvum]]'')\n\n===Category C===\nCategory C agents are emerging [[pathogen]]s that might be [[genetic engineering|engineered]] for mass dissemination because of their availability, ease of production and dissemination, high mortality rate, or ability to cause a major health impact.\n\n* [[Nipah virus]]\n* [[Hantavirus]]\n* [[Corona virus or CoVID-19]]\n\n==Scenarios==\n\nThere are multiple considerable scenarios, how terrorists might employ biological agents.<ref name=\"croodybook\"/> In 2000, tests conducted by various US agencies showed that indoor attacks in densely populated spaces are much more serious than outdoor attacks. Such enclosed spaces are large buildings, trains, indoor arenas, theaters, malls, tunnels and similar. Contra-measures against such scenarios are building architecture and ventilation systems engineering. In 1993, sewage was spilled out into a river, subsequently drawn into the water system and affected [[1993_Milwaukee_Cryptosporidiosis_outbreak|400,000 people in Milwaukee]], Wisconsin.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Petersen |first1=Carolyn |title=Cryptosporidium and the food supply |journal=The Lancet |date=May 1995 |volume=345 |issue=8958 |pages=1128\u20131129 |doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(95)90972-9|pmid=7723540 }}</ref> The disease-causing organism was [[cryptosporidium parvum]]. This man-made disaster can be a template for a terrorist scenario.<ref name=\"croodybook\"/> Nevertheless, terrorist scenarios are considered more likely near the points of delivery than at the water sources before the [[water treatment]].<ref name=croodybook/> Release of biological agents is more likely for a single building or a neighborhood. Contra-measures against this scenario is the further limitation of access to the water supply systems, tunnels, and infrastructure. Agricultural [[crop-duster]] flights might be misused as delivery devices for biological agents as well.<ref name=croodybook/> Contra-measures against this scenario are background checks of employees of crop-dusting companies and surveillance procedures. \n\nIn the most common hoax scenario, no biological agents are employed.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lathrop |first1=Peggy |last2=Mann |first2=Linda M. |title=Preparing for bioterrorism |journal=Proceedings (Baylor University. Medical Center) |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=219\u2013223 |date=2001|pmc=1305820 |pmid=16369620 |doi=10.1080/08998280.2001.11927766 }}</ref> For instance, an envelope with powder in it that says, \u201cYou've just been exposed to anthrax.\u201d Such hoaxes already showed to produce a large [[psychological warfare|psychological impact on the population]].<ref name=wheelis>{{cite journal |last1=Wheelis |first1=Mark |last2=Casagrande |first2=Rocco |last3=Madden |first3=Laurence V. |title=Biological Attack on Agriculture: Low-Tech, High-Impact BioterrorismBecause bioterrorist attack requires relatively little specialized expertise and technology, it is a serious threat to US agriculture and can have very large economic repercussions |journal=BioScience |date=1 July 2002 |volume=52 |issue=7 |pages=569\u2013576 |doi=10.1641/0006-3568(2002)052[0569:BAOALT]2.0.CO;2 |url=https://academic.oup.com/bioscience/article/52/7/569/247956#126036035 |language=en |issn=0006-3568|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nAnti-agriculture attacks are considered to require relatively little expertise and technology.<ref name=wheelis/> Biological agents against livestock, fish, vegetation, and crops are mostly not contagious to humans and therefore easier to handle by the attackers. Even a few cases of infections can disrupt a country's agricultural production and export for months like in the case with [[Foot-and-mouth_disease|FMD]].\n\n==Planning and response==\n{{main|Biodefense}}\n{{Globalize|section|USA|2name=the United States|date=June 2012}}\nPlanning may involve the development of biological identification systems. Until recently in the United States, most biological defense strategies have been geared to protecting soldiers on the battlefield rather than ordinary people in cities. Financial cutbacks have limited the tracking of disease outbreaks. Some outbreaks, such as food poisoning due to ''[[Escherichia coli|E. coli]]'' or ''[[Salmonella]]'', could be of either natural or deliberate origin.\n\n=== Preparedness ===\nExport controls on biological agents are not applied uniformly providing terrorists a route for acquisition.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kuntz|first=Carol|url=https://books.google.com/?id=7bisH_7fo00C&pg=PR3&dq=A+Biological+Threat+Prevention+Strategy+:+Complicating+Adversary+Acquisition+and+Misuse+of+Biological+Agents#v=onepage|title=A Biological Threat Prevention Strategy: Complicating Adversary Acquisition and Misuse of Biological Agents|last2=Salerno|first2=Reynolds|last3=Jacobs|first3=Eli|date=2013-05-15|publisher=Center for Strategic & International Studies|isbn=978-1-4422-2474-2|language=en}}</ref> Laboratories are working on advanced detection systems to provide early warning, identify [[contamination|contaminated areas]] and populations at risk, and to facilitate prompt treatment.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nikolelis|first=Dimitrios P.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=k-m9CwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&q=terrorism|title=Biosensors for Security and Bioterrorism Applications|last2=Nikoleli|first2=Georgia-Paraskevi|date=2016-03-12|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-319-28926-7|language=en}}</ref> Methods for predicting the use of biological agents in urban areas as well as assessing the area for the hazards associated with a biological attack are being established in major cities. In addition, [[forensic]] technologies are working on identifying biological agents, their geographical origins and/or their initial source. Efforts include decontamination technologies to restore facilities without causing additional environmental concerns.\n\nEarly detection and rapid response to bioterrorism depend on close cooperation between [[public health]] authorities and law enforcement; however, such cooperation is lacking. National detection assets and vaccine stockpiles are not useful if local and state officials do not have access to them.<ref>{{citation|last=Bernett|first=Brian C.|title=US Biodefense and Homeland Security: Toward Detection and Attribution|url=http://www.ccc.nps.navy.mil/research/theses/bernett06.pdf|accessdate=2009-05-24|date=December 2006|publisher=Naval Postgraduate School|location=Monterey, California, United States|page=21|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080229164557/http://www.ccc.nps.navy.mil/research/theses/bernett06.pdf|archivedate=2008-02-29}}</ref>\n\nAspects of protection against bioterrorism in the United States include:\n*Detection and resilience strategies in combating bioterrorism. This occurs primarily through the efforts of the [[DHS Office of Health Affairs|Office of Health Affairs]] (OHA), a part of the [[Department of Homeland Security]] (DHS), whose role is to prepare for an emergency situation that impacts the health of the American populace. Detection has two primary technological factors. First there is OHA's BioWatch program in which collection devices are disseminated to thirty high risk areas throughout the country to detect the presence of aerosolized biological agents before symptoms present in patients.<ref name=\"PrepX\">United States. Cong. House. Committee on Homeland Security. Ensuring Effective Preparedness Responses and Recovery for Events Impacting Health Security Hearing before the Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response and Communications of the Committee on Homeland Security, House of Representatives, One Hundred Twelfth Congress, First Session, March 17, 2011. 112th Cong., 1st sess. HR 397. Washington: U.S. G.P.O., 2012. Print.</ref> This is significant primarily because it allows a more proactive response to a disease outbreak rather than the more passive treatment of the past.\n*Implementation of the Generation-3 automated detection system. This advancement is significant simply because it enables action to be taken in four to six hours due to its automatic response system, whereas the previous system required aerosol detectors to be manually transported to laboratories.<ref name=\"PrepX\"/> Resilience is a multifaceted issue as well, as addressed by OHA. One way in which this is ensured is through exercises that establish preparedness; programs like the Anthrax Response Exercise Series exist to ensure that, regardless of the incident, all emergency personnel will be aware of the role they must fill.<ref name=\"PrepX\"/> Moreover, by providing information and education to public leaders, emergency medical services and all employees of the DHS, OHS suggests it can significantly decrease the impact of bioterrorism.<ref name=\"PrepX\"/>\n*Enhancing the technological capabilities of first responders is accomplished through numerous strategies. The first of these strategies was developed by the Science and Technology Directorate (S&T) of DHS to ensure that the danger of suspicious powders could be effectively assessed, (as many dangerous biological agents such as anthrax exist as a white powder). By testing the accuracy and specificity of commercially available systems used by first responders, the hope is that all biologically harmful powders can be rendered ineffective.<ref name=\"PrepY\">United States. Cong. House. Committee on Homeland Security. First Responder Technologies: Ensuring a Prioritized Approach for Homeland Security Research and Development : Joint Hearing before the Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response and Communications and the Subcommittee on Cybersecurity, Infrastructure Protection, and Security Technologies of the Committee on Homeland Security, House of Representatives, One Hundred Twelfth Congress, Second Session, May 9, 2012. 112th Cong., 2nd sess. HR 397. N.p.: n.p., n.d. Print.</ref>\n*Enhanced equipment for first responders. One recent advancement is the commercialization of a new form of Tyvex\u2122 armor which protects first responders and patients from chemical and biological contaminants. There has also been a new generation of Self-Contained Breathing Apparatuses (SCBA) which has been recently made more robust against bioterrorism agents. All of these technologies combine to form what seems like a relatively strong deterrent to bioterrorism. However, New York City as an entity has numerous organizations and strategies that effectively serve to deter and respond to bioterrorism as it comes. From here the logical progression is into the realm of New York City's specific strategies to prevent bioterrorism.<ref name=\"PrepY\"/>\n*Excelsior Challenge. In the second week of September 2016, the state of New York held a large emergency response training exercise called the Excelsior Challenge, with over 100 emergency responders participating. According to [[WKTV]], \"This is the fourth year of the Excelsior Challenge, a training exercise designed for police and first responders to become familiar with techniques and practices should a real incident occur.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wktv.com/news/A_new_challenge_for_police_and_EMS_personnel.html|title=WKTV.com {{!}} A new Challenge for police and EMS personnel|date=2016-09-15|access-date=2016-10-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005104757/http://www.wktv.com/news/A_new_challenge_for_police_and_EMS_personnel.html#|archive-date=2016-10-05|url-status=dead}}</ref> The event was held over three days and hosted by the State Preparedness Training Center in [[Oriskany, New York|Oriskany]], New York. Participants included [[Bomb disposal|bomb squad]]<nowiki/>s, canine handlers, tactical team officers and emergency medical services.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://homelandprepnews.com/countermeasures/19747-first-responders-train-new-technology-n-y-s-largest-emergency-response-exercise/|title=First responders train with new technology at N.Y.'s largest emergency response exercise - Homeland Preparedness News|date=2016-09-19|language=en-US|access-date=2016-10-03}}</ref> In an interview with ''Homeland Preparedness News'', Bob Stallman, assistant director at the New York State Preparedness Training Center, said, \"We're constantly seeing what\u2019s happening around the world and we tailor our training courses and events for those types of real-world events.\" For the first time, the 2016 training program implemented New York's new electronic system. The system, called NY Responds, electronically connects every county in New York to aid in disaster response and recovery. As a result, \"counties have access to a new technology known as Mutualink, which improves [[interoperability]] by integrating telephone, radio, video, and file-sharing into one application to allow local emergency staff to share real-time information with the state and other counties.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> The State Preparedness Training Center in Oriskany was designed by the State Division of Homeland Security, and Emergency Services (DHSES) in 2006. It cost $42 million to construct on over 1100 acres and is available for training 360 days a year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newyorkupstate.com/news/2016/09/ny_police_train_for_terrorist_attacks_bombs_active_shooters_videos.html|title=Watch NY police train for terrorist attacks, bombs, active shooters (videos)|access-date=2016-10-03|date=2016-09-15}}</ref> Students from SUNY Albany's College of Emergency Preparedness, Homeland Security and Cybersecurity, were able to participate in this year's exercise and learn how \"DHSES supports law enforcement specialty teams.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n* Project BioShield. The accrual of vaccines and treatments for potential biological threats, also known as medical countermeasures has been an important aspect in preparing for a potential bioterrorist attack; this took the form of a program beginning in 2004, referred to as [[Project Bioshield Act|Project BioShield]].<ref name=\"Hylton\">[[Wil S. Hylton|Hylton, Wil S.]] \"How Ready Are We for Bioterrorism?\" The New York Times. The New York Times Company, 26 Oct. 2011. Web.</ref> The significance of this program should not be overlooked as \u201cthere is currently enough smallpox vaccine to inoculate every United States citizen\u2026 and a variety of therapeutic drugs to treat the infected.\u201d<ref name=\"Hylton\"/> The Department of Defense also has a variety of laboratories currently working to increase the quantity and efficacy of countermeasures that comprise the national stockpile.<ref name=\"PrepXYZ\"/> Efforts have also been taken to ensure that these medical countermeasures can be disseminated effectively in the event of a bioterrorist attack. The National Association of Chain Drug Stores championed this cause by encouraging the participation of the private sector in improving the distribution of such countermeasures if required.<ref name=\"PrepXYZ\">United States. Cong. House. Committee on Homeland Security. Taking Measure of Countermeasures. Hearing before the Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response and Communications of the Committee on Homeland Security, House of Representatives, One Hundred Twelfth Congress, First Session, April 13, 2011 and May 12, 2011. 112 Cong., 1st sess. HR 397. Washington: U.S. G.P.O., 2012. Print.</ref>\n\nOn a CNN news broadcast in 2011, the CNN chief medical correspondent, Dr. Sanjay Gupta, weighed in on the American government's recent approach to bioterrorist threats. He explains how, even though the United States would be better fending off bioterrorist attacks now than they would be a decade ago, the amount of money available to fight bioterrorism over the last three years has begun to decrease. Looking at a detailed report that examined the funding decrease for bioterrorism in fifty-one American cities, Dr. Gupta stated that the cities \"wouldn\u2019t be able to distribute vaccines as well\" and \"wouldn't be able to track viruses.\" He also said that film portrayals of global pandemics, such as ''[[Contagion (2011 film)|Contagion]]'', were actually quite possible and may occur in the United States under the right conditions.<ref>John King, USA. CNNW. San Francisco. 20 Dec. 2011. Television.</ref>\n\nA news broadcast by [[MSNBC]] in 2010 also stressed the low levels of bioterrorism preparedness in the United States.  The broadcast stated that a bipartisan report gave the Obama administration a failing grade for its efforts to respond to a bioterrorist attack. The news broadcast invited the former New York City police commissioner, Howard Safir, to explain how the government would fare in combating such an attack. He said how \"biological and chemical weapons are probable and relatively easy to disperse.\" Furthermore, Safir thought that efficiency in bioterrorism preparedness is not necessarily a question of money, but is instead dependent on putting resources in the right places. The broadcast suggested that the nation was not ready for something more serious.<ref>MSNBC News Live. MSNBC. New York City. 26 Jan. 2010. Television</ref>\n\nIn a September 2016 interview conducted by Homeland Preparedness News, Daniel Gerstein, a senior policy researcher for the RAND Corporation, stresses the importance in preparing for potential bioterrorist attacks on the nation. He implored the U.S. government to take the proper and necessary actions to implement a strategic plan of action to save as many lives as possible and to safeguard against potential chaos and confusion. He believes that because there have been no significant instances of bioterrorism since the anthrax attacks in 2001, the government has allowed itself to become complacent making the country that much more vulnerable to unsuspecting attacks, thereby further endangering the lives of U.S. citizens.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://homelandprepnews.com/biological-threats/19645-rands-gerstein-u-s-needs-biodefense-strategy-protect-terror-threats/|title=RAND's Gerstein: U.S. needs biodefense strategy to protect against terror threats|last=Rozens|first=Tracy|date=2016-09-02|website=Homeland Preparedness News|publisher=|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-19}}</ref>\n\nGerstein formerly served in the Science and Technology Directorate of the Department of Homeland Security from 2011 to 2014. He claims there has not been a serious plan of action since 2004 during George W. Bush's presidency, in which he issued a Homeland Security directive delegating responsibilities among various federal agencies. He also stated that the blatant mishandling of the Ebola virus outbreak in 2014 attested to the government's lack of preparation. This past May, legislation that would create a national defense strategy was introduced in the Senate, coinciding with the timing of ISIS-affiliated terrorist groups get closer to weaponizing biological agents. In May, 2016, Kenyan officials apprehended two members of an Islamic extremist group in motion to set off a biological bomb containing anthrax. Mohammed Abdi Ali, the believed leader of the group, who was a medical intern, was arrested along with his wife, a medical student. The two were caught just before carrying out their plan.<ref>https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/05/04/foiled-kenya-anthrax-plot-hints-at-islamic-states-scramble-for-africa/</ref> The Blue Ribbon Study Panel on Biodefense, which comprises a group of experts on national security and government officials, in which Gerstein had previously testified to, submitted its National Blueprint for Biodefense to Congress in October 2015 listing their recommendations for devising an effective plan.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBill Gates said in a February 18, 2017 ''Business Insider'' op-ed (published near the time of his Munich Security Conference speech) that it is possible for an airborne pathogen to kill at least 30 million people over the course of a year.<ref>https://www.businessinsider.com/bill-gates-op-ed-bio-terrorism-epidemic-world-threat-2017-2</ref> In a ''New York Times'' report, the [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation|Gates Foundation]] predicted that a modern outbreak similar to the [[1918 flu pandemic|Spanish Influenza pandemic]] (which killed between 50 million and 100 million people) could end up killing more than 360 million people worldwide, even considering widespread availability of vaccines and other healthcare tools. The report cited increased [[globalization]], rapid international air travel, and [[urbanization]] as increased reasons for concern.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hstoday.us/industry-news/general/single-article/exclusive-pandemic-crossroads/17c710beb467f48ccf7609188a8feb7a.html|title=Homeland Security Today: EXCLUSIVE: Pandemic Crossroads|last=Hutchinson|first=Robert C.|date=2017-07-09|website=www.hstoday.us|language=en|access-date=2017-09-12}}{{dead link|date=September 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> In a March 9, 2017 interview with CNBC, former U.S. Senator [[Joe Lieberman]], who was co-chair of the bipartisan [[Blue Ribbon Study Panel on Biodefense]], said a worldwide pandemic could end the lives of more people than a nuclear war. Lieberman also expressed worry that a terrorist group like ISIS could develop a synthetic influenza strain and introduce it to the world to kill civilians.<ref name=\":3\" /> In July 2017, Robert C. Hutchinson, former agent at the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]], called for a \"whole-of-government\" response to the next global health threat, which he described as including strict security procedures at our borders and proper execution of government preparedness plans.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAlso, novel approaches in biotechnology, such as synthetic biology, could be used in the future to design new types of biological warfare agents.<ref>Kelle A (2009) Security issues related to synthetic biology. Chapter 7. In: Schmidt M, Kelle A, Ganguli-Mitra A, de Vriend H (eds) Synthetic biology. The technoscience and its societal conse- quences. Springer, Berlin</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = JCVI: Research / Projects / Synthetic Genomics {{!}} Options for Governance / Overview|url = http://www.jcvi.org/cms/research/projects/syngen-options/overview/|website = www.jcvi.org|access-date = 2016-01-24|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160130071934/http://www.jcvi.org/cms/research/projects/syngen-options/overview/#|archive-date = 2016-01-30|url-status = dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Office of Biotechnology Activities {{!}} Office of Science Policy|url = http://osp.od.nih.gov/office-biotechnology-activities/biosecurity/pdf/NSABB%2520SynBio%2520-DRAFT%2520Report-FINAL%2520(2)_6-7-10.pdf|website = osp.od.nih.gov|access-date = 2016-01-24|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160201073836/http://osp.od.nih.gov/office-biotechnology-activities/biosecurity/pdf/NSABB%2520SynBio%2520-DRAFT%2520Report-FINAL%2520(2)_6-7-10.pdf#|archive-date = 2016-02-01|url-status = dead}}</ref><ref>M.Buller, The potential use of genetic engineering to enhance orthopox viruses as bioweapons. Presentation at the International Conference \u2018Smallpox Biosecurity. Preventing the Unthinkable\u2019 (21\u201322 October 2003) Geneva, Switzerland</ref> Special attention has to be laid on future experiments (of concern) that:<ref>Kelle A. 2007. Synthetic Biology & Biosecurity Awareness In Europe. Bradford Science and Technology Report No.9</ref>\n# Would demonstrate how to render a vaccine ineffective;\n# Would confer resistance to therapeutically useful antibiotics or antiviral agents;\n# Would enhance the virulence of a pathogen or render a nonpathogen virulent;\n# Would increase transmissibility of a pathogen;\n# Would alter the host range of a pathogen;\n# Would enable the evasion of diagnostic/detection tools;\n# Would enable the weaponization of a biological agent or toxin\nMost of the biosecurity concerns in synthetic biology, however, are focused on the role of DNA synthesis and the risk of producing genetic material of lethal viruses (e.g. 1918 Spanish flu, polio) in the lab.<ref>Tumpej TM et al. 2005. Characterization of the Reconstructed 1918 Spanish Influenza Pandemic Virus. Science Vol. 310(5745):77\u201380</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Cello | first1 = J. | last2 = Paul | first2 = A. V. | last3 = Wimmer | first3 = E. | year = 2002 | title = Chemical synthesis of poliovirus cDNA: generation of infectious virus in the absence of natural template | url = | journal = Science | volume = 297 | issue = 5583| pages = 1016\u20131018 | doi=10.1126/science.1072266 | pmid=12114528| bibcode = 2002Sci...297.1016C }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Synthetic viruses: a new opportunity to understand and prevent viral disease|journal = Nature Biotechnology|date = 2009-12-01|issn = 1087-0156|pmc = 2819212|pmid = 20010599|pages = 1163\u201372|volume = 27|issue = 12|doi = 10.1038/nbt.1593|first = Eckard|last = Wimmer|first2 = Steffen|last2 = Mueller|first3 = Terrence M|last3 = Tumpey|first4 = Jeffery K|last4 = Taubenberger}}</ref> The CRISPR/Cas system has emerged as a promising technique for gene editing. It was hailed by The Washington Post as \"the most important innovation in the synthetic biology space in nearly 30 years.\"<ref name=\"WangerMRoleOfClinicalInformationSystems\" /> While other methods take months or years to edit gene sequences, CRISPR speeds that time up to weeks.<ref name=\"WangerMRoleOfClinicalInformationSystems\" /> However, due to its ease of use and accessibility, it has raised a number of ethical concerns, especially surrounding its use in the biohacking space.<ref>{{Cite news|title = The Crispr Quandary|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/15/magazine/the-crispr-quandary.html|newspaper = The New York Times|date = 2015-11-09|access-date = 2016-01-24|issn = 0362-4331|first = Jennifer|last = Kahn}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = CRISPR, the disruptor|url = http://www.nature.com/news/crispr-the-disruptor-1.17673|website = Nature News & Comment|access-date = 2016-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title = Everything you need to know about why CRISPR is such a hot technology|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/innovations/wp/2015/11/04/everything-you-need-to-know-about-why-crispr-is-such-a-hot-technology/|newspaper = The Washington Post|date = 2015-11-04|access-date = 2016-01-24|issn = 0190-8286|language = en-US|first = Dominic|last = Basulto}}</ref>\n\n===Biosurveillance===\nIn 1999, the [[University of Pittsburgh]]'s Center for [[Biomedical]] Informatics deployed the first automated bioterrorism detection system, called [[Real-Time Outbreak Disease Surveillance|RODS (Real-Time Outbreak Disease Surveillance)]]. RODS is designed to collect data from many data sources and use them to perform signal detection, that is, to detect a possible bioterrorism event at the earliest possible moment. RODS, and other systems like it, collect data from sources including clinic data, laboratory data, and data from over-the-counter drug sales.<ref name=\"WangerMRoleOfClinicalInformationSystems\">{{citation|last=Wagner|first=Michael M.|author2=Espino, Jeremy|title=Healthcare Information Management Systems|chapter-url=|edition=3|year=2004|publisher=Springer-Verlag|location=New York|pages=513\u2013539|chapter=The role of clinical information systems in public health surveillance|display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref name=\"WangerMAvailabilityAndComparativeValueOfData\">{{citation|last=Wagner|first=Michael M.|author2=Aryel, Ron|title=Availability and Comparative Value of Data Elements Required for an Effective Bioterrorism Detection System|url=http://rods.health.pitt.edu/LIBRARY/dato2AHRQInterimRpt112801.pdf|accessdate=2009-05-22|date=2001-11-28|publisher=Real-time Outbreak and Disease Surveillance Laboratory|display-authors=etal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110303223152/http://rods.health.pitt.edu/LIBRARY/dato2AHRQInterimRpt112801.pdf|archivedate=2011-03-03}}</ref> In 2000, Michael Wagner, the codirector of the RODS laboratory, and [[Ron Aryel]], a subcontractor, conceived the idea of obtaining live data feeds from \"non-traditional\" (non-health-care) data sources. The RODS laboratory's first efforts eventually led to the establishment of the National Retail Data Monitor, a system which collects data from 20,000 retail locations nationwide.<ref name=\"WangerMRoleOfClinicalInformationSystems\" />\n\nOn February 5, 2002, [[George W. Bush]] visited the RODS laboratory and used it as a model for a [[USD|$]]300 million spending proposal to equip all 50 states with biosurveillance systems. In a speech delivered at the nearby [[Masonic temple]], Bush compared the RODS system to a modern \"[[DEW]]\" line (referring to the Cold War ballistic missile early warning system).<ref>{{citation|last=Togyer|first=Jason|title=Pitt Magazine: Airborne Defense|url=http://www.pittmag.pitt.edu/june2002/feature1.html|accessdate=2009-05-22|date=June 2002|publisher=University of Pittsburgh|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616101219/http://www.pittmag.pitt.edu/june2002/feature1.html|archive-date=2010-06-16|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe principles and practices of biosurveillance, a new interdisciplinary science, were defined and described in the ''Handbook of Biosurveillance'', edited by Michael Wagner, Andrew Moore and Ron Aryel, and published in 2006. Biosurveillance is the science of real-time disease outbreak detection. Its principles apply to both natural and man-made epidemics (bioterrorism).\n\nData which potentially could assist in early detection of a bioterrorism event include many categories of information. Health-related data such as that from hospital computer systems, clinical laboratories, [[electronic health record]] systems, medical examiner record-keeping systems, 911 call center computers, and veterinary medical record systems could be of help; researchers are also considering the utility of data generated by [[ranching]] and [[feedlot]] operations, food processors, [[drinking water]] systems, school attendance recording, and physiologic monitors, among others.<ref name=\"WangerMAvailabilityAndComparativeValueOfData\" />\n\nIn [[Europe]], disease surveillance is beginning to be organized on the continent-wide scale needed to track a biological emergency. The system not only monitors infected persons, but attempts to discern the origin of the outbreak.\n\nResearchers have experimented with devices to detect the existence of a threat:\n\n* Tiny [[integrated circuit|electronic chips]] that would contain living [[neuron|nerve cells]] to warn of the presence of bacterial toxins (identification of broad range toxins)\n* [[Fiber-optic]] tubes lined with [[antibody|antibodies]] coupled to light-emitting molecules (identification of specific pathogens, such as anthrax, botulinum, ricin)\n\nSome research shows that ultraviolet [[avalanche photodiodes]] offer the high gain, reliability and robustness needed to detect anthrax and other bioterrorism agents in the air. The fabrication methods and device characteristics were described at the 50th Electronic Materials Conference in Santa Barbara on June 25, 2008. Details of the photodiodes were also published in the February 14, 2008 issue of the journal Electronics Letters and the November 2007 issue of the journal IEEE Photonics Technology Letters.<ref>[http://newswise.com/articles/view/541788/ Avalanche Photodiodes Target Bioterrorism Agents] Newswise, Retrieved on June 25, 2008.</ref>\n\nThe United States Department of Defense conducts global biosurveillance through several programs, including the Global Emerging Infections Surveillance and Response System.<ref>Pellerin, Cheryl. [http://www.defense.gov/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=65852 \"Global Nature of Terrorism Drives Biosurveillance.\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112191814/http://www.defense.gov/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=65852 |date=January 12, 2013 }} ''American Forces Press Service'', 27 October 2011.</ref>\n\nAnother powerful tool developed within New York City for use in countering bioterrorism is the development of the New York City [[Syndromic Surveillance]] System. This system is essentially a way of tracking disease progression throughout New York City, and was developed by the [[New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene]] (NYC DOHMH) in the wake of the 9/11 attacks. The system works by tracking the symptoms of those taken into the emergency department\u2014based on the location of the hospital to which they are taken and their home address\u2014and assessing any patterns in symptoms. These established trends can then be observed by medical epidemiologists to determine if there are any disease outbreaks in any particular locales; maps of disease prevalence can then be created rather easily.<ref>Chen, H, D Zeng, and Y Pan. \"Infectious Disease Informatics: Syndromic Surveillance for Public Health and Bio-Defense.\" 20120, XXII, 209p. 68 illus.., Hardcover.</ref> This is an obviously beneficial tool in fighting bioterrorism as it provides a means through which such attacks could be discovered in their nascence; assuming bioterrorist attacks result in similar symptoms across the board, this strategy allows New York City to respond immediately to any bioterrorist threats that they may face with some level of alacrity.\n\n==Response to bioterrorism incident or threat==\n{{Globalize|section|USA|2name=the United States|date=June 2012}}\nGovernment agencies which would be called on to respond to a bioterrorism incident would include law enforcement, hazardous materials and decontamination units, and emergency medical units, if available.\n\nThe US military has specialized units, which can respond to a bioterrorism event; among them are the [[United States Marine Corps]]' [[Chemical Biological Incident Response Force]] and the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]]'s [[20th Support Command (CBRNE)]], which can detect, identify, and neutralize threats, and [[decontamination|decontaminate]] victims exposed to bioterror agents. US response would include the [[Center for Disease Control]].\n\nHistorically, governments and authorities have relied on quarantines to protect their populations. International bodies such as the [[World Health Organization]] already devote some of their resources to monitoring epidemics and have served clearing-house roles in historical epidemics.\n\nMedia attention toward the seriousness of biological attacks increased in 2013 to 2014. In July 2013, ''Forbes'' published an article with the title \"Bioterrorism: A Dirty Little Threat With Huge Potential Consequences.\"<ref>Bell, Larry. [https://www.forbes.com/sites/larrybell/2013/07/21/bioterrorism-a-dirty-little-threat-with-huge-potential-consequences/ \"Bioterrorism: A Dirty Little Threat With Huge Potential Consequences\"]. ''Forbes''. 2013-07-21 (Retrieved 2014-02-17)</ref> In November 2013, Fox News reported on a new strain of botulism, saying that the Centers for Disease and Control lists botulism as one of two agents that have \"the highest risks of mortality and morbidity\", noting that there is no antidote for botulism.<ref>Heitz, David. [http://www.foxnews.com/health/2013/11/02/deadly-bioterror-threats-6-real-risks/ \"Deadly bioterror threats: 6 real risks\"]. Fox News. 2013-11-02 (Retrieved 2014-02-17)</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'' reported that the U.S. military in November was trying to develop a vaccine for troops from the bacteria that cause the disease Q fever, an agent the military once used as a biological weapon.<ref>Locker, Ray. [https://www.usatoday.com/story/nation/2013/11/15/q-fever-vaccine-search-continues/3527345/ \"Pentagon seeking vaccine for bioterror disease threat\"]. ''USA Today''. 2013-11-18 (Retrieved 2014-02-17)</ref> In February 2014, the former special assistant and senior director for biodefense policy to President George W. Bush called the bioterrorism risk imminent and uncertain<ref>Cohen, Bryan. [http://bioprepwatch.com/biological-threats/kadlec-says-biological-attack-is-uncertain-imminent-reality/335981/ \"Kadlec says biological attack is uncertain, imminent reality\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209212132/http://bioprepwatch.com/biological-threats/kadlec-says-biological-attack-is-uncertain-imminent-reality/335981/ |date=2015-02-09 }}. Bio Prep Watch. 2014-02-17 (Retrieved 2014-02-17)</ref> and Congressman [[Bill Pascrell]] called for increasing federal measures against bioterrorism as a \"matter of life or death.\"<ref>Cohen, Bryan. [https://archive.is/20140217165044/http://bioprepwatch.com/bioterrorism/pascrell-says-bioterror-threat-a-life-or-death-matter/335939/ \"Pascrell: Bioterror threat a life or death matter\"]. Bio Prep Watch. 2014-02-12 (Retrieved 2014-02-17)</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote a story saying the United States would spend $40 million to help certain low and middle-income countries deal with the threats of bioterrorism and infectious diseases.<ref>Tavernise, Sabrina. [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/14/health/us-backs-new-global-initiative-against-infectious-diseases.html?hpw&rref=health&_r=0 \"U.S. Backs New Global Initiative Against Infectious Diseases\"]. ''New York Times''. 2014-02-13 (Retrieved 2014-02-17)</ref>\n\n[[Bill Gates]] has warned that bioterrorism could kill more people than nuclear war.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bioterrorism could kill more people than nuclear war, Bill Gates to warn world leaders|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/02/17/biological-terrorism-could-kill-people-nuclear-attacks-bill/|accessdate=19 February 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=18 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, a [[CNN]] employee discovered on an airplane a \"sensitive, top-secret document in the seatback pouch explaining how the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] would respond to a bioterrorism attack at the [[Super Bowl]].\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900009991/jays-jokes-did-you-forget-your-bioterrorism-report-on-the-plane.html|title=Jay's Jokes: Did you forget your bioterrorism report on the plane?|last=Evensen|first=Jay|date=2018-02-12|work=DeseretNews.com|access-date=2018-02-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== 2017 U.S. budget proposal affecting bioterrorism programs ===\nPresident Donald Trump promoted his first budget around keeping America safe. However, one aspect of defense would receive less money: \"protecting the nation from deadly pathogens, man-made or natural,\" according to ''The New York Times''. Agencies tasked with biosecurity get a decrease in funding under the Administration's budget proposal.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/28/us/politics/biosecurity-trump-budget-defense.html|title=Trump's Proposed Budget Cuts Trouble Bioterrorism Experts|last=Baumgaertner|first=Emily|date=2017-05-28|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-05-30|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nFor example:<ref name=\":2\" />\n* The Office of Public Health Preparedness and Response would be cut by $136 million, or 9.7 percent. The office tracks outbreaks of disease.\n* The National Center for Emerging and Zoonotic Infectious Diseases would be cut by $65 million, or 11 percent. The center is a branch of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention that fights threats like anthrax and the [[Ebola virus]], and additionally towards research on HIV/AIDS vaccines.\n* Within the [[National Institutes of Health]], the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]] (NIAID) would lose 18 percent of its budget. NIAID oversees responses to Zika, Ebola and [[HIV/AIDS]] vaccine research.\n\"The next [[weapon of mass destruction]] may not be a bomb,\" Lawrence O. Gostin, the director of the World Health Organization's Collaborating Center on Public Health Law and Human Rights, told ''The New York Times''. \"It may be a tiny pathogen that you can't see, smell or taste, and by the time we discover it, it'll be too late.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Lack of international standards on public health experiments ===\nTom Inglesy, the CEO and director of the Center for Health Security at the [[Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health]] and an internationally recognized expert on public health preparedness, pandemic and emerging infectious disease said in 2017 that the lack of an internationally standardized approval process that could be used to guide countries in conducting public health experiments for resurrecting a disease that has already been eradicated increases the risk that the disease could be used in bioterrorism. This was in reference to the lab synthesis of [[Orthopoxvirus|horsepox]] in 2017 by researchers at the [[University of Alberta]]. The researchers recreated horsepox, an extinct cousin of the [[Smallpox|smallpox virus]], in order to research new ways to treat cancer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://homelandprepnews.com/featured/23673-bioterrorism-threats-require-common-global-experimentation-oversight-expert-says/|title=Bioterrorism threats require common global experimentation oversight, expert says|last=Riley|first=Kim|date=2017-08-10|work=Homeland Preparedness News|access-date=2018-01-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{main|Biological warfare in popular culture}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{citation|last=Block|first=Steven M.|title=The growing threat of biological weapons|url=http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/feature/the-growing-threat-of-biological-weapons|accessdate=2009-05-22|volume=89 | issue=1|year=2001|doi=10.1511/2001.1.28|journal=American Scientist|page=28|bibcode=2001AmSci..89.....B}}\n* {{citation|last=Christopher|first=G. W.|title=Adapted from Biological Warfare: A Historical Perspective|url=|year=1998|publisher=Operational Medicine Division|location=Fort Detrick, Maryland|display-authors=etal}}\n* {{citation|last1=Eitzen|first1=E.|last2=Takafuji|first2=E.|title=Military Medicine: Medical Aspects of Chemical and Biological Warfare|chapter-url=|year=1997|publisher=Office of the Surgeon General, Department of the Army|chapter=Historical Overview of Biological Warfare}}\n* {{citation|title=Iraq's Biological Weapon Program|url=http://www.iraqwatch.org/profiles/biological.html|accessdate=2009-05-22|date=August 2006|publisher=Iraq's Biological Weapon Program|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090411043128/http://www.iraqwatch.org/profiles/biological.html|archivedate=2009-04-11}}\n* {{citation|last=Milanovich|first=F.|title=Reducing the threat of biological weapons|url=http://www.llnl.gov/str/Milan.html|accessdate=2009-05-22|date=June 1998|publisher=Science and Technology Review|pages=4\u20139|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081123160358/https://www.llnl.gov/str/Milan.html|archive-date=2008-11-23|url-status=dead}}\n* {{citation|last=Paquette|first=Laure|title=Bioterrorism in Medical and Healthcare Administration|url=https://books.google.com/?id=fLUIfjbpjUIC&pg=PP1&dq=Bioterrorism+in+Medical+and+Healthcare+Administration|accessdate=2009-05-22|edition=1|date=2006-06-29|publisher=CRC|isbn=978-0-8247-5651-2}}\n* {{citation|last=Wagner|first=M.|author2=Moore, A. |author3=Aryel, R.|title=Handbook of Biosurveillance|url=|year=2006|publisher=Academic Press|location=San Diego, California, United States}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource|The Town That Was Poisoned}}\n{{Library resources box |by=no |onlinebooks=no |others=yes lcheading=Bioterrorism}}\n{{Refbegin}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110616062822/http://student.cs.ucc.ie/cs1064/jabowen/IPSC/articles/carusBiocrimes.pdf Bioterrorism and Biocrimes.The Illicit Use of Biological Agents Since 1900, by W. Seth Carus]\n* [https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:4klaEuJMfO8J:www.adl.org/learn/anthrax/beyond_anthrax.pdf+Stephen+Pera+%22Allen+Schwander+%22&hl=en&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESj7z1og116Xu462BdEPflh91VyPKxWR5pM56grte13Y7Rb1FsT13GstGge3I_6P7MmFQSW1HvyutwVtf1yTIKUEcN06_WI-0v_aSGzD7W8-y9N0ZjkUNZW1sy3fZfppzSZyt9QV&sig=AHIEtbQQNYSJL_dcDHdQvR_emtek0drKAg Beyond Anthrax.Extremism and the Bioterrorism Threat]\n* [http://www.eht-forum.org/ Emerging Health Threats Forum]\n* [http://health.europa.eu/my_environment/bio_terrorism/index_en.htm EU Health Portal]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Information on EU activities related to bioterrorism\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061129022411/http://www.bt.cdc.gov/bioterrorism/ United States Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/bioterror/ NOVA: Bioterror]\n* [http://web.mit.edu/professional/short-programs/courses/combating_bioterrorism.html Pandemics and Bioterrorism: From Realistic Threats to Effective Policies]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141021001529/http://www.newslobby.net/2014/10/14/bioterrorism-could-ebola-be-a-possible-new-biological-weapon/ Bioterrorism: Could Ebola be a Possible New Biological Weapon?]\n* [https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/sites/default/files/microsites/ostp/p3co-finalguidancestatement.pdf Recommended Policy Guidance for Departmental Development of Review Mechanisms for Potential Pandemic Pathogen Care and Oversight (P3CO)]. Obama Administration. January 9, 2017. \n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Bioterrorism}}\n{{U.S. biological defense}}\n\n[[Category:Biological warfare]]\n[[Category:Bioterrorism| ]]\n[[Category:Terrorism by method]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:NBC-Mask M-17.jpg|thumb|United States [[Airman]] wearing an [[M17 gas mask|M-17]] nuclear, biological, and chemical warfare mask and hood]]\n{{terrorism}}\n\n'''Bioterrorism''' is [[terrorism]] involving the intentional release or dissemination of [[biological agent]]s. These agents are [[bacteria]], [[virus]]es, insects, fungi, or [[toxin]]s, and may be in a naturally occurring or a human-modified form, in much the same way in [[biological warfare]]. Further, modern [[agribusiness]] is vulnerable to [[:Category:Anti-agriculture_weapons|anti-agricultural]] attacks by terrorists, and such attacks can seriously damage economy as well as [[consumer confidence]].<ref name=\"croodybook\">{{cite book |last1=Croddy |first1=Eric |last2=Perez-Armendariz |first2=Clarissa |last3=Hart |first3=John |title=Chemical and biological warfare : a comprehensive survey for the concerned citizen |date=2002 |publisher=Copernicus Books |isbn=0387950761 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/chemicalbiologic00crod/page/78 78-84] |url=https://archive.org/details/chemicalbiologic00crod/page/78 }}</ref> The later destructive activity is called '''agrobioterrorism''' and is subtype of [[agro-terrorism]].<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Roberge |first1=Lawrence F. |title=Agrobioterrorism |journal=Defense Against Biological Attacks: Volume II |date=2019 |pages=359\u2013383 |doi=10.1007/978-3-030-03071-1_16 |isbn=978-3-030-03070-4 |publisher=Springer International Publishing |language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Definition==\nBioterrorism is the deliberate release of viruses, bacteria, toxins or other harmful agents to cause illness or death in people, animals, or plants.<ref>{{cite web|title=Bioterrorism {{!}} Anthrax {{!}} CDC|url=https://www.cdc.gov/anthrax/bioterrorism/index.html|website=www.cdc.gov|accessdate=25 October 2017|language=en-us}}</ref> These agents are typically found in nature, but could be mutated or altered to increase their ability to cause disease, make them resistant to current medicines, or to increase their ability to be spread into the environment. Biological agents can be spread through the air, water, or in food. Biological agents are attractive to [[Terrorism|terrorists]] because they are extremely difficult to detect and do not cause illness for several hours to several days. Some bioterrorism agents, like the [[smallpox virus]], can be spread from person to person and some, like [[anthrax]], cannot.<ref name=\"CDCBioterrorismOverview\">{{cite web|title=Bioterrorism Overview|url=http://www.bt.cdc.gov/bioterrorism/overview.asp|accessdate=2009-05-22|date=2008-02-12|publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303184927/http://www.bt.cdc.gov/bioterrorism/overview.asp|archivedate=2016-03-03}}</ref><ref>Preston, Richard (2002). ''The Demon in the Freezer'', Ballantine Books, New York. {{ISBN|9780345466631}}.</ref>\n\nBioterrorism may be favored because biological agents are relatively easy and inexpensive to obtain, can be easily disseminated, and can cause widespread fear and panic beyond the actual physical damage.<ref>Advantages of Biologics as Weapons Bioterrorism: A Threat to National Security or Public Health Defining Issue? MM&I 554 University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison and Wisconsin State Laboratory of Hygiene, September 30, 2008.</ref> Military leaders, however, have learned that, as a military asset, bioterrorism has some important limitations; it is difficult to use a bioweapon in a way that only affects the enemy and not friendly forces. A biological weapon is useful to terrorists mainly as a method of creating mass panic and disruption to a state or a country. However, technologists such as [[Bill Joy]] have warned of the potential power which genetic engineering might place in the hands of future bio-terrorists.<ref>{{citation|last=Joy|first=Bill|title=Why the Future Doesn't Need Us: How 21st Century Technologies Threaten to Make Humans an Endangered Species|date=2007-03-31|publisher=Random House|isbn=978-0-553-52835-0|title-link=Why the Future Doesn't Need Us}}</ref>\n\nThe use of agents that do not cause harm to humans, but disrupt the economy, have also been discussed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agpolicy.org/weekpdf/116.pdf|title=Bioterrorism - the high economic costs of an attack|date=October 2002}}</ref> One such pathogen is the [[foot-and-mouth disease]] (FMD) virus, which is capable of causing widespread economic damage and public concern (as witnessed in the [[2001 United Kingdom foot-and-mouth outbreak|2001]] and [[2007 United Kingdom foot-and-mouth outbreak|2007]] FMD outbreaks in the UK), while having almost no capacity to infect humans.\n\n==History==\n{{see also|History of biological warfare}}\n\nBy the time [[World War I]] began, attempts to use anthrax were directed at animal populations. This generally proved to be ineffective.\n\nShortly after the start of World War I, Germany launched a biological sabotage campaign in the United States, Russia, Romania, and France.<ref name=\"GregoryBWaggDMilitaryMedicine\">{{citation|last=Gregory|first=B|author2=Waag, D.|title=Military Medicine: Medical aspects of biological warfare|url=http://www.bordeninstitute.army.mil/published_volumes/biological_warfare/BW-ch06.pdf|accessdate=2009-05-22|year=1997|publisher=Office of the Surgeon General, Department of the Army|id=Library of Congress 97-22242|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090612003248/http://www.bordeninstitute.army.mil/published_volumes/biological_warfare/BW-ch06.pdf|archive-date=2009-06-12|url-status=dead}}</ref> At that time, [[Anton Dilger]] lived in Germany, but in 1915 he was sent to the United States carrying cultures of [[glanders]], a virulent disease of horses and mules. Dilger set up a laboratory in his home in [[Chevy Chase, Maryland|Chevy Chase]], Maryland. He used [[stevedore]]s working the docks in Baltimore to infect horses with [[glanders]] while they were waiting to be shipped to Britain. Dilger was under suspicion as being a German agent, but was never arrested. Dilger eventually fled to Madrid, Spain, where he died during the [[1918 flu pandemic|Influenza Pandemic of 1918]].<ref>{{citation|title=Experts Q & A|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/amex/weapon/sfeature/qa.html|accessdate=2009-05-22|date=2006-12-15|publisher=Public Broadcasting Service}}</ref> In 1916, the Russians arrested a German agent with similar intentions. Germany and its allies infected French cavalry horses and many of Russia's mules and horses on the Eastern Front. These actions hindered artillery and troop movements, as well as supply convoys.<ref name=\"GregoryBWaggDMilitaryMedicine\" />\n \t\nIn 1972, police in [[Chicago]] arrested two college students, Allen Schwander and Stephen Pera, who had planned to poison the city's water supply with [[typhoid]] and other bacteria. Schwander had founded a terrorist group, \"R.I.S.E.\", while Pera collected and grew cultures from the hospital where he worked. The two men fled to [[Cuba]] after being released on bail. Schwander died of natural causes in 1974, while Pera returned to the U.S. in 1975 and was put on probation.<ref>W. Seth Carus, \"R.I.S.E.\", in ''Toxic Terror: Assessing Terrorist Use of Chemical and Biological Weapons'' (MIT Press, 2000), p.55, p.69</ref>\n\nIn 1980, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) announced the eradication of smallpox, a highly contagious and incurable disease. Although the disease has been eliminated in the wild, frozen stocks of smallpox virus are still maintained by the governments of the United States and Russia. Disastrous consequences are feared if rogue politicians or terrorists were to get hold of the smallpox strains. Since vaccination programs are now terminated, the world population is more susceptible to smallpox than ever before.\n\nIn [[Oregon]] in 1984, followers of the [[Rajneesh|Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh]] attempted to control a local [[election]] by [[1984 Rajneeshee bioterror attack|incapacitating the local population]]. This was done by infecting [[salad]] bars in 11 restaurants, produce in grocery stores, doorknobs, and other public domains with ''[[Salmonella typhimurium]]'' bacteria in the city of [[The Dalles]], [[Oregon]]. The attack infected 751 people with severe [[food poisoning]]. There were no fatalities. This incident was the first known bioterrorist attack in the United States in the 20th century.<ref>[http://www.medmicro.wisc.edu/undergraduate/courses/554/ppt/BT-PHproblem081030.ppt#363,15, Past U.S. Incidents of Food Bioterrorism. In Bioterrorism: A Threat to National Security or Public Health Defining Issue, University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison and the Wisconsin State Laboratory of Hygiene, MM&I 554, September 30, 2008]{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> It was also the single largest bioterrorism attack on U.S. soil.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gizmodo.com.au/2016/11/the-largest-bioterrorism-attack-in-us-history-was-an-attempt-to-swing-an-election/|title=The Largest Bioterrorism Attack In US History Was An Attempt To Swing An Election|last=Novak|first=Matt|date=2016-11-03|work=Gizmodo|access-date=2016-12-02|via=}}</ref>\n \t\nIn June 1993, the religious group [[Aum Shinrikyo]] released anthrax in Tokyo. Eyewitnesses reported a foul odor. The attack was a failure, as it did not infect a single person. The reason for this is that the group used the vaccine strain of the bacterium. The spores recovered from the attack showed that they were identical to an anthrax vaccine strain given to animals at the time. These vaccine strains are missing the genes that cause a symptomatic response.<ref name=\"cdc.gov\">[http://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/10/1/03-0238_article CDC-'''Bacillus anthracis''' Incident, Kameido, Tokyo, 1993]</ref>\n\nIn September and October 2001, several cases of [[2001 anthrax attacks|anthrax broke out]] in the [[United States]], apparently caused deliberately. Letters laced with infectious anthrax were concurrently delivered to news media offices and the U.S Congress, alongside an [[2001 anthrax attacks#Anthrax letter to Chile|ambiguously related case]] in [[Chile]]. The letters killed 5.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/2008/CRIME/08/06/anthrax.case/index.html CNN]</ref>\n\n==Types of agents==\n{{Globalize|section|USA|2name=the United States|date=June 2012}}\nUnder current [[United States law]], [[bio-agents]] which have been declared by the [[U.S. Department of Health and Human Services]] or the [[U.S. Department of Agriculture]] to have the \"potential to pose a severe threat to public health and safety\" are officially defined as \"[[select agents]].\" The CDC categorizes these agents (A, B or C) and administers the [[Select Agent Program]], which regulates the laboratories which may possess, use, or transfer select agents within the United States. As with US attempts to categorize harmful recreational drugs, designer viruses are not yet categorized and avian H5N1 has been shown to achieve high mortality and human-communication in a laboratory setting.\n\n===Category A===\nThese high-priority agents pose a risk to national security, can be easily transmitted and disseminated, result in high mortality, have potential major public health impact, may cause public panic, or require special action for public health preparedness.\n\n* Tularemia or \"rabbit fever\":<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/tularemia/|title=CDC Tularemia - Emergency Preparedness & Response|publisher=|date=2019-02-21}}</ref> Tularemia has a very low fatality rate if treated, but can severely incapacitate. The disease is caused by the ''[[Francisella tularensis]]'' bacterium, and can be contracted through contact with [[fur]], inhalation, ingestion of contaminated water or insect bites. ''Francisella tularensis'' is very infectious. A small number of organisms (10\u201350 or so) can cause disease. If ''F. tularensis'' were used as a weapon, the bacteria would likely be made airborne for exposure by inhalation. People who inhale an infectious aerosol would generally experience severe respiratory illness, including life-threatening pneumonia and systemic infection, if they are not treated. The bacteria that cause tularemia occur widely in nature and could be isolated and grown in quantity in a laboratory, although manufacturing an effective aerosol weapon would require considerable sophistication.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bt.cdc.gov/agent/tularemia/facts.asp|title=CDC Tularemia - Key Facts About Tularemia|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100619165524/http://www.bt.cdc.gov/agent/tularemia/facts.asp|archivedate=2010-06-19}}</ref>\n* [[Anthrax disease|Anthrax]]: Anthrax is a non-contagious disease caused by the spore-forming bacterium ''Bacillus anthracis''. The ability of Anthrax to produce within small spores, or bacilli bacterium, makes it readily permeable to porous skin and can cause abrupt symptoms within 24 hours of exposure. The dispersal of this pathogen among densely populated areas is said to carry less than one percent mortality rate, for cutaneous exposure, to a ninety percent or higher mortality for untreated inhalational infections.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Adalja|first=Amesh A.|last2=Toner|first2=Eric|last3=Inglesby|first3=Thomas V.|date=2015-03-05|title=Clinical Management of Potential Bioterrorism-Related Conditions|journal=New England Journal of Medicine|volume=372|issue=10|pages=954\u2013962|doi=10.1056/NEJMra1409755|issn=0028-4793|pmid=25738671}}</ref> An [[anthrax vaccines|anthrax vaccine]] does exist but requires many injections for stable use. When discovered early, anthrax can be cured by administering [[antibiotic]]s (such as [[ciprofloxacin]]).<ref>{{cite journal\n  |title = A Short Course of Antibiotic Treatment Is Effective in Preventing Death from Experimental Inhalational Anthrax after Discontinuing Antibiotics\n  |last1 = Vietri\n  |first1 = Nicholas J.\n  |last2 = Purcell\n  |first2 = Bret K.\n  |last3 = Tobery\n  |first3 = Steven A.\n  |last4 = Rasmussen\n  |first4 = Suzanne L.\n  |last5 = Leffel\n  |first5 = Elizabeth K.\n  |last6 = Twenhafel\n  |first6 = Nancy A.\n  |last7 = Ivins\n  |first7 = Bruce E.\n  |last8 = Kellogg\n  |first8 = Mark D.\n  |last9 = Webster\n  |first9 = Wendy M.\n  |last10 = Wright\n  |first10 = Mary E.\n  |last11 = Friedlander\n  |first11 = Arthur M.\n  |journal = [[The Journal of Infectious Diseases]]\n  |issn = 0022-1899\n  |volume = 199\n  |issue = 3\n  |year = 2009\n  |pages = 336\u201341\n  |jstor = 40254424\n  \n  \n  |doi=10.1086/596063\n|pmid = 19099484\n  |doi-access = free\n  }}</ref> Its first modern incidence in biological warfare were when Scandinavian \"freedom fighters\" supplied by the German General Staff used anthrax with unknown results against the Imperial Russian Army in Finland in 1916.<ref>Bisher, Jamie, \"During World War I, Terrorists Schemed to Use Anthrax in the Cause of Finnish Independence,\" Military History, August 2003, pp. 17\u201322.[https://web.archive.org/web/20091027151654/http://geocities.com/jamie_bisher/anthrax.htm Anthrax Sabotage in Finland]</ref> In 1993, the [[Aum Shinrikyo]] used anthrax in an unsuccessful attempt in Tokyo with zero fatalities.<ref name=\"cdc.gov\"/> Anthrax was used in a [[2001 anthrax attack|series of attacks]] by a microbiologist at the US Army Medical Research Institute of Infection Disease on the offices of several United States Senators in late 2001. The anthrax was in a powder form and it was delivered by the mail.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/eid/vol8no10/02-0330.htm|title=Emerging Infectious Diseases journal|publisher=|access-date=2017-09-08|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101015112554/http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/eid/vol8no10/02-0330.htm|archive-date=2010-10-15|url-status=dead}}</ref> This bioterrorist attack inevitably prompted seven cases of cutaneous anthrax and eleven cases of inhalation anthrax, with five leading to deaths. Additionally, an estimated 10 to 26 cases had prevented fatality through treatment supplied to over 30,000 individuals.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Clarke|first=S. C.|date=2005|title=Bacteria as potential tools in bioterrorism, with an emphasis on bacterial toxins|journal=British Journal of Biomedical Science|volume=62|issue=1|pages=40\u201346|issn=0967-4845|pmid=15816214|doi=10.1080/09674845.2005.11732685}}</ref> Anthrax is one of the few biological agents that federal employees have been vaccinated for. In the US an anthrax vaccine, [[Anthrax Vaccine Adsorbed]] (AVA) exists and requires five injections for stable use. Other [[anthrax vaccines]] also exist. The strain used in the 2001 anthrax attack was identical to the strain used by the [[USAMRIID]].<ref name=\"MacKenzie\">{{cite magazine |author=Debora MacKenzie |title=Anthrax attack bug 'identical' to army strain |magazine=New Scientist |accessdate=16 February 2013 |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/dn2265\n }}</ref>\n* [[Smallpox]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/smallpox/|title=CDC Smallpox Home|publisher=|date=2019-02-19}}</ref> Smallpox is a highly contagious [[virus]]. It is transmitted easily through the atmosphere and has a high [[mortality rate]] (20\u201340%). Smallpox was [[smallpox#Eradication|eradicated]] in the world in the 1970s, thanks to a worldwide vaccination program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/smallpox/prep/cdc-prep.asp|title=CDC Smallpox - What CDC Is Doing to Protect the Public From Smallpox|access-date=2018-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504090748/https://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/smallpox/prep/cdc-prep.asp|archive-date=2018-05-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, some virus samples are still available in Russian and American laboratories. Some believe that after the collapse of the Soviet Union, cultures of smallpox have become available in other countries. Although people born pre-1970 will have been vaccinated for smallpox under the WHO program, the effectiveness of vaccination is limited since the vaccine provides high level of immunity for only 3 to 5 years. Revaccination's protection lasts longer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smallpox.mil/messageMap/messageMapAll.asp?cID=57|title=IHB - The DoD Immunization Information and Training Portal|access-date=2009-05-26|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090814032533/http://smallpox.mil/messageMap/messageMapAll.asp?cID=57|archive-date=2009-08-14|url-status=dead}}</ref> As a biological weapon smallpox is dangerous because of the highly contagious nature of both the infected and their pox. Also, the infrequency with which vaccines are administered among the general population since the eradication of the disease would leave most people unprotected in the event of an outbreak. Smallpox occurs only in humans, and has no external hosts or vectors.\n* [[Botulinum toxin]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/botulism/|title=CDC Botulism - Emergency Preparedness & Response|publisher=|date=2019-08-19}}</ref> The neurotoxin<ref>{{cite journal|title=BOTULINUM TOXIN | pmc=2856357 | pmid=20418969|doi=10.4103/0019-5154.60343|volume=55| issue=1 |year=2010|pages=8\u201314 | last1 = Nigam | first1 = PK | last2 = Nigam | first2 = A | journal=Indian Journal of Dermatology}}</ref> Botulinum is the deadliest toxin known to man, and is produced by the bacterium ''[[Clostridium botulinum]]''. Botulism causes death by [[respiratory failure]] and [[paralysis]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/botulism/factsheet.asp|title=CDC - Facts About Botulism|access-date=2018-12-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170703054124/https://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/botulism/factsheet.asp|archive-date=2017-07-03|url-status=dead}}</ref> Furthermore, the toxin is readily available worldwide due to its cosmetic applications in injections.\n*[[Bubonic plague]]:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/plague/|title=CDC Plague Information - Emergency Preparedness & Response|publisher=|date=2019-02-21}}</ref> Plague is a disease caused by the ''[[Yersinia pestis]]'' bacterium. Rodents are the normal host of plague, and the disease is transmitted to humans by [[flea]] bites and occasionally by [[Bioaerosol|aerosol]] in the form of [[pneumonic plague]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dvbid/plague/index.htm|title=CDC - 01 This Page Has Moved - CDC Plague Home Page - CDC Division of Vector-Borne Infectious Diseases (DVBID)|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519183229/http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/dvbid/plague/index.htm|archivedate=2009-05-19}}</ref> The disease has a history of use in biological warfare dating back many centuries, and is considered a threat due to its ease of culture and ability to remain in circulation among local rodents for a long period of time. The weaponized threat comes mainly in the form of pneumonic plague (infection by inhalation)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bt.cdc.gov/agent/plague/faq.asp|title=CDC Plague - Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ) About Plague|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090528004421/http://www.bt.cdc.gov/agent/plague/faq.asp|archivedate=2009-05-28}}</ref> It was the disease that caused the [[Black Death]] in Medieval Europe.\n* [[Viral hemorrhagic fever]]s:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/vhf/|title=CDC Viral Hemorrhagic Fevers - Emergency Preparedness & Response|publisher=|date=2019-05-16}}</ref> This includes hemorrhagic fevers caused by members of the family ''[[Filoviridae]]'' ([[Marburg virus]] and [[Ebola virus]]), and by the family ''[[Arenaviridae]]'' (for example [[Lassa virus]] and [[Machupo virus]]). [[Ebola virus disease]], in particular, has caused high [[fatality rate]]s ranging from 25\u201390% with a 50% average. No cure currently exists, although vaccines are in development. The Soviet Union investigated the use of filoviruses for biological warfare, and the [[Aum Shinrikyo]] group unsuccessfully attempted to obtain cultures of Ebola virus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/5/4/99-0409_article|title=Aum Shinrikyo: Once and Future Threat? |publisher=|date=1999-08-04}}</ref> Death from Ebola virus disease is commonly due to [[multiple organ failure]] and [[hypovolemic shock]]. Marburg virus was first discovered in [[Marburg]], Germany. No treatments currently exist aside from supportive care. The arenaviruses have a somewhat reduced case-fatality rate compared to disease caused by filoviruses, but are more widely distributed, chiefly in central [[Africa]] and [[South America]].\n\n===Category B===\nCategory B agents are moderately easy to disseminate and have low mortality rates.\n\n* [[Brucellosis]] ([[Brucella|''Brucella'' species]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/brucellosis/|title=CDC Brucellosis - Emergency Preparedness & Response|publisher=|date=2019-05-16}}</ref>\n* Epsilon toxin of ''[[Clostridium perfringens]]''\n* Food safety threats (for example, ''[[Salmonella]] species'', [[Escherichia coli O157:H7|''E coli'' O157:H7]], ''[[Shigella]]'', [[Staphylococcus aureus]]'')\n* [[Glanders]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/nczved/dfbmd/disease_listing/glanders_gi.html |title=CDC Glanders |access-date=2017-09-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100209041042/http://www.cdc.gov/nczved/dfbmd/disease_listing/glanders_gi.html |archive-date=2010-02-09 |url-status=dead }}</ref> (''[[Burkholderia mallei]]'')\n* [[Melioidosis]] (''[[Burkholderia pseudomallei]]'')<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/nczved/dfbmd/disease_listing/melioidosis_gi.html |title=CDC Melioidosis |access-date=2017-09-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211092041/http://www.cdc.gov/nczved/dfbmd/disease_listing/melioidosis_gi.html |archive-date=2010-02-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/nczved/dfbmd/disease_listing/melioidosis_gi.html#2 |title=CDC Why has melioidosis become a current issue? |access-date=2017-09-08 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100211092041/http://www.cdc.gov/nczved/dfbmd/disease_listing/melioidosis_gi.html#2 |archive-date=2010-02-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* [[Psittacosis]] (''[[Chlamydia psittaci]]'')\n* [[Q fever]] (''[[Coxiella burnetii]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/qfever/|title=CDC Q Fever - Emergency Preparedness and Response|publisher=|date=2019-01-15}}</ref>\n* [[Ricin]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emergency.cdc.gov/agent/ricin/|title=CDC Ricin - Emergency Preparedness & Response|publisher=|date=2019-05-16}}</ref> toxin from ''[[Castor oil plant|Ricinus communis]]'' ([[castor bean]]s)\n* [[Abrin]] toxin from ''[[Abrus precatorius]]'' ([[Rosary pea]]s)\n* [[Staphylococcus|Staphylococcal]] enterotoxin B\n* [[Typhus]] (''[[Rickettsia prowazekii]]'')\n* Viral [[encephalitis]] ([[alphavirus]]es, for example,: [[Venezuelan equine encephalitis virus|Venezuelan equine encephalitis]], [[Eastern equine encephalitis virus|eastern equine encephalitis]], [[Western equine encephalitis virus|western equine encephalitis]])\n* Water supply threats (for example, ''[[Vibrio cholerae]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.webmd.com/a-to-z-guides/cholera-11156|title=Cholera|work=WebMD}}</ref> ''[[Cryptosporidium parvum]]'')\n\n===Category C===\nCategory C agents are emerging [[pathogen]]s that might be [[genetic engineering|engineered]] for mass dissemination because of their availability, ease of production and dissemination, high mortality rate, or ability to cause a major health impact.\n\n* [[Nipah virus]]\n* [[Hantavirus]]\n\n==Scenarios==\n\nThere are multiple considerable scenarios, how terrorists might employ biological agents.<ref name=\"croodybook\"/> In 2000, tests conducted by various US agencies showed that indoor attacks in densely populated spaces are much more serious than outdoor attacks. Such enclosed spaces are large buildings, trains, indoor arenas, theaters, malls, tunnels and similar. Contra-measures against such scenarios are building architecture and ventilation systems engineering. In 1993, sewage was spilled out into a river, subsequently drawn into the water system and affected [[1993_Milwaukee_Cryptosporidiosis_outbreak|400,000 people in Milwaukee]], Wisconsin.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Petersen |first1=Carolyn |title=Cryptosporidium and the food supply |journal=The Lancet |date=May 1995 |volume=345 |issue=8958 |pages=1128\u20131129 |doi=10.1016/s0140-6736(95)90972-9|pmid=7723540 }}</ref> The disease-causing organism was [[cryptosporidium parvum]]. This man-made disaster can be a template for a terrorist scenario.<ref name=\"croodybook\"/> Nevertheless, terrorist scenarios are considered more likely near the points of delivery than at the water sources before the [[water treatment]].<ref name=croodybook/> Release of biological agents is more likely for a single building or a neighborhood. Contra-measures against this scenario is the further limitation of access to the water supply systems, tunnels, and infrastructure. Agricultural [[crop-duster]] flights might be misused as delivery devices for biological agents as well.<ref name=croodybook/> Contra-measures against this scenario are background checks of employees of crop-dusting companies and surveillance procedures. \n\nIn the most common hoax scenario, no biological agents are employed.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Lathrop |first1=Peggy |last2=Mann |first2=Linda M. |title=Preparing for bioterrorism |journal=Proceedings (Baylor University. Medical Center) |volume=14 |issue=3 |pages=219\u2013223 |date=2001|pmc=1305820 |pmid=16369620 |doi=10.1080/08998280.2001.11927766 }}</ref> For instance, an envelope with powder in it that says, \u201cYou've just been exposed to anthrax.\u201d Such hoaxes already showed to produce a large [[psychological warfare|psychological impact on the population]].<ref name=wheelis>{{cite journal |last1=Wheelis |first1=Mark |last2=Casagrande |first2=Rocco |last3=Madden |first3=Laurence V. |title=Biological Attack on Agriculture: Low-Tech, High-Impact BioterrorismBecause bioterrorist attack requires relatively little specialized expertise and technology, it is a serious threat to US agriculture and can have very large economic repercussions |journal=BioScience |date=1 July 2002 |volume=52 |issue=7 |pages=569\u2013576 |doi=10.1641/0006-3568(2002)052[0569:BAOALT]2.0.CO;2 |url=https://academic.oup.com/bioscience/article/52/7/569/247956#126036035 |language=en |issn=0006-3568|doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\nAnti-agriculture attacks are considered to require relatively little expertise and technology.<ref name=wheelis/> Biological agents against livestock, fish, vegetation, and crops are mostly not contagious to humans and therefore easier to handle by the attackers. Even a few cases of infections can disrupt a country's agricultural production and export for months like in the case with [[Foot-and-mouth_disease|FMD]].\n\n==Planning and response==\n{{main|Biodefense}}\n{{Globalize|section|USA|2name=the United States|date=June 2012}}\nPlanning may involve the development of biological identification systems. Until recently in the United States, most biological defense strategies have been geared to protecting soldiers on the battlefield rather than ordinary people in cities. Financial cutbacks have limited the tracking of disease outbreaks. Some outbreaks, such as food poisoning due to ''[[Escherichia coli|E. coli]]'' or ''[[Salmonella]]'', could be of either natural or deliberate origin.\n\n=== Preparedness ===\nExport controls on biological agents are not applied uniformly providing terrorists a route for acquisition.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Kuntz|first=Carol|url=https://books.google.com/?id=7bisH_7fo00C&pg=PR3&dq=A+Biological+Threat+Prevention+Strategy+:+Complicating+Adversary+Acquisition+and+Misuse+of+Biological+Agents#v=onepage|title=A Biological Threat Prevention Strategy: Complicating Adversary Acquisition and Misuse of Biological Agents|last2=Salerno|first2=Reynolds|last3=Jacobs|first3=Eli|date=2013-05-15|publisher=Center for Strategic & International Studies|isbn=978-1-4422-2474-2|language=en}}</ref> Laboratories are working on advanced detection systems to provide early warning, identify [[contamination|contaminated areas]] and populations at risk, and to facilitate prompt treatment.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Nikolelis|first=Dimitrios P.|url=https://books.google.com/?id=k-m9CwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&q=terrorism|title=Biosensors for Security and Bioterrorism Applications|last2=Nikoleli|first2=Georgia-Paraskevi|date=2016-03-12|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-319-28926-7|language=en}}</ref> Methods for predicting the use of biological agents in urban areas as well as assessing the area for the hazards associated with a biological attack are being established in major cities. In addition, [[forensic]] technologies are working on identifying biological agents, their geographical origins and/or their initial source. Efforts include decontamination technologies to restore facilities without causing additional environmental concerns.\n\nEarly detection and rapid response to bioterrorism depend on close cooperation between [[public health]] authorities and law enforcement; however, such cooperation is lacking. National detection assets and vaccine stockpiles are not useful if local and state officials do not have access to them.<ref>{{citation|last=Bernett|first=Brian C.|title=US Biodefense and Homeland Security: Toward Detection and Attribution|url=http://www.ccc.nps.navy.mil/research/theses/bernett06.pdf|accessdate=2009-05-24|date=December 2006|publisher=Naval Postgraduate School|location=Monterey, California, United States|page=21|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080229164557/http://www.ccc.nps.navy.mil/research/theses/bernett06.pdf|archivedate=2008-02-29}}</ref>\n\nAspects of protection against bioterrorism in the United States include:\n*Detection and resilience strategies in combating bioterrorism. This occurs primarily through the efforts of the [[DHS Office of Health Affairs|Office of Health Affairs]] (OHA), a part of the [[Department of Homeland Security]] (DHS), whose role is to prepare for an emergency situation that impacts the health of the American populace. Detection has two primary technological factors. First there is OHA's BioWatch program in which collection devices are disseminated to thirty high risk areas throughout the country to detect the presence of aerosolized biological agents before symptoms present in patients.<ref name=\"PrepX\">United States. Cong. House. Committee on Homeland Security. Ensuring Effective Preparedness Responses and Recovery for Events Impacting Health Security Hearing before the Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response and Communications of the Committee on Homeland Security, House of Representatives, One Hundred Twelfth Congress, First Session, March 17, 2011. 112th Cong., 1st sess. HR 397. Washington: U.S. G.P.O., 2012. Print.</ref> This is significant primarily because it allows a more proactive response to a disease outbreak rather than the more passive treatment of the past.\n*Implementation of the Generation-3 automated detection system. This advancement is significant simply because it enables action to be taken in four to six hours due to its automatic response system, whereas the previous system required aerosol detectors to be manually transported to laboratories.<ref name=\"PrepX\"/> Resilience is a multifaceted issue as well, as addressed by OHA. One way in which this is ensured is through exercises that establish preparedness; programs like the Anthrax Response Exercise Series exist to ensure that, regardless of the incident, all emergency personnel will be aware of the role they must fill.<ref name=\"PrepX\"/> Moreover, by providing information and education to public leaders, emergency medical services and all employees of the DHS, OHS suggests it can significantly decrease the impact of bioterrorism.<ref name=\"PrepX\"/>\n*Enhancing the technological capabilities of first responders is accomplished through numerous strategies. The first of these strategies was developed by the Science and Technology Directorate (S&T) of DHS to ensure that the danger of suspicious powders could be effectively assessed, (as many dangerous biological agents such as anthrax exist as a white powder). By testing the accuracy and specificity of commercially available systems used by first responders, the hope is that all biologically harmful powders can be rendered ineffective.<ref name=\"PrepY\">United States. Cong. House. Committee on Homeland Security. First Responder Technologies: Ensuring a Prioritized Approach for Homeland Security Research and Development : Joint Hearing before the Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response and Communications and the Subcommittee on Cybersecurity, Infrastructure Protection, and Security Technologies of the Committee on Homeland Security, House of Representatives, One Hundred Twelfth Congress, Second Session, May 9, 2012. 112th Cong., 2nd sess. HR 397. N.p.: n.p., n.d. Print.</ref>\n*Enhanced equipment for first responders. One recent advancement is the commercialization of a new form of Tyvex\u2122 armor which protects first responders and patients from chemical and biological contaminants. There has also been a new generation of Self-Contained Breathing Apparatuses (SCBA) which has been recently made more robust against bioterrorism agents. All of these technologies combine to form what seems like a relatively strong deterrent to bioterrorism. However, New York City as an entity has numerous organizations and strategies that effectively serve to deter and respond to bioterrorism as it comes. From here the logical progression is into the realm of New York City's specific strategies to prevent bioterrorism.<ref name=\"PrepY\"/>\n*Excelsior Challenge. In the second week of September 2016, the state of New York held a large emergency response training exercise called the Excelsior Challenge, with over 100 emergency responders participating. According to [[WKTV]], \"This is the fourth year of the Excelsior Challenge, a training exercise designed for police and first responders to become familiar with techniques and practices should a real incident occur.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wktv.com/news/A_new_challenge_for_police_and_EMS_personnel.html|title=WKTV.com {{!}} A new Challenge for police and EMS personnel|date=2016-09-15|access-date=2016-10-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161005104757/http://www.wktv.com/news/A_new_challenge_for_police_and_EMS_personnel.html#|archive-date=2016-10-05|url-status=dead}}</ref> The event was held over three days and hosted by the State Preparedness Training Center in [[Oriskany, New York|Oriskany]], New York. Participants included [[Bomb disposal|bomb squad]]<nowiki/>s, canine handlers, tactical team officers and emergency medical services.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://homelandprepnews.com/countermeasures/19747-first-responders-train-new-technology-n-y-s-largest-emergency-response-exercise/|title=First responders train with new technology at N.Y.'s largest emergency response exercise - Homeland Preparedness News|date=2016-09-19|language=en-US|access-date=2016-10-03}}</ref> In an interview with ''Homeland Preparedness News'', Bob Stallman, assistant director at the New York State Preparedness Training Center, said, \"We're constantly seeing what\u2019s happening around the world and we tailor our training courses and events for those types of real-world events.\" For the first time, the 2016 training program implemented New York's new electronic system. The system, called NY Responds, electronically connects every county in New York to aid in disaster response and recovery. As a result, \"counties have access to a new technology known as Mutualink, which improves [[interoperability]] by integrating telephone, radio, video, and file-sharing into one application to allow local emergency staff to share real-time information with the state and other counties.\"<ref name=\":1\" /> The State Preparedness Training Center in Oriskany was designed by the State Division of Homeland Security, and Emergency Services (DHSES) in 2006. It cost $42 million to construct on over 1100 acres and is available for training 360 days a year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newyorkupstate.com/news/2016/09/ny_police_train_for_terrorist_attacks_bombs_active_shooters_videos.html|title=Watch NY police train for terrorist attacks, bombs, active shooters (videos)|access-date=2016-10-03|date=2016-09-15}}</ref> Students from SUNY Albany's College of Emergency Preparedness, Homeland Security and Cybersecurity, were able to participate in this year's exercise and learn how \"DHSES supports law enforcement specialty teams.\"<ref name=\":1\" />\n* Project BioShield. The accrual of vaccines and treatments for potential biological threats, also known as medical countermeasures has been an important aspect in preparing for a potential bioterrorist attack; this took the form of a program beginning in 2004, referred to as [[Project Bioshield Act|Project BioShield]].<ref name=\"Hylton\">[[Wil S. Hylton|Hylton, Wil S.]] \"How Ready Are We for Bioterrorism?\" The New York Times. The New York Times Company, 26 Oct. 2011. Web.</ref> The significance of this program should not be overlooked as \u201cthere is currently enough smallpox vaccine to inoculate every United States citizen\u2026 and a variety of therapeutic drugs to treat the infected.\u201d<ref name=\"Hylton\"/> The Department of Defense also has a variety of laboratories currently working to increase the quantity and efficacy of countermeasures that comprise the national stockpile.<ref name=\"PrepXYZ\"/> Efforts have also been taken to ensure that these medical countermeasures can be disseminated effectively in the event of a bioterrorist attack. The National Association of Chain Drug Stores championed this cause by encouraging the participation of the private sector in improving the distribution of such countermeasures if required.<ref name=\"PrepXYZ\">United States. Cong. House. Committee on Homeland Security. Taking Measure of Countermeasures. Hearing before the Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response and Communications of the Committee on Homeland Security, House of Representatives, One Hundred Twelfth Congress, First Session, April 13, 2011 and May 12, 2011. 112 Cong., 1st sess. HR 397. Washington: U.S. G.P.O., 2012. Print.</ref>\n\nOn a CNN news broadcast in 2011, the CNN chief medical correspondent, Dr. Sanjay Gupta, weighed in on the American government's recent approach to bioterrorist threats. He explains how, even though the United States would be better fending off bioterrorist attacks now than they would be a decade ago, the amount of money available to fight bioterrorism over the last three years has begun to decrease. Looking at a detailed report that examined the funding decrease for bioterrorism in fifty-one American cities, Dr. Gupta stated that the cities \"wouldn\u2019t be able to distribute vaccines as well\" and \"wouldn't be able to track viruses.\" He also said that film portrayals of global pandemics, such as ''[[Contagion (2011 film)|Contagion]]'', were actually quite possible and may occur in the United States under the right conditions.<ref>John King, USA. CNNW. San Francisco. 20 Dec. 2011. Television.</ref>\n\nA news broadcast by [[MSNBC]] in 2010 also stressed the low levels of bioterrorism preparedness in the United States.  The broadcast stated that a bipartisan report gave the Obama administration a failing grade for its efforts to respond to a bioterrorist attack. The news broadcast invited the former New York City police commissioner, Howard Safir, to explain how the government would fare in combating such an attack. He said how \"biological and chemical weapons are probable and relatively easy to disperse.\" Furthermore, Safir thought that efficiency in bioterrorism preparedness is not necessarily a question of money, but is instead dependent on putting resources in the right places. The broadcast suggested that the nation was not ready for something more serious.<ref>MSNBC News Live. MSNBC. New York City. 26 Jan. 2010. Television</ref>\n\nIn a September 2016 interview conducted by Homeland Preparedness News, Daniel Gerstein, a senior policy researcher for the RAND Corporation, stresses the importance in preparing for potential bioterrorist attacks on the nation. He implored the U.S. government to take the proper and necessary actions to implement a strategic plan of action to save as many lives as possible and to safeguard against potential chaos and confusion. He believes that because there have been no significant instances of bioterrorism since the anthrax attacks in 2001, the government has allowed itself to become complacent making the country that much more vulnerable to unsuspecting attacks, thereby further endangering the lives of U.S. citizens.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://homelandprepnews.com/biological-threats/19645-rands-gerstein-u-s-needs-biodefense-strategy-protect-terror-threats/|title=RAND's Gerstein: U.S. needs biodefense strategy to protect against terror threats|last=Rozens|first=Tracy|date=2016-09-02|website=Homeland Preparedness News|publisher=|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-19}}</ref>\n\nGerstein formerly served in the Science and Technology Directorate of the Department of Homeland Security from 2011 to 2014. He claims there has not been a serious plan of action since 2004 during George W. Bush's presidency, in which he issued a Homeland Security directive delegating responsibilities among various federal agencies. He also stated that the blatant mishandling of the Ebola virus outbreak in 2014 attested to the government's lack of preparation. This past May, legislation that would create a national defense strategy was introduced in the Senate, coinciding with the timing of ISIS-affiliated terrorist groups get closer to weaponizing biological agents. In May, 2016, Kenyan officials apprehended two members of an Islamic extremist group in motion to set off a biological bomb containing anthrax. Mohammed Abdi Ali, the believed leader of the group, who was a medical intern, was arrested along with his wife, a medical student. The two were caught just before carrying out their plan.<ref>https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/05/04/foiled-kenya-anthrax-plot-hints-at-islamic-states-scramble-for-africa/</ref> The Blue Ribbon Study Panel on Biodefense, which comprises a group of experts on national security and government officials, in which Gerstein had previously testified to, submitted its National Blueprint for Biodefense to Congress in October 2015 listing their recommendations for devising an effective plan.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nBill Gates said in a February 18, 2017 ''Business Insider'' op-ed (published near the time of his Munich Security Conference speech) that it is possible for an airborne pathogen to kill at least 30 million people over the course of a year.<ref>https://www.businessinsider.com/bill-gates-op-ed-bio-terrorism-epidemic-world-threat-2017-2</ref> In a ''New York Times'' report, the [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation|Gates Foundation]] predicted that a modern outbreak similar to the [[1918 flu pandemic|Spanish Influenza pandemic]] (which killed between 50 million and 100 million people) could end up killing more than 360 million people worldwide, even considering widespread availability of vaccines and other healthcare tools. The report cited increased [[globalization]], rapid international air travel, and [[urbanization]] as increased reasons for concern.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hstoday.us/industry-news/general/single-article/exclusive-pandemic-crossroads/17c710beb467f48ccf7609188a8feb7a.html|title=Homeland Security Today: EXCLUSIVE: Pandemic Crossroads|last=Hutchinson|first=Robert C.|date=2017-07-09|website=www.hstoday.us|language=en|access-date=2017-09-12}}{{dead link|date=September 2018|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> In a March 9, 2017 interview with CNBC, former U.S. Senator [[Joe Lieberman]], who was co-chair of the bipartisan [[Blue Ribbon Study Panel on Biodefense]], said a worldwide pandemic could end the lives of more people than a nuclear war. Lieberman also expressed worry that a terrorist group like ISIS could develop a synthetic influenza strain and introduce it to the world to kill civilians.<ref name=\":3\" /> In July 2017, Robert C. Hutchinson, former agent at the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]], called for a \"whole-of-government\" response to the next global health threat, which he described as including strict security procedures at our borders and proper execution of government preparedness plans.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nAlso, novel approaches in biotechnology, such as synthetic biology, could be used in the future to design new types of biological warfare agents.<ref>Kelle A (2009) Security issues related to synthetic biology. Chapter 7. In: Schmidt M, Kelle A, Ganguli-Mitra A, de Vriend H (eds) Synthetic biology. The technoscience and its societal conse- quences. Springer, Berlin</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = JCVI: Research / Projects / Synthetic Genomics {{!}} Options for Governance / Overview|url = http://www.jcvi.org/cms/research/projects/syngen-options/overview/|website = www.jcvi.org|access-date = 2016-01-24|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160130071934/http://www.jcvi.org/cms/research/projects/syngen-options/overview/#|archive-date = 2016-01-30|url-status = dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Office of Biotechnology Activities {{!}} Office of Science Policy|url = http://osp.od.nih.gov/office-biotechnology-activities/biosecurity/pdf/NSABB%2520SynBio%2520-DRAFT%2520Report-FINAL%2520(2)_6-7-10.pdf|website = osp.od.nih.gov|access-date = 2016-01-24|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160201073836/http://osp.od.nih.gov/office-biotechnology-activities/biosecurity/pdf/NSABB%2520SynBio%2520-DRAFT%2520Report-FINAL%2520(2)_6-7-10.pdf#|archive-date = 2016-02-01|url-status = dead}}</ref><ref>M.Buller, The potential use of genetic engineering to enhance orthopox viruses as bioweapons. Presentation at the International Conference \u2018Smallpox Biosecurity. Preventing the Unthinkable\u2019 (21\u201322 October 2003) Geneva, Switzerland</ref> Special attention has to be laid on future experiments (of concern) that:<ref>Kelle A. 2007. Synthetic Biology & Biosecurity Awareness In Europe. Bradford Science and Technology Report No.9</ref>\n# Would demonstrate how to render a vaccine ineffective;\n# Would confer resistance to therapeutically useful antibiotics or antiviral agents;\n# Would enhance the virulence of a pathogen or render a nonpathogen virulent;\n# Would increase transmissibility of a pathogen;\n# Would alter the host range of a pathogen;\n# Would enable the evasion of diagnostic/detection tools;\n# Would enable the weaponization of a biological agent or toxin\nMost of the biosecurity concerns in synthetic biology, however, are focused on the role of DNA synthesis and the risk of producing genetic material of lethal viruses (e.g. 1918 Spanish flu, polio) in the lab.<ref>Tumpej TM et al. 2005. Characterization of the Reconstructed 1918 Spanish Influenza Pandemic Virus. Science Vol. 310(5745):77\u201380</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Cello | first1 = J. | last2 = Paul | first2 = A. V. | last3 = Wimmer | first3 = E. | year = 2002 | title = Chemical synthesis of poliovirus cDNA: generation of infectious virus in the absence of natural template | url = | journal = Science | volume = 297 | issue = 5583| pages = 1016\u20131018 | doi=10.1126/science.1072266 | pmid=12114528| bibcode = 2002Sci...297.1016C }}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|title = Synthetic viruses: a new opportunity to understand and prevent viral disease|journal = Nature Biotechnology|date = 2009-12-01|issn = 1087-0156|pmc = 2819212|pmid = 20010599|pages = 1163\u201372|volume = 27|issue = 12|doi = 10.1038/nbt.1593|first = Eckard|last = Wimmer|first2 = Steffen|last2 = Mueller|first3 = Terrence M|last3 = Tumpey|first4 = Jeffery K|last4 = Taubenberger}}</ref> The CRISPR/Cas system has emerged as a promising technique for gene editing. It was hailed by The Washington Post as \"the most important innovation in the synthetic biology space in nearly 30 years.\"<ref name=\"WangerMRoleOfClinicalInformationSystems\" /> While other methods take months or years to edit gene sequences, CRISPR speeds that time up to weeks.<ref name=\"WangerMRoleOfClinicalInformationSystems\" /> However, due to its ease of use and accessibility, it has raised a number of ethical concerns, especially surrounding its use in the biohacking space.<ref>{{Cite news|title = The Crispr Quandary|url = https://www.nytimes.com/2015/11/15/magazine/the-crispr-quandary.html|newspaper = The New York Times|date = 2015-11-09|access-date = 2016-01-24|issn = 0362-4331|first = Jennifer|last = Kahn}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = CRISPR, the disruptor|url = http://www.nature.com/news/crispr-the-disruptor-1.17673|website = Nature News & Comment|access-date = 2016-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title = Everything you need to know about why CRISPR is such a hot technology|url = https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/innovations/wp/2015/11/04/everything-you-need-to-know-about-why-crispr-is-such-a-hot-technology/|newspaper = The Washington Post|date = 2015-11-04|access-date = 2016-01-24|issn = 0190-8286|language = en-US|first = Dominic|last = Basulto}}</ref>\n\n===Biosurveillance===\nIn 1999, the [[University of Pittsburgh]]'s Center for [[Biomedical]] Informatics deployed the first automated bioterrorism detection system, called [[Real-Time Outbreak Disease Surveillance|RODS (Real-Time Outbreak Disease Surveillance)]]. RODS is designed to collect data from many data sources and use them to perform signal detection, that is, to detect a possible bioterrorism event at the earliest possible moment. RODS, and other systems like it, collect data from sources including clinic data, laboratory data, and data from over-the-counter drug sales.<ref name=\"WangerMRoleOfClinicalInformationSystems\">{{citation|last=Wagner|first=Michael M.|author2=Espino, Jeremy|title=Healthcare Information Management Systems|chapter-url=|edition=3|year=2004|publisher=Springer-Verlag|location=New York|pages=513\u2013539|chapter=The role of clinical information systems in public health surveillance|display-authors=etal}}</ref><ref name=\"WangerMAvailabilityAndComparativeValueOfData\">{{citation|last=Wagner|first=Michael M.|author2=Aryel, Ron|title=Availability and Comparative Value of Data Elements Required for an Effective Bioterrorism Detection System|url=http://rods.health.pitt.edu/LIBRARY/dato2AHRQInterimRpt112801.pdf|accessdate=2009-05-22|date=2001-11-28|publisher=Real-time Outbreak and Disease Surveillance Laboratory|display-authors=etal|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110303223152/http://rods.health.pitt.edu/LIBRARY/dato2AHRQInterimRpt112801.pdf|archivedate=2011-03-03}}</ref> In 2000, Michael Wagner, the codirector of the RODS laboratory, and [[Ron Aryel]], a subcontractor, conceived the idea of obtaining live data feeds from \"non-traditional\" (non-health-care) data sources. The RODS laboratory's first efforts eventually led to the establishment of the National Retail Data Monitor, a system which collects data from 20,000 retail locations nationwide.<ref name=\"WangerMRoleOfClinicalInformationSystems\" />\n\nOn February 5, 2002, [[George W. Bush]] visited the RODS laboratory and used it as a model for a [[USD|$]]300 million spending proposal to equip all 50 states with biosurveillance systems. In a speech delivered at the nearby [[Masonic temple]], Bush compared the RODS system to a modern \"[[DEW]]\" line (referring to the Cold War ballistic missile early warning system).<ref>{{citation|last=Togyer|first=Jason|title=Pitt Magazine: Airborne Defense|url=http://www.pittmag.pitt.edu/june2002/feature1.html|accessdate=2009-05-22|date=June 2002|publisher=University of Pittsburgh|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100616101219/http://www.pittmag.pitt.edu/june2002/feature1.html|archive-date=2010-06-16|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe principles and practices of biosurveillance, a new interdisciplinary science, were defined and described in the ''Handbook of Biosurveillance'', edited by Michael Wagner, Andrew Moore and Ron Aryel, and published in 2006. Biosurveillance is the science of real-time disease outbreak detection. Its principles apply to both natural and man-made epidemics (bioterrorism).\n\nData which potentially could assist in early detection of a bioterrorism event include many categories of information. Health-related data such as that from hospital computer systems, clinical laboratories, [[electronic health record]] systems, medical examiner record-keeping systems, 911 call center computers, and veterinary medical record systems could be of help; researchers are also considering the utility of data generated by [[ranching]] and [[feedlot]] operations, food processors, [[drinking water]] systems, school attendance recording, and physiologic monitors, among others.<ref name=\"WangerMAvailabilityAndComparativeValueOfData\" />\n\nIn [[Europe]], disease surveillance is beginning to be organized on the continent-wide scale needed to track a biological emergency. The system not only monitors infected persons, but attempts to discern the origin of the outbreak.\n\nResearchers have experimented with devices to detect the existence of a threat:\n\n* Tiny [[integrated circuit|electronic chips]] that would contain living [[neuron|nerve cells]] to warn of the presence of bacterial toxins (identification of broad range toxins)\n* [[Fiber-optic]] tubes lined with [[antibody|antibodies]] coupled to light-emitting molecules (identification of specific pathogens, such as anthrax, botulinum, ricin)\n\nSome research shows that ultraviolet [[avalanche photodiodes]] offer the high gain, reliability and robustness needed to detect anthrax and other bioterrorism agents in the air. The fabrication methods and device characteristics were described at the 50th Electronic Materials Conference in Santa Barbara on June 25, 2008. Details of the photodiodes were also published in the February 14, 2008 issue of the journal Electronics Letters and the November 2007 issue of the journal IEEE Photonics Technology Letters.<ref>[http://newswise.com/articles/view/541788/ Avalanche Photodiodes Target Bioterrorism Agents] Newswise, Retrieved on June 25, 2008.</ref>\n\nThe United States Department of Defense conducts global biosurveillance through several programs, including the Global Emerging Infections Surveillance and Response System.<ref>Pellerin, Cheryl. [http://www.defense.gov/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=65852 \"Global Nature of Terrorism Drives Biosurveillance.\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112191814/http://www.defense.gov/news/newsarticle.aspx?id=65852 |date=January 12, 2013 }} ''American Forces Press Service'', 27 October 2011.</ref>\n\nAnother powerful tool developed within New York City for use in countering bioterrorism is the development of the New York City [[Syndromic Surveillance]] System. This system is essentially a way of tracking disease progression throughout New York City, and was developed by the [[New York City Department of Health and Mental Hygiene]] (NYC DOHMH) in the wake of the 9/11 attacks. The system works by tracking the symptoms of those taken into the emergency department\u2014based on the location of the hospital to which they are taken and their home address\u2014and assessing any patterns in symptoms. These established trends can then be observed by medical epidemiologists to determine if there are any disease outbreaks in any particular locales; maps of disease prevalence can then be created rather easily.<ref>Chen, H, D Zeng, and Y Pan. \"Infectious Disease Informatics: Syndromic Surveillance for Public Health and Bio-Defense.\" 20120, XXII, 209p. 68 illus.., Hardcover.</ref> This is an obviously beneficial tool in fighting bioterrorism as it provides a means through which such attacks could be discovered in their nascence; assuming bioterrorist attacks result in similar symptoms across the board, this strategy allows New York City to respond immediately to any bioterrorist threats that they may face with some level of alacrity.\n\n==Response to bioterrorism incident or threat==\n{{Globalize|section|USA|2name=the United States|date=June 2012}}\nGovernment agencies which would be called on to respond to a bioterrorism incident would include law enforcement, hazardous materials and decontamination units, and emergency medical units, if available.\n\nThe US military has specialized units, which can respond to a bioterrorism event; among them are the [[United States Marine Corps]]' [[Chemical Biological Incident Response Force]] and the [[United States Army|U.S. Army]]'s [[20th Support Command (CBRNE)]], which can detect, identify, and neutralize threats, and [[decontamination|decontaminate]] victims exposed to bioterror agents. US response would include the [[Center for Disease Control]].\n\nHistorically, governments and authorities have relied on quarantines to protect their populations. International bodies such as the [[World Health Organization]] already devote some of their resources to monitoring epidemics and have served clearing-house roles in historical epidemics.\n\nMedia attention toward the seriousness of biological attacks increased in 2013 to 2014. In July 2013, ''Forbes'' published an article with the title \"Bioterrorism: A Dirty Little Threat With Huge Potential Consequences.\"<ref>Bell, Larry. [https://www.forbes.com/sites/larrybell/2013/07/21/bioterrorism-a-dirty-little-threat-with-huge-potential-consequences/ \"Bioterrorism: A Dirty Little Threat With Huge Potential Consequences\"]. ''Forbes''. 2013-07-21 (Retrieved 2014-02-17)</ref> In November 2013, Fox News reported on a new strain of botulism, saying that the Centers for Disease and Control lists botulism as one of two agents that have \"the highest risks of mortality and morbidity\", noting that there is no antidote for botulism.<ref>Heitz, David. [http://www.foxnews.com/health/2013/11/02/deadly-bioterror-threats-6-real-risks/ \"Deadly bioterror threats: 6 real risks\"]. Fox News. 2013-11-02 (Retrieved 2014-02-17)</ref> ''[[USA Today]]'' reported that the U.S. military in November was trying to develop a vaccine for troops from the bacteria that cause the disease Q fever, an agent the military once used as a biological weapon.<ref>Locker, Ray. [https://www.usatoday.com/story/nation/2013/11/15/q-fever-vaccine-search-continues/3527345/ \"Pentagon seeking vaccine for bioterror disease threat\"]. ''USA Today''. 2013-11-18 (Retrieved 2014-02-17)</ref> In February 2014, the former special assistant and senior director for biodefense policy to President George W. Bush called the bioterrorism risk imminent and uncertain<ref>Cohen, Bryan. [http://bioprepwatch.com/biological-threats/kadlec-says-biological-attack-is-uncertain-imminent-reality/335981/ \"Kadlec says biological attack is uncertain, imminent reality\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209212132/http://bioprepwatch.com/biological-threats/kadlec-says-biological-attack-is-uncertain-imminent-reality/335981/ |date=2015-02-09 }}. Bio Prep Watch. 2014-02-17 (Retrieved 2014-02-17)</ref> and Congressman [[Bill Pascrell]] called for increasing federal measures against bioterrorism as a \"matter of life or death.\"<ref>Cohen, Bryan. [https://archive.is/20140217165044/http://bioprepwatch.com/bioterrorism/pascrell-says-bioterror-threat-a-life-or-death-matter/335939/ \"Pascrell: Bioterror threat a life or death matter\"]. Bio Prep Watch. 2014-02-12 (Retrieved 2014-02-17)</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote a story saying the United States would spend $40 million to help certain low and middle-income countries deal with the threats of bioterrorism and infectious diseases.<ref>Tavernise, Sabrina. [https://www.nytimes.com/2014/02/14/health/us-backs-new-global-initiative-against-infectious-diseases.html?hpw&rref=health&_r=0 \"U.S. Backs New Global Initiative Against Infectious Diseases\"]. ''New York Times''. 2014-02-13 (Retrieved 2014-02-17)</ref>\n\n[[Bill Gates]] has warned that bioterrorism could kill more people than nuclear war.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bioterrorism could kill more people than nuclear war, Bill Gates to warn world leaders|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/02/17/biological-terrorism-could-kill-people-nuclear-attacks-bill/|accessdate=19 February 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=18 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2018, a [[CNN]] employee discovered on an airplane a \"sensitive, top-secret document in the seatback pouch explaining how the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] would respond to a bioterrorism attack at the [[Super Bowl]].\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900009991/jays-jokes-did-you-forget-your-bioterrorism-report-on-the-plane.html|title=Jay's Jokes: Did you forget your bioterrorism report on the plane?|last=Evensen|first=Jay|date=2018-02-12|work=DeseretNews.com|access-date=2018-02-16|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== 2017 U.S. budget proposal affecting bioterrorism programs ===\nPresident Donald Trump promoted his first budget around keeping America safe. However, one aspect of defense would receive less money: \"protecting the nation from deadly pathogens, man-made or natural,\" according to ''The New York Times''. Agencies tasked with biosecurity get a decrease in funding under the Administration's budget proposal.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/28/us/politics/biosecurity-trump-budget-defense.html|title=Trump's Proposed Budget Cuts Trouble Bioterrorism Experts|last=Baumgaertner|first=Emily|date=2017-05-28|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-05-30|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nFor example:<ref name=\":2\" />\n* The Office of Public Health Preparedness and Response would be cut by $136 million, or 9.7 percent. The office tracks outbreaks of disease.\n* The National Center for Emerging and Zoonotic Infectious Diseases would be cut by $65 million, or 11 percent. The center is a branch of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention that fights threats like anthrax and the [[Ebola virus]], and additionally towards research on HIV/AIDS vaccines.\n* Within the [[National Institutes of Health]], the [[National Institute of Allergy and Infectious Diseases]] (NIAID) would lose 18 percent of its budget. NIAID oversees responses to Zika, Ebola and [[HIV/AIDS]] vaccine research.\n\"The next [[weapon of mass destruction]] may not be a bomb,\" Lawrence O. Gostin, the director of the World Health Organization's Collaborating Center on Public Health Law and Human Rights, told ''The New York Times''. \"It may be a tiny pathogen that you can't see, smell or taste, and by the time we discover it, it'll be too late.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n=== Lack of international standards on public health experiments ===\nTom Inglesy, the CEO and director of the Center for Health Security at the [[Johns Hopkins Bloomberg School of Public Health]] and an internationally recognized expert on public health preparedness, pandemic and emerging infectious disease said in 2017 that the lack of an internationally standardized approval process that could be used to guide countries in conducting public health experiments for resurrecting a disease that has already been eradicated increases the risk that the disease could be used in bioterrorism. This was in reference to the lab synthesis of [[Orthopoxvirus|horsepox]] in 2017 by researchers at the [[University of Alberta]]. The researchers recreated horsepox, an extinct cousin of the [[Smallpox|smallpox virus]], in order to research new ways to treat cancer.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://homelandprepnews.com/featured/23673-bioterrorism-threats-require-common-global-experimentation-oversight-expert-says/|title=Bioterrorism threats require common global experimentation oversight, expert says|last=Riley|first=Kim|date=2017-08-10|work=Homeland Preparedness News|access-date=2018-01-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\n{{main|Biological warfare in popular culture}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n{{Refbegin}}\n* {{citation|last=Block|first=Steven M.|title=The growing threat of biological weapons|url=http://www.americanscientist.org/issues/feature/the-growing-threat-of-biological-weapons|accessdate=2009-05-22|volume=89 | issue=1|year=2001|doi=10.1511/2001.1.28|journal=American Scientist|page=28|bibcode=2001AmSci..89.....B}}\n* {{citation|last=Christopher|first=G. W.|title=Adapted from Biological Warfare: A Historical Perspective|url=|year=1998|publisher=Operational Medicine Division|location=Fort Detrick, Maryland|display-authors=etal}}\n* {{citation|last1=Eitzen|first1=E.|last2=Takafuji|first2=E.|title=Military Medicine: Medical Aspects of Chemical and Biological Warfare|chapter-url=|year=1997|publisher=Office of the Surgeon General, Department of the Army|chapter=Historical Overview of Biological Warfare}}\n* {{citation|title=Iraq's Biological Weapon Program|url=http://www.iraqwatch.org/profiles/biological.html|accessdate=2009-05-22|date=August 2006|publisher=Iraq's Biological Weapon Program|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090411043128/http://www.iraqwatch.org/profiles/biological.html|archivedate=2009-04-11}}\n* {{citation|last=Milanovich|first=F.|title=Reducing the threat of biological weapons|url=http://www.llnl.gov/str/Milan.html|accessdate=2009-05-22|date=June 1998|publisher=Science and Technology Review|pages=4\u20139|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081123160358/https://www.llnl.gov/str/Milan.html|archive-date=2008-11-23|url-status=dead}}\n* {{citation|last=Paquette|first=Laure|title=Bioterrorism in Medical and Healthcare Administration|url=https://books.google.com/?id=fLUIfjbpjUIC&pg=PP1&dq=Bioterrorism+in+Medical+and+Healthcare+Administration|accessdate=2009-05-22|edition=1|date=2006-06-29|publisher=CRC|isbn=978-0-8247-5651-2}}\n* {{citation|last=Wagner|first=M.|author2=Moore, A. |author3=Aryel, R.|title=Handbook of Biosurveillance|url=|year=2006|publisher=Academic Press|location=San Diego, California, United States}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource|The Town That Was Poisoned}}\n{{Library resources box |by=no |onlinebooks=no |others=yes lcheading=Bioterrorism}}\n{{Refbegin}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110616062822/http://student.cs.ucc.ie/cs1064/jabowen/IPSC/articles/carusBiocrimes.pdf Bioterrorism and Biocrimes.The Illicit Use of Biological Agents Since 1900, by W. Seth Carus]\n* [https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:4klaEuJMfO8J:www.adl.org/learn/anthrax/beyond_anthrax.pdf+Stephen+Pera+%22Allen+Schwander+%22&hl=en&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESj7z1og116Xu462BdEPflh91VyPKxWR5pM56grte13Y7Rb1FsT13GstGge3I_6P7MmFQSW1HvyutwVtf1yTIKUEcN06_WI-0v_aSGzD7W8-y9N0ZjkUNZW1sy3fZfppzSZyt9QV&sig=AHIEtbQQNYSJL_dcDHdQvR_emtek0drKAg Beyond Anthrax.Extremism and the Bioterrorism Threat]\n* [http://www.eht-forum.org/ Emerging Health Threats Forum]\n* [http://health.europa.eu/my_environment/bio_terrorism/index_en.htm EU Health Portal]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Information on EU activities related to bioterrorism\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20061129022411/http://www.bt.cdc.gov/bioterrorism/ United States Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]\n* [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/nova/bioterror/ NOVA: Bioterror]\n* [http://web.mit.edu/professional/short-programs/courses/combating_bioterrorism.html Pandemics and Bioterrorism: From Realistic Threats to Effective Policies]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20141021001529/http://www.newslobby.net/2014/10/14/bioterrorism-could-ebola-be-a-possible-new-biological-weapon/ Bioterrorism: Could Ebola be a Possible New Biological Weapon?]\n* [https://obamawhitehouse.archives.gov/sites/default/files/microsites/ostp/p3co-finalguidancestatement.pdf Recommended Policy Guidance for Departmental Development of Review Mechanisms for Potential Pandemic Pathogen Care and Oversight (P3CO)]. Obama Administration. January 9, 2017. \n{{Refend}}\n\n{{Bioterrorism}}\n{{U.S. biological defense}}\n\n[[Category:Biological warfare]]\n[[Category:Bioterrorism| ]]\n[[Category:Terrorism by method]]\n", "name_user": "1.187.186.199", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eCategory C)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bioterrorism"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mexico", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Mexico}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Mexico\n| map1            = {{Switcher\n|[[file:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Mexico.svg|200xpx]]\n| Number of cumulative confirmed cases by state\n|[[file:COVID-19 Outbreak Active Cases in Mexico.svg|200xpx]]\n| Number of active confirmed cases by state\n|[[file:COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Mexico per 100,000 inhabitants.svg|200xpx]]\n| Cumulative cases per 100,000 inhabitants by state \n|[[file:COVID-19 Outbreak Active Cases in Mexico per 100,000 inhabitants.svg|200xpx]]\n| Active cases per 100,000 inhabitants by state | default = 1\n}}\n| legend1         = <center>Confirmed cases (as of April 21)</center>\n| map2            = COVID-19 Outbreak Deaths in Mexico.svg\n| legend2         = Number of confirmed deaths by state\n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome coronavirus 2|SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Mexico]]\n| first_case      = [[Mexico City]] and [[Los Mochis]]<ref name=\"First\" />\n| arrival_date    = 28 February 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=02|day1=28|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China<br /> (via Italy and the United States)<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.informador.mx/mexico/Confirman-siete-casos-de-coronavirus-en-Mexico-20200307-0085.html |title= Confirman siete casos de coronavirus en M\u00e9xico |language=Spanish |work=informador.mx |date=7 March 2020 |access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n| recovery_cases  = 5,956\n| deaths          = 1,069\n| confirmed_cases = 11,633\n| active_cases    = 4,127\n| suspected_cases = 7,588\n| severe_cases    = 1,735 <small>(severe)</small><br/> 378 <small>(mechanical ventilation)</small><ref name=\"cases1\" />\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{URL|https://coronavirus.gob.mx/}}\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Mexico]] in February 2020. However, the [[Consejo Nacional de Ciencia y Tecnolog\u00eda (Mexico)|National Council of Science and Technology (CONACYT)]] reported two cases of COVID-19 in mid-January 2020 in the states of Nayarit and Tabasco, one case per state.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://datos.covid-19.conacyt.mx/#COMNac |title=Covid-19 CONACYT |date= April 21, 2020 |language=es}}</ref> As of April 23, there had been 11,633 confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Mexico and 1,069 reported deaths<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/nacional/mexico-supera-las-mil-muertes-por-coronavirus-hay-11-633-casos-confirmados |title=M\u00e9xico supera las mil muertes por coronavirus; hay 11,633 casos confirmados. |author= Redacci\u00f3n |date= April 23, 2020 |language=es |website= El Financiero}}</ref>, although the Secretariat of Health estimated, in mid April 2020, that there were more than 26,000 cases in Mexico, because they were considering the total number of cases confirmed as a statistical sample.<ref name=\"sentinela\" />\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Mexico medical cases chart}}\n\n=== January 2020 ===\nOn 22 January 2020, the [[Secretariat of Health (Mexico)|Secretariat of Health]] issued a statement saying that the novel coronavirus COVID-19 did not present a danger to Mexico. 441 cases had been confirmed in [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in mainland China|China]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Thailand|Thailand]], [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in South Korea|South Korea]], and [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|the United States]], and a travel advisory was issued on 9 January.<ref name=indigo />\n\nOn January 30, 2020 before the declaration of a pandemic by the [[World Health Organization]] the Government of Mexico designed a ''Preparation and Response Plan'' that was made by the National Committee for Health Safety, a working group led by Secretariat of Health composed by different health entities aiming to act upon the imminent arrival of the pandemic. This group carried out a series of alert measures, rehabilitation and updating of epidemiological regulations based on the International Health Regulations, being the first Latam country that deployed a [[mathematical modelling of infectious disease]].<ref name=salud />\n\n=== February 2020 ===\nThe cruise ship ''[[Grand Princess]]'' docked in [[Puerto Vallarta]] (15 February), [[Manzanillo, Colima|Manzanillo]] (16 February), [[Mazatl\u00e1n]] (17 February) and [[Cabo San Lucas]](18 February), spending 9 to 12 hours in each port. The first COVID-19 death in California was a man who had been on this ship on an earlier cruise. This ship was later quarantined off San Francisco and docked in Oakland 11 March with 21 onboard who tested positive for the coronavirus.<ref>[https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2020-03-09/what-we-know-about-grand-princess-docking-coronavirus-quarantine What we know about Grand Princess docking] Los Angeles Times</ref>\n\nThe cruise ship {{ship||MSC Meraviglia}}, which was not allowed to dock in the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Cayman Islands|Cayman Islands]] or [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Jamaica|Jamaica]], docked in [[Cozumel]], Quintana Roo, on 27 February. Three passengers were diagnosed with ''[[influenza A virus]],'' but no cases of coronavirus were found.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://politica.expansion.mx/mexico/2020/02/26/el-crucero-que-arribo-a-cozumel-esta-libre-de-coronavirus |title=El crucero que arrib\u00f3 a Cozumel est\u00e1 libre de coronavirus |trans-title=The cruise ship that arrived in Cozumel is free of coronaviruses |language=es |work=Expansi\u00f3n Politica |date=27 February 2020 |access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February, Mexico confirmed its first three cases. A 35-year-old man and a 59-year-old man in [[Mexico City]] and a 41-year-old man in the northern state of [[Sinaloa]] tested positive and were held in isolation at a hospital and a hotel, respectively. They had travelled to [[Bergamo]] and stayed in Italy for a week in mid-February.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2020/02/28/mexico-confirms-its-first-2-coronavirus-cases/|title=Mexico Confirms Its First 2 Coronavirus Cases|last=|first=|date=28 February 2020|website=CBS Los Angeles |url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.trust.org/item/20200228134645-auoh9/|title=Mexico confirms first coronavirus cases in two men returned from Italy|last=Foundation|first=Thomson Reuters|website=news.trust.org|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"First\">{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/GobiernoMX/status/1233418133353844736|title=La @SSalud_mx confirm\u00f3 dos casos de coronavirus en M\u00e9xico, el primero en la capital y el segundo en Sinaloa. Se trata de pacientes de bajo riesgo que est\u00e1n siendo atendidos. Invitamos a la poblaci\u00f3n a seguir informada y tomar medidas de prevenci\u00f3n|last=M\u00e9xico|first=Gobierno de|date=28 February 2020|website=@GobiernoMX|language=es|access-date=28 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://elfinanciero.com.mx/salud/van-3-casos-confirmados-de-coronavirus-en-mexico|title=Van 3 casos confirmados de coronavirus en M\u00e9xico|website=El Financiero|language=es|access-date=29 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 February, a fourth case was detected and confirmed in the city of [[Torre\u00f3n]], in the state of [[Coahuila]], from a 20-year-old woman who traveled to Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milenio.com/estados/coronavirus-torreon-confirma-miguel-riquelme-caso-covid19|title=Coronavirus en M\u00e9xico: lo \u00faltimo del nuevo caso en Torre\u00f3n|website=milenio.com|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== March 2020 ===\n====March 1 to 15====\nOn 1 March, a fifth case was announced in [[Chiapas]] in a student who had just returned from Italy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://abcnoticias.mx/confirman-caso-de-coronavirus-en-chiapas/159656|title=Confirman caso de coronavirus en Chiapas|website=ABC Noticias|language=es|date=1 March 2020|accessdate=1 March 2020}}</ref> On 6 March, a sixth case was confirmed in the [[State of Mexico]] in a 71-year-old man who had returned from Italy on 21 February.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://politica.expansion.mx/mexico/2020/03/06/confirman-sexto-caso-de-coronavirus-en-el-estado-de-mexico|title=La Secretar\u00eda de Salud confirma el sexto caso de coronavirus en M\u00e9xico|date=7 March 2020|website=ADNPol\u00edtico|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nCOVID-19 was the topic of conversation at the meeting of the National Governors' Conference (Conago) held on 5 March 2020. In addition to governors from different states (or state health representatives), the directors of [[Instituto de Salud para el Bienestar|Instituto de Salud para el Bienestar (INSABI)]], [[Mexican Social Security Institute|IMSS]], and [[Institute for Social Security and Services for State Workers|ISSSTE]] participated.<ref name=conago>[https://www.elsoldecuernavaca.com.mx/local/analizan-gobernadores-situacion-del-coronavirus-4928720.html Governors analyze the situation of Coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} by Miriam Estrada, ''El Sol de Cuernavaca'', 5 Mar 2020, retrieved 16 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nOn March 6 during the first session of National Council of Health, [[Hugo L\u00f3pez-Gatell Ram\u00edrez]], one of the main strategists and spokespersons of Mexican Government on pandemics, led the first daily press conference on Covid-19.<ref name=nat_coun_health>{{Citation|title=Conferencia de prensa. Informe diario sobre coronavirus COVID-19 en M\u00e9xico. Secretar\u00eda de Salud|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZruOELSa7vA|language=en|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 7 March, a seventh case was also confirmed in [[Mexico City]] in a 46-year-old male who had previously had contact with another confirmed case in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reporteindigo.com/reporte/confirman-el-septimo-caso-de-coronavirus-en-mexico/|title=Se eleva a 7 el n\u00famero de casos confirmados de coronavirus en M\u00e9xico|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, an eighth case was reported in [[Puebla (state)|Puebla]], a 47-year-old German man who had returned from a business trip to Italy.<ref name=\"8 cases\">{{cite web |first1=|title=Puebla reporta primer caso positivo de coronavirus |url=https://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/nacional/proveedor-aleman-de-volkswagen-dio-positivo-a-coronavirus-secretaria-de-salud-de-puebla |website=El Financiero |publisher=Cuartoscuro |accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref> On the same date, 40 members of a dance company in Puebla, returning from a tour in Italy, were quarantined.<ref name=\"Ballet Ce Acatl\">{{cite web |last1=Arellano Garc\u00eda |first1=Cesar |title=Supervisar\u00e1n salud de ballet folkl\u00f3rico que vuelve de Italia |url=https://www.jornada.com.mx/ultimas/politica/2020/03/10/supervisaran-salud-de-ballet-folklorico-que-vuelve-de-italia-4751.html |website=La Jornada |publisher=La Jornada |accessdate=11 March 2020|date=10 March 2020 }}</ref> The [[Mexican Stock Exchange]] fell to a record low on 10 March due to fears of the coronavirus and because of falling oil prices. The [[Bank of Mexico|Bank of Mexico (Banxico)]] stepped in to prop up the value of the peso, which fell 14% to 22.929 per US dollar.<ref name=banixco>[https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/mexicos-stock-market-hits-record-low-over-coronavirus-crisis-and-collapsing-oil-prices Mexico's stock market hits record low over coronavirus crisis and collapsing oil prices] {{in lang|en}} ''El Universal'' (English), 10 March 2020</ref>\n\nOn 11 March, a ninth case was confirmed in the city of [[Monterrey]], [[Nuevo Le\u00f3n]]. A 57-year-old man, who had recently come back from a trip all across Europe, was placed under quarantine. The man, who has remained anonymous, came back from his trip a week before and had contact with eight other people who have also been placed under quarantine in their houses. The man has been confirmed to reside in the city of [[San Pedro Garza Garc\u00eda]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mty.telediario.mx/local/confirman-el-primer-caso-de-coronavirus-en-nuevo-leon|title=Confirman el primer caso de coronavirus en Nuevo Le\u00f3n|date=11 March 2020|website=Telediario Monterrey|language=es|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 March, Mexico announced it had a total of 15 confirmed cases, with new cases in [[Puebla]] and [[Durango]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/es-mx/noticias/mexico/ya-son-15-casos-de-coronavirus-en-m%C3%A9xico-hay-82-sospechosos/ar-BB117yPi?ocid=msedgntp|title=Ya son 15 casos de coronavirus en M\u00e9xico; hay 82 sospechosos|website=msn.com|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> A day later, senator {{ill|Samuel Garc\u00eda Sep\u00falveda|es}} accused the federal government of hiding the true number of confirmed cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sdpnoticias.com/local/nuevo-leon/gobierno-de-mexico-esconde-cifras-coronavirus-pandemia-samuel-garcia.html |title=Gobierno de M\u00e9xico ESCONDE cifras reales de CORONAVIRUS, acusa Samuel Garc\u00eda|last=SDPnoticias.com|website=SDPnoticias.com |language=spanish|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> After that, the government of Nuevo Le\u00f3n declared Phase 2. Mexico on 13 March had confirmed a total of 16 cases.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nOn 13 March, it was confirmed that the [[Mexican Stock Exchange]] Chairman, [[Jaime Ruiz Sacristan]], tested positive as an asymptomatic case.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://elfinanciero.com.mx/salud/da-positivo-de-coronavirus-el-presidente-de-la-bolsa-mexicana-jaime-ruiz-sacristan|title=Da positivo de coronavirus el presidente de la Bolsa Mexicana, Jaime Ruiz Sacrist\u00e1n|website=El Financiero|language=es|access-date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Later, the Secretariat of Health announced in press conference that the number of confirmed cases had risen to 26.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Espino |first1=Manuel |title=M\u00e9xico suma 26 casos positivos de coronavirus |url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/coronavirus-13-de-marzo-mexico-suma-26-casos-positivos-de-coronavirus |website=El Universal |date=14 March 2020 |publisher=El Universal, compa\u00f1\u00eda period\u00edstica Nacional |accessdate=14 March 2020 |ref=13 March 26 cases}}</ref> Several universities, including the [[National Autonomous University of Mexico|UNAM]] and [[Monterrey Institute of Technology and Higher Education|Tec de Monterrey]], switched to virtual classes. Authorities announced to be considering the cancellation of the ''Festival Internacional de Cine de Guadalajara''. In M\u00e9rida, the ''Tianguis Tur\u00edstico'' was postponed to September. Several major sporting events were also canceled.<ref name=cancelations>{{cite web |url=https://www.informador.mx/mexico/Suspenden-actividades-masivas-por-coronavirus-20200313-0020.html |title=Suspenden actividades masivas por coronavirus |trans-title=Massive Suspension of Activities Due to Coronavirus |language=Spanish |work=Informador.mx |date=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Student during Coronavirus in Mexico (cropped).jpg|thumb|upright|As part of the suspension of academic activities decreed by the SEP, students of all levels began taking classes online.]]\nOn 14 March, [[Fernando Petersen]], the secretary of health of the state of [[Jalisco]], confirmed the first two cases of COVID-19 were detected in Hospital Civil de [[Guadalajara]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.informador.mx/jalisco/Confirman-primeros-dos-casos-de-coronavirus-en-Jalisco-20200314-0052.html|title=Confirman primeros dos casos de coronavirus en Jalisco|website=El Informador: Noticias de Jalisco, M\u00e9xico, Deportes & Entretenimiento|language=es-ES|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Two new cases were confirmed in Nuevo Le\u00f3n, and the [[Secretariat of Public Education (Mexico)|Secretariat of Public Education (SEP)]] announced that all sporting and civic events in schools would be canceled.<ref name=sep>{{cite web |url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/coronavirus-sep-cancela-eventos-deportivos-y-civicos-en-escuelas |title=SEP cancela eventos deportivos y c\u00edvicos en escuelas por coronavirus |trans-title=SEP cancels sporting and civic events in schools due to coronavirus |language=Spanish |work=El Universal |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> The same day, the Secretariat of Education announced that Easter break, originally planned from 6 to 17 April, would be extended from 20 March to 20 April as a preventive measure.<ref name=\"Prevention Easter break in schools\">{{cite web |last1=Huizache |first1=Dolores |title=SEP anuncia que vacaciones de Semana Santa se adelantan por coronavirus |url=https://www.am.com.mx/noticias/SEP-anuncia-que-vacaciones-de-Semana-Santa-se-adelantan-por-coronavirus-20200314-0021.html |website=AM Mexico |publisher=EDITORIAL MARTINICA S.A. DE C.V. |accessdate=14 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Secretariat of Finance and Public Credit|Secretariat of Finance and Public Credit (SCHP)]] announced it was taking measures to prevent a 0.5% fall in [[Gross domestic product |gross domestic product (GDP)]].<ref name=schp>{{cite web |url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/cartera/listo-paquete-contraciclico-para-impulsar-economia |title=Por Covid-19, Hacienda tiene plan contrac\u00edclico |trans-title=Because of coronavirus, Treasury has a countercyclical package ready to boost economy |work=El Universal |date=14 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> Drugstores in [[Cuernavaca]] report shortages of masks, antibacterial gel, and other items.<ref>[https://www.elsoldecuernavaca.com.mx/local/comienzan-a-escasear-productos-por-covid-19-4971890.html Products start to be scarce due to COVID-19] {{in lang|es}} Jessica Arellano, ''El Sol de Cuernavaca'', 14 Mar 2020</ref> On the same day the [[Universidad Aut\u00f3noma de Nuevo Le\u00f3n|Autonomous University of Nuevo Leon, (UANL)]] (the country's third largest university in terms of student population) suspended classes for its more than 206,000 students starting on March 17 and ending on April 20.<ref name=uanl>{{cite web |last1=Garza|first1=Aracely|title= Universidad Aut\u00f3noma de NL suspende clases por Covid-19|language=es|trans-title=Autonomous University of NL suspends classes because of Covid-19|url= https://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/universidad-autonoma-de-nl-suspende-clases-por-covid-19/1369792 |website=Exc\u00e9lsior |date=14 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Garza|first1=Aracely|language=es|title= Suspende UANL clases virtuales |url= https://m.imagenradio.com.mx/suspende-uanl-clases-virtuales |website=Imagen Radio |date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nBusinessman Jos\u00e9 Kuri was reported in critical condition on 14 March after a trip to [[Vail, Colorado]], United States, although early reports of his death were false.<ref>{{cite web|website=El Sol de M\u00e9xico|title=El empresario Jos\u00e9 Kuri se encuentra en estado cr\u00edtico a causa de coronavirus|trans-title=The businessman Jos\u00e9 Kuri is in critical condition due to coronavirus|language=es|date=15 Mar 2020|accessdate=16 Mar 2020|author=EFE|url=https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/mexico/sociedad/el-empresario-jose-kuri-se-encuentra-en-estado-critico-a-causa-de-coronavirus-4974999.html}}</ref> As of 14 March, there have been 41 confirmed cases of [[COVID-19]] in Mexico.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://politica.expansion.mx/presidencia/2020/03/14/mexico-llega-a-41-casos-confirmados-de-coronavirus-con-155-sospechosos |title=M\u00e9xico llega a 41 casos confirmados de coronavirus, con 155 casos sospechosos |work=expansion.mx |language=Spanish |date=14 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020|trans-title=Mexico has 41 confirmed and 155 suspected cases of coronavirus}}</ref>\n\nThe 14 and 15 March ''[[Vive Latino|Festival Vive Latino]]'' (rock and Latin music) in Mexico City opened according to schedule, in spite of fears of contagion. Temperatures of the 70,000 people who attend each day were taken at the door and anti-bacterial gel was widely distributed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.infobae.com/america/mexico/2020/03/14/el-coronavirus-avanza-apresurado-en-mexico-y-las-pruebas-de-detencion-cuestan-hasta-18000-pesos/ |title=El coronavirus avanza apresurado en M\u00e9xico y las pruebas de detecci\u00f3n cuestan hasta 18,000 pesos |trans-title=Coronavirus rushes ahead in Mexico and screening tests cost up to 18,000 pesos |language=Spanish |work=Infobae |date=14 March 2020 |access-date=16 March 2020}}</ref> Organizers said that the ''[[Passion Play of Iztapalapa]]'' would continue as scheduled in Holy Week. Tito Dom\u00ednguez, vice president of the organizing committee, noted that a miracle had saved Iztapalapa during the [[Cholera outbreaks and pandemics|cholera outbreak in 1833]].<ref>[https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/metropoli/cdmx/pasion-de-cristo-en-iztapalapa-podria-cancelarse-debido-al-covid-19-coronavirus-claudia-sheinbaum-iglesia-catolica-pasion-de-cristo-coronavirus-covid-19-mexico-4974131.html Coronavirus will not stop the Stations of the Cross in Iztapalapa: organizing committee] {{in lang|es}} Maleny Navarro, ''El Sol de M\u00e9xico''. 15 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, Head of Government [[Claudia Sheinbaum]] stated that Mexico City expects to spend an extra MXN $100 million (US$4.4 million) to prevent the spread of COVID-19.<ref name=sheinbaum>[https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/metropoli/cdmx/preven-gasto-de-100-mdp-extra-para-combatir-coronavirus-en-cdmx-4974203.html Expenditure of 100 extra mp to prevent coronavirus in CDMX] {{in lang|es}} by Maleny Navarro, ''El Sol de M\u00e9xico'', 15 Mar 2020</ref> The first confirmed case of coronavirus in [[Acapulco]], Guerrero, was reported.<ref>[https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/republica/sociedad/confirman-primer-caso-de-covid-19-en-guerrero-coronavirus-4974870.html Confirman primer caso de Covid-19 en Guerrero] {{in lang|es}} by Jos\u00e9 Francisco Zorroza, ''El Sol de Acapulco'', 15 Mar 2020</ref> [[Quer\u00e9taro]] reported two new cases, bringing the total to six.<ref>[https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/mundo/coronavirus-covid-19/nota/1932576/0/aumenta-seis-el-numero-de-casos-de-coronavirus-en-queretaro#info Queretaro increases the number of coronavirus cases to six] {{in lang|es}} by Francisco Floes Hernndez, El Universal, 15 Mar 2020</ref> [[Nuevo Leon]] reported its fifth case.<ref>[https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/estados/coronavirus-suman-5-casos-positivos-en-nuevo-leon Coronavirus: 5 positive cases in Nuevo Leon] {{in lang|es}} by David Carrizales, 15 Mar 2020</ref> The [[Norte\u00f1o (music)|Norte\u00f1o]] group Los Tres Tristes Tigres released a [[corrido|song]] on 15 March titled \"El corrido del coronavirus\".<ref>[https://www.elsoldecuernavaca.com.mx/doble-via/virales/video-el-pin-coronavirus-a-todos-saco-de-quicio-el-nuevo-corrido-de-los-los-tres-tristes-tigres-covid19-covid-19-salud-humor-canciones-musica-nortea-comparas-de-panico-papel-de-bano-tom-hanks-amlo-disneyland-viral-corrido-4974778.html Los Tres Tristes Tigres compose \"El corrido del coronavirus\"] {{in lang|es}} by Miguel Ceballos, ''El Sol de Puebla'', 15 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n====March 16 to 22====\nAs of 16 March, President L\u00f3pez Obrador continued to downplay the impact of coronavirus. \"Pandemics ... won't do anything to us,\" and accused the press and the opposition for its reportage.<ref>[https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-03-19/as-mexican-peso-collapses-over-coronavirus-threat-criticism-falls-on-president-lopez-obrador \"As Mexican peso collapses over coronavirus threat, criticism falls on president Lopez Obrador\" Los Angeles Times 2020/03/20] accessed 20 March 2020</ref>  On 16 March, lawyer Marco Antonio del Toro petitioned the federal courts to cease all but essential activities for a period of 30 to 40 days because of the coronavirus outbreak.<ref>[https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/mexico/piden-suspender-actividades-en-juzgados-y-tribunales-por-coronavirus-covid-19-mexico-contagios-pandemia-epidemia-4976721.html Suspension of judicial activities for coronavirus requested] {{in lang|es}} Manrique Gandaria, ''El Sol de M\u00e9xico'', 16 Mar 2020</ref> The total of confirmed cases reached 82.<ref name=\"Marc 16 confirmed cases\">{{cite web |last1=Castillo Torres |first1=Gustavo |title=Coronavirus en M\u00e9xico: 82 casos confirmados; s\u00f3lo 2% est\u00e1n graves |url=https://www.unotv.com/noticias/portal/nacional/detalle/coronavirus-mexico-82-casos-confirmados-solo-2-estan-graves-785052/ |website=UnoTV |date=17 March 2020 |publisher=AMX Contenido S.A. de C.V. |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> The [[Universidad Aut\u00f3noma del Estado de Morelos|Autonomous University of the State of Morelos, (UAEM)]] suspended classes for its 22,000 students.<ref name=uaem>[https://www.milenio.com/estados/uaem-suspende-clases-por-coronavirus UAEM suspends classes due to coronavirus] {{in lang|es}} by David Monroy, ''Milenio'', 16 Mar 2020</ref> A diplomatic incident arose between the governments of Mexico and [[El Salvador]], concerning 12 Salvadorean citizens wearing face masks on a plane departing from Mexico City to San Salvador. [[Nayib Bukele]], president of El Salvador denounced as \"irresponsible\" that they were allowed to board the plane along with other passengers and offered to send a plane to transport them without contact with other people. The claim was supported by [[Avianca]] airline<ref>{{cite web |url=https://twitter.com/AviancaCAM/status/1239696214469337088|title=Agradecemos al Presidente del El Salvador @nayibbukele por darnos la informaci\u00f3n y alertarnos sobre los pacientes con COVID-19 intentando abordar el vuelo de Avianca #431 proveniente de la Ciudad de M\u00e9xico hacia El Salvador el d\u00eda 16 de Marzo de 2020.|last=Centroam\u00e9rica|first=Avianca|date=2020-03-16|website=@AviancaCAM|language=es|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> while the Mexican government said that there were no reasons to assume that they were positive for COVID-19. Eventually, the flight was cancelled. [[Marcelo Ebrard]], head of Foreign Affairs announced after negative results of COVID tests of that Salvadorean passengers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.milenio.com/politica/coronavirus-llama-ebrard-nayib-bukele-aclarar-fuentes-pasajeros|title=Coronavirus: llama Ebrard a Nayib Bukele aclarar fuentes de pasajeros|website=milenio.com|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March, 11 new cases were confirmed, raising the national total to 93, with [[Campeche]] being the only state with no confirmed cases.<ref name=\"Confirmed cases 17 March\">{{cite web |last1=Milenio Digital |title=Secretar\u00eda de Salud reporta 93 casos de coronavirus en M\u00e9xico; hay 206 sospechosos |url=https://www.milenio.com/politica/coronavirus-mexico-93-casos-confirmados-206-sospechosos |website=Milenio.com |publisher=Milenio Diario, S.A de C.V |accessdate=18 March 2020}}</ref> Mexico's limited response, including allowing a large concert and the women's soccer championship, as well as a lack of testing, have been criticized. Critics note that president [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador|L\u00f3pez Obrador]] does not practice social distancing but continues to greet large crowds, and the borders have not been closed. Of particular concern is the health of thousands of migrants in temporary camps along the border with the United States. The former national commissioner for influenza in Mexico during the [[2009 flu pandemic]], Alejandro Mac\u00edas, said the problem is compounded by the fact that Mexico lacks sufficient intensive care unit beds, medical care workers and ventilators.<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/mexico-government-pressure-coronavirus-response-200316210710906.html Mexico's government under pressure over coronavirus response] by Jihan Abdalla, Al Jazeera, 17 March 2020  [https://thehill.com/latino/488100-mexico-under-international-criticism-for-coronavirus-response Mexico under international criticism for coronavirus response] BY RAFAEL BERNAL, The Hill, 18 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nOn 18 March, 25 more cases were confirmed raising the total to 118 cases and 314 suspected cases.<ref name=\"18march\">{{cite web |url=https://heraldodemexico.com.mx/pais/coronavirus-mexico-casos-confirmados-positivos-covid19-hoy-miercoles-18-marzo-secretaria-salud/|title= Coronavirus en M\u00e9xico: Hay 118 casos confirmados de COVID-19|date=March 18, 2020|language=es|work=El Heraldo de M\u00e9xico}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.milenio.com/politica/coronavirus-mexico-118-casos-confirmados-314-sospechosos |title= Confirman 118 casos de coronavirus en M\u00e9xico; hay 314 sospechosos |date=March 18, 2020|language=es|work=Milenio}}</ref> Authorities in Jalisco are concerned about a group of 400 people who recently returned from [[Vail, Colorado]]; 40 people have symptoms of COVID-19.<ref>[https://www.milenio.com/internacional/coronavirus-mexico-18-marzo-noticias-hora-casos-vivo Coronavirus en M\u00e9xico, noticias de \u00faltima hora] Milenio, 18 Mar 2020</ref><ref>[https://www.latimes.com/world-nation/story/2020-03-20/some-of-mexicos-wealthiest-residents-went-to-colorado-to-ski-they-brought-home-coronavirus \"Some of Mexico's Wealthiest Residents Went to Colorado to Ski and Brought Home Coronavirus\". Los Angeles Times 2020/03/20] accessed 20 March 2020.</ref> The same day, the Mexican government announced that they will allocate 3.5 billion pesos ({{abbr|approx.|approximately}} 146 million US dollars{{refn|on March 18}}) to buy medical and laboratory equipment, washing and disinfection material, and ventilators.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/coronavirus-18-de-marzo-aumentan-118-los-casos-confirmados-de-coronavirus-en-mexico |title= AUMENTAN A 118 LOS CASOS CONFIRMADOS DE CORONAVIRUS EN M\u00c9XICO |date=March 18, 2020|language=es|work=El Universal}}</ref> During the night  the first COVID-19 related death in the country was confirmed, a 41-year-old man without a travel history outside the country who was hospitalized at the National Institute of Respiratory Diseases (INER).<ref name=\"death1\">{{cite web|url= https://www.jornada.com.mx/ultimas/politica/2020/03/18/fallece-victima-de-covid-19-en-el-iner-9638.html |title= Fallece primera v\u00edctima de Covid-19 en el INER |date=March 18, 2020|language=es|work=[[La Jornada]]}}</ref> Colima Governor [[Jos\u00e9 Ignacio Peralta]] declared a state of emergency after the state's first case, a man who had recently returned from Germany, was reported on 17 March.<ref>[https://www.informador.mx/mexico/Colima-declara-emergencia-por-COVID-19-20200318-0134.html Colima declara emergencia por COVID-19] El Informador, 18 Mar 2020</ref> [[Ford Motor Company|Ford]], [[Honda]], and [[Audi]] closed their manufacturing plants in Mexico.<ref name=ford>{{cite news|author=<!-- not stated -->|title=Empresas automotrices suspenden producci\u00f3n en M\u00e9xico|language=es |url=https://www.informador.mx/economia/Empresas-automotrices-suspenden-produccion-en-Mexico-20200318-0114.html|website=El Informador|date=March 18, 2020|access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Hundreds of hotel employees in [[Canc\u00fan]] were fired.<ref name=cancun>[https://laverdadnoticias.com/quintanaroo/Coronavirus-Cancun-Comenzaron-los-despidos-en-los-hoteles-20200318-0006.html Coronavirus Canc\u00fan: Comenzaron los despidos en los hoteles] {{in lang|es}} by Angel Bal\u00e1n, La Verdad, 18 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nAuthorities announced on 18 March that they were looking for hundreds of citizens who may be carriers of the coronavirus, especially in the states of Puebla, Jalisco, Aguascalientes, and Guerrero. A four-member family in Puebla who had traveled to the United States kept their symptoms secret as they visited neighbors in La Vista and visited a gym. Authorities were still trying to track down the 400 people in Jalisco and Nayarit who recently traveled to Vail, Colorado. In Aguascalientes they were looking to track down passengers of Flight 2638 who traveled with a sick man from New York. The [[Autonomous University of Guerrero|Autonomous University of Guerrero (UAGRO)]] in Chilpancingo closed after a female student tested positive for the virus. The Technical Institute of Guerrero and the state Supreme Court also closed.<ref name=look>[https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/mexican-authorities-are-tracking-hundreds-possible-covid-19-carriers Mexican authorities are tracking hundreds of possible Covid 19 carriers] {{in lang|en}} by David Carrizales, 19 Mar 2020</ref>\n\n[[Morelos]] had its first two confirmed cases on 19 March\u2014a 54-year-old woman from [[Cuautla, Morelos|Cuautla]] and a 37-year-old man from [[Cuernavaca]].<ref>[https://www.diariodemorelos.com/noticias/urgente-confirmados-ya-2-casos-de-coronavirus-en-morelos URGENTE: CONFIRMADOS YA 2 CASOS DE CORONAVIRUS COVID19 EN MORELOS] {{in lang|es}} ''Diario de Morelos'', 19 Mar 2020</ref> [[Sinaloa]] announced its third case, a 20-year-old woman from [[Culiac\u00e1n]].<ref>[https://www.debate.com.mx/culiacan/Confirman-el-tercer-caso-de-coronavirus-en-Sinaloa-20200319-0157.html Confirman el tercer caso de coronavirus en Sinaloa] {{in lang|es}} by FRANCISCO CASTRO, ''Debate'', 19 Mar 2020</ref>\n\nU.S Secretary of State [[Mike Pompeo]] announced on 20 March there would be restrictions on travel across the [[Mexico\u2013United States border]]. Said restrictions would not apply to cargo.<ref name=pompeo>{{cite web|website=Deadline|title=President Donald Trump Goes Off On NBC News Reporter, Comcast During Coronavirus Press Briefing|date=March 20, 2020|author=Ted Johnson|url=https://deadline.com/2020/03/u-s-and-mexico-to-restrict-non-essential-travel-on-southern-border-mike-pompeo-warns-of-disinformation-1202888618/|language=en}}</ref> The [[Instituto Nacional de Antropolog\u00eda e Historia|National Institute of Anthropology and History (INAH)]] announced that the archaeological zones [[Teotihuac\u00e1n]], [[Xochicalco]], and [[El Tepozteco]] will be closed on 21\u201322 March. [[Chich\u00e9n Itz\u00e1]] will close indefinitely starting 21 March. [[Guachimontones]] will close 21, 22, and 23 March. [[Palenque]], [[Tula (Mesoamerican site)|Tula]] and [[Tingambato]] will close 21 March.<ref name=inah>[https://launion.com.mx/morelos/zona-sur/noticias/157226-cerraran-las-zonas-arqueologicas-de-xochicalco-y-tepoztlan.html?utm_medium=Social&utm_source=Facebook&fbclid=IwAR3J791dkyCGjqbxVpYJPQhZ2i6AJi6PvA9ylt65t0LS1hN20dxAET1jjoA#Echobox=1584718003 Cerrar\u00e1n las zonas arqueol\u00f3gicas de Xochicalco y Tepoztl\u00e1n] {{in lang|es}} La Union de Morelos, 20 Mar 2020</ref> [[Alsea (company)|Alsea]], which operates restaurants such as Starbucks, VIPS, and Domino's Pizza offered its employees unpaid leave.<ref name=alsea>[https://www.diariodemorelos.com/noticias/starbucks-y-vips-ofrecen-empleados-dejar-de-trabajar-un-mes-sin-goce-de-sueldo-por-covid-19?fbclid=IwAR1bHSJdt5O5D8QECH-3Yk547e2nKDlW-eZtwO870EFtZHBUAlkQOjOjr4s Starbucks y VIPs ofrecen a empleados dejar de trabajar un mes sin goce de sueldo, por COVID-19] {{in lang|es}} El Diario de Morelos, 20 Mar 2020</ref> Mayor Juanita Romero (PAN) of [[Nacozari de Garc\u00eda Municipality]], Sonora, declares a curfew, in effect until 20 April. Only the [[President of Mexico]] has the legal authority to declare such a declaration.<ref name=curfew>[https://www.proceso.com.mx/622668/nacozari-toque-de-queda Alcaldesa de Nacozari ordena toque de queda, facultad exclusiva del presidente] {{in lang|es}} by Milton Martinez, Proceso, 20 Mar 2020</ref> During the night, 38 more cases and one more death were confirmed raising the total to 203 cases, 2 deaths, and 606 suspected cases.<ref name=\"20march\">{{cite web |url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/seguridad/coronavirus-20-de-marzo-mexico-confirma-dos-muertos-por-covid-19-suma-203-casos |title= M\u00c9XICO CONFIRMA DOS MUERTOS POR CORONAVIRUS; SUMA 203 CASOS POSITIVOS |date=March 20, 2020|language=es|work=El Universal |author1= Alexis Ortiz |author2= Perla Miranda }}</ref>\n\nOn March 21 the total confirmed cases were 251.<ref name=\"21march\">{{cite web |url= https://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/sube-a-251-el-numero-de-contagiados-de-coronavirus-en-mexico/1371282 |title= Sube a 251 el n\u00famero de contagiados de coronavirus en M\u00e9xico |date=March 21, 2020|language=es|work=Exc\u00e9lsior |author1= Redacci\u00f3n}}</ref> One day later 65 more cases were confirmed and the total of suspected cases grew to 793.<ref name=\"22march\">{{cite web |url= https://www.eleconomista.com.mx/politica/Cifra-de-casos-confirmados-de-coronavirus-en-Mexico-sube-a-316-Secretaria-de-Salud-20200322-0050.html |title= Con 316 casos confirmados, sigue fase de transici\u00f3n |date=March 22, 2020|language=es|work=El Economista |author1= Rolando Ramos}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, bars, nightclubs, movie theaters, and museums were closed in Mexico City.<ref name=bars>[https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/mexico-city-closes-museums-bars-nightclubs-and-movie-theaters-bid-halt-coronavirus-spread Mexico City closes museums, bars, nightclubs, and movie theaters in a bid to halt coronavirus spread] {{in lang|en}} El Universal, 23 March 2020</ref> Governor [[Enrique Alfaro Ram\u00edrez]] of Jalisco announced that beginning Thursday, 26 March, Jalisco and seven other states in the [[Baj\u00edo]] and western Mexico will block flights from areas such as [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in California|California]] that have a high rate of coronavirus. He also said that they will purchase 25,000 testing kits.<ref name=planes>[https://www.debate.com.mx/guadalajara/Jalisco-bloquearia-vuelos-y-compra-25-mil-pruebas-de-COVID-19-20200323-0224.html Jalisco will block flights and buy 25 thousand tests of COVID-19] {{in lang|es}} by CAROLINA SOL\u00cdS, Debate, 23 March</ref>\n\n====March 23 to 31====\n[[File:Acceso de personas con s\u00edntomas de enfermedades respiratorias al Instituto Nacional de Ciencias M\u00e9dicas y Nutrici\u00f3n Salvador Zubir\u00e1n.jpg|thumbnail|right|People entering a special respiratory illness symptom assessment area at the [[Salvador Zubir\u00e1n National Institute of Health Sciences and Nutrition|Instituto Nacional de Ciencias M\u00e9dicas y Nutrici\u00f3n Salvador Zubir\u00e1n]], Mexico City. The hospital was converted into a special care area for COVID patients.]]\n\nMexico entered Phase 2 of the coronavirus pandemic on March 23, according to the [[World Health Organization]], with 367 confirmed cases. Phase 2 includes cases where the sick individuals did not have direct contact with someone who had recently been in another country.<ref name=who>{{cite web |url= https://www.forbes.com.mx/noticias-salud-mexico-fase-2-pandemia-por-coronavirus-oms/ |title= M\u00e9xico, en Fase 2 de pandemia por Coronavirus: OMS |language=es |date= March 23, 2020 |website= Forbes M\u00e9xico}}</ref> On the same day it was confirmed that two more people died from COVID-19, raising the total to 4 reported deaths.<ref name=\"23march\">{{cite web |url= https://www.sdpnoticias.com/nacional/muertos-casos-confirmados-de-coronavirus-en-mexico-cifras-23-de-marzo.html |title= Suman 4 muertos por Covid-19 en M\u00e9xico; confirman 367 casos de contagio |date=March 23, 2020|language=es|work=SDP Noticias |author1= Alexis Pav\u00f3n}}</ref> That day was announced on President L\u00f3pez Obrador's daily press conference the realization of the National Campaign of Healthy Distancing ({{ill|Jornada Nacional de Sana Distancia|lt=|es||WD=}}) a national program of non-pharmaceutical measures based on [[social distancing]] among the behavioral changes suggested by WHO as hand washing, covering one's mouth when coughing, maintaining distance from other people, and monitoring and [[self-isolation]] for people who suspect they are infected.<ref name=social>{{cite web |url=https://www.jornada.com.mx/ultimas/politica/2020/03/23/comienza-la-jornada-nacional-de-sana-distancia-1056.html|title=Comienza la Jornada Nacional de Sana Distancia|last=L|first=Ang\u00e9lica Enciso|date=2020-03-23|work=[[La Jornada]]|language=es|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref> On that same day in the daily press conference was announced also a media campaign led by \"Susana Distancia\" (wordplay of a healthy distance) a fictional female [[superhero]] aiming to promote social distancing into the people.<ref name=susana>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dw.com/en/mexican-superhero-susana-distancia-swoops-in-to-promote-social-distancing/a-52873960|title=Mexican superhero Susana Distancia swoops in to promote social distancing|last=Martyr|first=Kate|work=[[Deutsche Welle]]|language=en-GB|date=21 March 2020|access-date=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nMeanwhile, a [[Warren Mitofsky|Mitofsky poll]] showed that 63% of Mexicans feared contracting Covid-19 and 25.5% feared dying from it. 28% said they were not willing to stay in their homes. 38.6% believed President L\u00f3pez Obrador was handling the situation well, and 37% disapproved.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.infobae.com/america/mexico/2020/03/23/coronavirus-en-mexico-crece-el-descontento-con-el-gobierno-de-amlo-y-el-temor-al-contagio/ |title= Coronavirus en M\u00e9xico: crece el descontento con el gobierno de AMLO y el temor al contagio |language=es |date= March 23, 2020 |website= Infobae}}</ref> Access to supermarkets in [[Coahuila]] was limited to one person per family, and the temperature of that person was taken before entering. The same rule applies to drugstores and convenience stores in the state, which has 12 confirmed cases of Covid-19.<ref name=supermarket>{{cite web |url= https://mvsnoticias.com/noticias/estados/solo-una-persona-por-familia-podra-acceder-a-supermercados-en-coahuila/ |title= Solo una persona por familia podr\u00e1 acceder a supermercados en Coahuila |author= Notimex  |language=es |date= March 23, 2020 |website= MVS Noticias}}</ref>\n\nAt his morning news conference on March 24, President [[Andr\u00e9s Manuel L\u00f3pez Obrador|L\u00f3pez Obrador]] announced that Mexico entered Phase 2 of the coronavirus pandemic, in effect until April 30. Gatherings of more than 100 people are prohibited, and both the army and the navy will participate. The armed forces have 1,738 doctors, 1,727 nurses, 100 intensive therapy ambulances, and 400 ambulances for transportation. The military also has 5 high specialty hospitals, 36 second-level hospitals, and 272 first-level hospitals with 262 health brigades across the country. Four deaths, 367 confirmed cases, and 826 suspected cases of COVID-19 have been reported.<ref name=amlo_phase2>{{cite web |url= https://www.unotv.com/noticias/portal/nacional/detalle/coronavirus-en-mexico-amlo-anuncia-plan-de-proteccion-contra-covid-19-776166/ |title= M\u00e9xico inicia fase 2 por coronavirus; toma estas medidas |author=  |language=es |date= March 24, 2020 |website= UNO TV}}</ref> The first Mexican woman died from COVID-19 on March 24, raising the total to 5 reported deaths in the country.<ref name=\"death5\">{{cite web|url= https://www.radioformula.com.mx/noticias/mexico/20200324/5-muertos-por-coronavirus-covid-19-mexico-martha-mujer-hospital-angeles-hoy/| title= Muere la primera mujer por Coronavirus en M\u00e9xico; van 5 decesos|author=Diego Santiago|work=Grupo F\u00f3rmula|date= March 24, 2020}}</ref> On the same day 405 total cases of COVID-19 were confirmed.<ref name=\"24march\">{{cite web|url= https://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/nacional/suman-5-decesos-por-coronavirus-en-mexico-suben-a-405-los-casos-confirmados/|title= Suman 5 decesos por coronavirus en M\u00e9xico; suben a 405 los casos confirmados |author= Redacci\u00f3n |work=El Financiero|date= March 24, 2020|language=es}}</ref>\n\nOn March 25, Dr. Abelardo \u00c1vila, researcher at the [[Salvador Zubir\u00e1n National Institute of Health Sciences and Nutrition]] warned that Mexico was particularly vulnerable to the COVID-19 pandemic because of underlying chronic illnesses such as [[obesity]], [[diabetes]], and [[hypertension]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.infobae.com/america/mexico/2020/03/25/mexico-es-mas-vulnerable-al-coronavirus-por-prevalencia-de-enfermedades-cronicas-dijeron-especialistas/ |title= M\u00e9xico es m\u00e1s vulnerable al coronavirus por prevalencia de enfermedades cr\u00f3nicas, dijeron especialistas |author=  |language=es |date= March 25, 2020 |website= Infobae}}</ref> Also on 25 March President L\u00f3pez Obrador ordered the [[Mexican Air Force]] to rescue Mexicans trapped in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Argentina|Argentina]].<ref name=airforce>[https://www.infobae.com/america/mexico/2020/03/25/lopez-obrador-ordeno-a-la-fuera-aerea-trasladar-a-su-pais-a-argentinos-varados-en-mexico-por-el-coronavirus-y-repatriar-a-connacionales/ L\u00f3pez Obrador orden\u00f3 a la Fuerza A\u00e9rea una misi\u00f3n de rescate de mexicanos y argentinos varados por coronavirus]{{in lang|es}} Infobae, 25 Mar 2020</ref> In Baja California, [[PROFECO]] closed two businesses in Tijuana for price-gouging.<ref name=profecobc>{{cite web |url= http://www.hiptex.com.mx/noticias/15232/clausura-profeco-dos-comercios-por-subir-precios-de-productos-basicos |title= Clausura Profeco dos comercios por subir precios de productos b\u00e1sicos |author=  |language=es |date= March 25, 2020 |website= Hiptex}}</ref> In Mexico City, Head of Government [[Claudia Sheinbaum]] announced financial support for families and micro industries affected by the pandemic. She also announced that automobile verification would be suspended through April 19. Movie theaters, bars, nightclubs, gyms, and other entertainment centers will remain closed.<ref name=finsupport>{{cite web |url= https://www.infobae.com/america/mexico/2020/03/25/creditos-para-micronegocios-y-500-pesos-para-ninos-las-acciones-de-cdmx-para-apoyar-a-la-poblacion-durante-emergencia-por-coronavirus/ |title= Cr\u00e9ditos para micronegocios y 500 pesos para ni\u00f1os: las acciones de CDMX para apoyar a la poblaci\u00f3n durante emergencia por coronavirus |author=  |language=es |date= March 25, 2020 |website= Infobae}}</ref> The same day it was reported that one man died from COVID-19 in [[San Luis Potos\u00ed]], raising the total to 6 reported deaths in Mexico and 475 confirmed cases.<ref name=\"death6\">{{cite web|author= Roc\u00edo L\u00f3pez |title= Muere hombre en San Luis Potos\u00ed por COVID-19; van 6 en M\u00e9xico|url= https://www.milenio.com/estados/coronavirus-san-luis-potosi-reportan-muerto-covid-19 |website=Milenio|date=March 25, 2020|language=es}}</ref><ref name=\"25march\">{{cite web|author= Redacci\u00f3n Digital |title= Van 6 muertes en M\u00e9xico por COVID-19; casos positivos ascienden a 475 |url= https://heraldodemexico.com.mx/pais/coronavirus-mexico-muertes-covid19-casos-positivos-contagios-hoy-miercoles-25-marzo-2020-fase-dos-secretaria-salud/ |website=El Heraldo de M\u00e9xico|date=March 25, 2020|language=es}}</ref> Governor [[Miguel Barbosa Huerta]] ([[National Regeneration Movement|Morena]]) claimed that only the wealthy were at risk, since the poor are immune to COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/26/americas/mexico-coronavirus-luis-miguel-barbosa-intl/index.html |title= Mexican governor claims poor people are 'immune' from coronavirus |author1= Matt Rivers|author2= Natalie Gall\u00f3n |author3= CNN|language=en |date= March 26, 2020 |website= CNN}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, President L\u00f3pez Obrador revealed he asked the [[G20]] to ensure that wealthy countries cannot take control of the world's medical supplies. He also called for assurances that borders would not be closed to commerce and that [[tariff]]s would not be unilaterally increased. Lastly, he called for an end to racism and discrimination.<ref name=g20>{{cite web |url= https://www.tvazteca.com/aztecanoticias/politica/notas/pide-amlo-en-g-20-que-onu-controle-comercio-de-medicamentos-de-covid-19 |title= Pide AMLO en G-20 que ONU controle comercio de medicamentos de COVID-19 |author= |language=es |date= March 26, 2020 |website= TV Azteca}}</ref> The Mexican government announced it would suspend most sectors' activities starting March 26 until April 19, with the exception of health and energy sectors, the oil industry; and public services such as water supply, waste management and public safety.<ref name=suspend_govt>{{cite news|last=Rueda |first=Rivelino|title=A partir de hoy para gobierno actividades|url=https://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/nacional/a-partir-de-hoy-para-gobierno-actividades|work=El Financiero|date=March 26, 2020|access-date=March 26, 2020|language=es}}</ref> Protesters in [[Sonora]] insisted that the government limit border crossings with the United States.<ref name=border>{{cite web |url= https://news.yahoo.com/mexicans-demand-crackdown-americans-crossing-154146270.html |title= Coronavirus: Mexicans demand crackdown on Americans crossing the border |author= BBC |language=en |date= March 26, 2020 |website= Yahoo! News}}</ref> [[Chihuahua (state)|Chihuahua]] announced that \u201cin the next few days\u201d it will start to quarantine migrants who are returned to the [[Ciudad Ju\u00e1rez]] border crossing. About 65 migrants are deported from [[El Paso, Texas]] daily, about 5,200 this year.<ref name=chi>{{cite web |url= https://apnews.com/cf7b480e9e1dc84d1970665120302d9e |title= Mexican border city to quarantine returning migrants |author= |language=en |date= March 26, 2020 |website= AP}}</ref> Two more deaths were reported on this day; 585 cases were confirmed, and there were 2,156 suspected cases.<ref name=\"26march\">{{cite web|url= https://www.radioformula.com.mx/noticias/mexico/20200326/585-casos-coronavirus-en-mexico-salud-federal-hoy-ultimas-noticias-26-de-marzo/amp/ | title= Ya hay 585 casos confirmados de coronavirus en M\u00e9xico |author=Diego Santiago|work=Grupo F\u00f3rmula|date= March 26, 2020}}</ref> [[Human Rights Watch]] accused AMLO of endangering lives by not providing accurate information about the pandemic.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.hrw.org/news/2020/03/26/mexico-mexicans-need-accurate-covid-19-information |title= Mexico: Mexicans Need Accurate COVID-19 Information |author= |language=en |date= March 26, 2020 |website= Human Rights Watch}}</ref> The government of San Luis Potosi reported the death of a 57-year-old man on March 26, bringing the total number of deaths in the country to nine. He had hypertension and diabetes.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://mexico.as.com/mexico/2020/03/27/tikitakas/1585280194_313276.html  |title= Coronavirus: San Luis confirma la segunda muerte en el estado |author= |language=es |date= March 26, 2020 |website= Mexico AS}}</ref> Citizens of [[Nogales, Sonora]] block border crossing from [[Nogales, Arizona]] in order to prevent the entrance of individuals with the virus infection and to prevent shortages of food, bottled water, toilet paper and cleaning supplies in local stores.<ref name=nogales>{{cite web |url= https://www.univision.com/noticias/america-latina/el-mundo-al-reves-mexicanos-bloquean-frontera-para-que-no-entren-a-su-pais-estadounidenses-contagiados-por-el-covid-19 |title= Mexicanos bloquean frontera para que no entren a su pa\u00eds estadounidenses contagiados por el COVID-19 |author= Isaias Alvarado |language=es |date= March 26, 2020 |website= Univision Noticias}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the Secretary of Health, a plurality of the 585 people infected in Mexico, 70, are between 30 and 34 years old. People over 65 are second, followed by those 25 to 29 and 45 to 49. The states with the most incidents are Mexico City (83), Jalisco (64) and Nuevo Leon (57).<ref>{{cite web |url= https://mexico.as.com/mexico/2020/03/27/tikitakas/1585334510_686136.html |title= De 30 a 34, la media de edad de contagios por coronavirus COVID-19 en M\u00e9xico |author= |language=es |date= March 27, 2020 |website= Mexico AS}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27 the federal government bought 5,000 ventilators from China as the government prepares for Phase 3 of the pandemic.<ref name=ventilator /> The total confirmed cases rose to 717; twelve deaths were reported, and there were 2,475 suspected cases.<ref name=\"27march\">{{cite web|url= https://politico.mx/minuta-politica/minuta-politica-gobierno-federal/ssa-presentar%C3%A1-informe-diario-sobre-coronavirus-en-m%C3%A9xico/ | title= Ssa: 717 casos confirmados de coronavirus y 2 mil 475 sospechosos |language=es |author=Pol\u00edtico MX|work=Pol\u00edtico.mx|date= March 27, 2020}}</ref> [[PROFECO]] (Office of the Federal Prosecutor for the Consumer) said it will fine merchants who unfairly raise the prices on household goods.<ref name=fine>{{cite web |url= https://www.adn40.mx/noticia/mexico/notas/2020-03-27-08-26/multa-de-hasta-3-millones-a-quien-suba-el-precio-de-la-canasta-basica |title= Multa de hasta 3 millones a quien suba el precio de la canasta b\u00e1sica |author= Redacci\u00f3n ADN40|language=es |date= March 27, 2020 |website= ADN40}}</ref> The governors of [[Governor of Nuevo Le\u00f3n|Nuevo Le\u00f3n]], [[Governor of Tamaulipas|Tamaulipas]] and [[Governor of Coahuila|Coahuila]] asked the federal government to close the border with [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|the United States]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.sinembargo.mx/27-03-2020/3756883 |title= Gobiernos de Coahuila, Nuevo Le\u00f3n y Tamaulipas piden a AMLO cerrar la frontera con EU por COVID-19 |author= Redacci\u00f3n/ Sin Embargo|language=es |date= March 27, 2020 |website= Sin Embargo}}</ref> \n\nOn March 28, Governor [[Omar Fayad]] of [[Hidalgo (state)|Hidalgo]] announced in a tweet that he tested positive for the virus and said that he was in self-quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/salud/omar-fayad-gobernador-de-hidalgo-da-positivo-a-covid-19 | title= Omar Fayad, gobernador de Hidalgo, da positivo a COVID-19 |author=Redacci\u00f3n |work=El Financiero|language=es |date= March 28, 2020}}</ref> The [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Mexico]] said services should be held indoors with no more than twenty people present. They may cancel all [[Holy Week in Mexico|Holy Week]] celebrations if things do not improve.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.milenio.com/politica/arquidiocesis-celebracion-semana-santa-puerta-cerrada |title= Arquidi\u00f3cesis pide que celebraciones de Semana Santa sean a puerta cerrada |author= Elia Castillo|language=es |date= March 28, 2020 |website= Milenio}}</ref> In the evening the Secretariat of Health reported 131 new confirmed cases and four more deaths, raising the total to 848 confirmed cases and 16 deaths.<ref name=\"28march\">{{cite web|url= https://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/sube-a-848-los-contagiados-de-coronavirus-en-mexico/1372746 | title= Sube a 848 los contagiados de coronavirus en M\u00e9xico |author=Redacci\u00f3n |work=Exc\u00e9lsior|language=es|date= March 28, 2020}}</ref> Governor [[Cuauht\u00e9moc Blanco]] of Morelos announced the seventh case and first death due to COVID-19 in the state, a 37-year-old man who had recently traveled to the United States.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.milenio.com/estados/coronavirus-confirman-el-primer-muerto-en-morelos-por-covid-19 |title= Cuauht\u00e9moc Blanco confirma la primer muerte por COVID-19 en Morelos |author= |language=es |date= March 28, 2020 |website= Milenio}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.diariodemorelos.com/noticias/situaci-n-actual-del-coronavirus-covid-19-en-morelos?fbclid=IwAR2mfAxLsQlJ6o3tndIvL0n8fOLVDzTE0pSZewHYL9ReOGBi6UznpBcmv4Y |title= SITUACI\u00d3N ACTUAL DEL CORONAVIRUS COVID-19 EN MORELOS |author= |language=es |date= March 28, 2020 |website= Diario de Morelos}}</ref> San Luis Potosi suspended wakes and funerals; the dead should be taken directly from the hospital to the [[crematorium]].<ref name=funeral>{{cite web |url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/estados/coronavirus-suspenden-funerales-por-covid-19-en-san-luis-potosi |title= Suspenden funerales por COVID-19 en San Luis Potos\u00ed |author= Redacci\u00f3n El Universal |language=es |date= March 28, 2020 |website= El Universal}}</ref>\n\nTabasco Governor [[Ad\u00e1n Augusto L\u00f3pez Hern\u00e1ndez]] tested positive for COVID-19 on March 29.<ref name=loppez_hernandez>{{cite web |url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/estados/coronavirus-gobernador-de-tabasco-da-positivo-covid-19-0 |title= Gobernador de Tabasco da positivo al Covid-19 |author=  |language=es |date= March 29, 2020 |website= El Universal}}</ref> Two tunnels with disinfectant spray were installed in the subways system of [[General Escobedo|Escobedo, Nuevo Le\u00f3n]].<ref>[https://www.excelsior.com.mx/nacional/por-covid-19-colocan-tuneles-para-desinfectar-hasta-30-personas-por-minuto/1372842 Por Covid-19, colocan t\u00faneles para desinfectar hasta 30 personas por minuto] {{in lang|es}} by Aracely Garza, Excelsior, 29 Mar 2020</ref> The government of [[Yucat\u00e1n]] threatens fines of $86,000 pesos and up to three years in prison for individuals who have tested positive for coronavirus and do not self-quarantine.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://noticieros.televisa.com/ultimas-noticias/coronavirus-multas-86-mil-pesos-personas-enfermas-aislen-yucatan/ |title= Multas de 86 mil pesos a personas con coronavirus que no se a\u00edslen en Yucat\u00e1n |author=  |language=es |date= March 29, 2020 |website= Noticieros Televisa}}</ref> The state of [[Quer\u00e9taro]] registered its first death from COVID-19, a 56-year-old man.<ref name=gov_tabasco>[https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/estados/coronavirus-queretaro-registra-la-primera-muerte-por-covid-19 Quer\u00e9taro registra la primera muerte por COVID-19] {{in lang|es}} El Universal, 29 March 2020</ref> The same day 993 cases of COVID-19 and 20 deaths from the disease were confirmed.<ref name=\"29march\">{{cite web|url= https://www.publimetro.com.mx/mx/coronavirus-covid-19/2020/03/29/casos-muertes-coronavirus-mexico-29-marzo-2020.html | title= Suman 993 casos de coronavirus en M\u00e9xico; hay 20 muertos|author=Publimetro |work=Publimetro|language=es|date= March 29, 2020}}</ref> Between 27 and 29 March, 566 Mexicans were brought home from other countries: 62 from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Colombia|Colombia]], 53 from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Ecuador|Ecuador]], 299 from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Peru|Peru]], 28 from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Guatemala|Guatemala (via land)]], and 134 from [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Cuba|Cuba]]. In turn, the Mexican government helped 86 people return to Ecuador, 99 to Peru, and 49 to Cuba.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.jornada.com.mx/ultimas/politica/2020/03/29/en-dos-dias-fueron-repatriados-576-mexicanos-suman-mas-de-8-mil-8945.html |title= En dos d\u00edas, fueron repatriados 576 mexicanos; suman m\u00e1s de 8 mil |author=La Redacci\u00f3n  |language=es |date= March 29, 2020 |website= La Jornada}}</ref>\n\nOn March 30, the total number of cases of COVID-19 surpassed one thousand with 1,094 confirmed cases and 28 reported deaths in the country. In the evening, a national health emergency was declared by Secretary [[Marcelo Ebrard]]; all sectors in the country are urged to stop most of their activities.<ref name=\"30march\">{{cite web|url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/sociedad/coronavirus-30-de-marzo-mexico-supera-los-mil-contagios-de-coronavirus-suman-mil-94 | title= M\u00c9XICO, EN EMERGENCIA SANITARIA; SUPERA LOS MIL CASOS DE CORONAVIRUS |author=Redacci\u00f3n  |work=El Universal|language=es|date= March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the early morning of March 31, 50,000 test kits, 100,000 masks and five ventilators (donated by [[Jack Ma]] and the [[Alibaba Group|Alibaba]] Foundation of China) arrived at the [[Mexico City International Airport]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://aristeguinoticias.com/0104/mexico/llegan-a-mexico-50-mil-kits-de-pruebas-para-detectar-covid-19-donados-por-china/ |title= Llegan a M\u00e9xico 50 mil kits de pruebas para detectar Covid-19, donados por China |author= |language=es |date= March 31, 2020 |website= Aristegui Noticias}}</ref> Nurses in Jalisco have been forced to get off public transportation and physically attacked by people fearful of COVID-19. Medical workers there and elsewhere have been advised not to wear their uniforms outside the hospital.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.infobae.com/america/mexico/2020/03/31/bajan-del-transporte-a-enfermeras-en-jalisco-y-les-rocian-cloro-por-miedo-a-contagios-de-covid-19/ |title= Bajan del transporte a enfermeras en Jalisco y les roc\u00edan cloro por miedo a contagios de Covid-19 |author= |language=es |date= March 31, 2020 |website= Infobae}}</ref> The same day the total confirmed cases of COVID-19 reached 1215 and one more death was reported. The government of [[Mexico City]] announced that 90% of the businesses in Mexico City would have to close because of the national health emergency declaration of the day before.<ref name=\"31march\">{{cite web|url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/coronavirus-31-de-marzo-casos-de-covid-19-en-mexico-llegan-mil-215-hay-29-muertos | title= CASOS DE CORONAVIRUS EN M\u00c9XICO LLEGAN A MIL 215; HAY 29 MUERTOS |author=Redacci\u00f3n  |work=El Universal|language=es|date= March 31, 2020}}</ref> In [[Austin, Texas]], Public Health officials started investigating an apparent cluster of COVID-19 after 28 of 70 \u201cspring breakers\u201d (students at the [[University of Texas at Austin]]) tested positive following their trip to [[Cabo San Lucas]], [[Baja California Sur]], in early March.<ref>{{cite web|website=[[KXAN-TV]]|date=March 31, 2020|title=28 of 70 spring breakers on Mexico trip test positive for coronavirus |url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KXAN-TV}}</ref> The [[Mexican Social Security Institute|Mexican Social Security Institute (IMSS)]] in [[Monclova]], Coahuila, reported that 29 medical and nursing staff tested positive for COVID-19. No patients have been infected.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-mexico/coronavirus-infects-29-medical-workers-at-mexico-hospital-idUSKBN21J3W2 |title= Coronavirus infects 29 medical workers at Mexico hospital |author= |language=en |date= March 31, 2020 |website= Reuters}}</ref>\n\n=== April 2020 ===\n\n==== April 1 to 15 ====\n[[File: Monterrey airport covid19.jpg |thumbnail|right|People wearing face masks at the [[Monterrey International Airport]] due to the COVID-19 pandemic.]]\nIt was reported on April 1 that seven migrants from Puebla residing in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)|New York]] have died of COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.animalpolitico.com/2020/04/siete-migrantes-poblanos-muertos-nueva-york-covid-19/ |title= Suman siete migrantes poblanos muertos en Nueva York por COVID-19 |author= |language=es |date= April 1, 2020 |website= Animal Pol\u00edtico}}</ref> Authorities reported 46% of cases as recoveries, which represents approximately 634 recoveries.<ref name=\"youtube1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=urlavWn2FWw&feature=youtu.be&t=675 |title=#ConferenciaDePrensa: #Coronavirus #COVID19 #Qu\u00e9dateEnCasaYa &#124; 1\u00b0 de abril de 2020 |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=2020-04-02}}</ref> In Coahuila, 21  health workers contracted the virus and one doctor died from it, bringing the number of deaths among doctors employed by IMSS to four. Nineteen of the 21 cases in Coahuila are mild and the individuals are ambulatory.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/several-health-workers-have-contracted-covid-19-mexico |title= Several health workers have contracted COVID-19 in Mexico |author= |language=en |date= April 1, 2020 |website= El Universal English}}</ref> Later the same day, 1,378 cases and 37 deaths of COVID-19 were reported in Mexico.<ref name=\"1april\">{{cite web|url= https://heraldodemexico.com.mx/pais/coronavirus-covid-19-mexico-resumen-miercoles-1-abril-2020-secretaria-salud-muertos-contagiados-cifras/ | title= Coronavirus en M\u00e9xico: Resumen mi\u00e9rcoles 1 de abril 2020 |author= Redacci\u00f3n Digital El Heraldo de M\u00e9xico |work=El Heraldo de M\u00e9xico|language=es|date= April 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 2, 1,510 cases of COVID-19 and 13 more deaths related to the disease were confirmed by Mexican authorities.<ref name=\"2april\">{{cite web|url= https://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/nacional/llega-a-50-la-cifra-de-muertos-por-coronavirus-y-van-mil-510-casos-confirmados | title= Llega a 50 la cifra de muertos por coronavirus en M\u00e9xico y van mil 510 casos confirmados |author=Redacci\u00f3n  |work=El Financiero|language=es|date= April 2, 2020}}</ref> In Mexico City, as hotels are forced to close, hotel guests are evicted from their rooms.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.elsoldemexico.com.mx/metropoli/cdmx/a-la-calle-hoteles-de-la-cdmx-desalojan-a-huespedes-ante-cuarentena-pandemia-covid-19-coronavirus-5052588.html |title= \u00a1A la calle! Hoteles de la CDMX desalojan a hu\u00e9spedes ante Covid-19 |author= Eduardo Torres |language=es |date= April 2, 2020 |website= El Sol de M\u00e9xico}}</ref>\n\nOn April 3, 1,688 cases and 60 deaths were confirmed by the Secretariat of Health.<ref name=\"3april\">{{cite web|url= https://politica.expansion.mx/mexico/2020/04/03/los-casos-positivos-de-coronavirus-se-elevan-a-1-688-y-a-60-los-decesos| title= Los casos positivos de coronavirus se elevan a 1,688 y a 60 los decesos|author=Expansi\u00f3n Pol\u00edtica  |work=Expansi\u00f3n Pol\u00edtica|language=es|date= April 3, 2020}}</ref> The following day, 202 more cases and 19 more deaths were confirmed by Mexican authorities.<ref name=\"4april\">{{cite web|url= https://www.dineroenimagen.com/actualidad/aumenta-1890-el-numero-de-contagiados-por-coronavirus-en-mexico/121274 | title= Aumenta a 1,890 el n\u00famero de contagiados por coronavirus en M\u00e9xico |author= |work=Dinero en Imagen |language=es|date= April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 5, President L\u00f3pez Obrador presented his plan to reactivate the economy. He said he did not want to increase fuel prices or taxes, and he was looking to hire more medical professionals for the armed forces. He said there was sufficient money to build the proposed thermoelectric plants that are needed in Yucat\u00e1n, Baja California and elsewhere. He stated that he had support from the private sector and he expressed his confidence that Mexico would soon overcome the current crisis.<ref name=plan>{{cite web|website=Mexico AS|title=AMLO presenta sus medidas para reactivar econom\u00eda ante el COVID-19 |language=es|trans-title=AMLO presents his measures to revive the economy effected by COVID-19|date=Apr 5, 2020 |author=Uriel Salmeron |url=https://mexico.as.com/mexico/2020/04/06/tikitakas/1586130668_050121.html}}</ref> On the same day , the total number of cases surpassed two thousand with 2143 cases and 94 deaths.<ref name=\"5april\">{{cite web|url= https://noticieros.televisa.com/ultimas-noticias/coronavirus-conferencia-mexico-hoy-5-abril-2020/ | title= Suman 94 muertos en M\u00e9xico por coronavirus; hay 2 mil 143 casos |author= Noticieros Televisa |work=Noticieros Televisa |language=es|date= April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n\nPresident L\u00f3pez Obrador and Governor Blanco of Morelos dedicated the ISSSTE hospital \u201cCarlos Calero\u201d in Cuernavaca that was going to be set aside to care for patients with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web|website=Mexico AS|title=Cuauht\u00e9moc Blanco y AMLO pusieron ejemplo de la 'sana distancia' |language=es|trans-title=Cuauht\u00e9moc Blanco and AMLO set an example of \u2018social distancing\u2019|date=Apr 5, 2020 |author=Erick de la Rosa |url=https://mexico.as.com/mexico/2020/04/05/tikitakas/1586047733_148789.html}}</ref> Fifteen new deaths were registered on April 5, bringing the total to 94. The age range of the deceased was from 26 to 91 years old with a median age of 56.5. Of the 94 dead, 79% were males and 21% were females.<ref>{{cite web |website=Mexico AS|title=Muertos por Coronavirus en M\u00e9xico hoy, 5 de abril|language=es|trans-title=Deaths by Coronavirus in Mexico today, April 5|date=Apr 5, 2020 |author=Juan Carlos Navarro |url=https://mexico.as.com/autor/juan_carlos_navarro_hernandez/a/}}</ref>\n\nOn April 6, 2,439 cases were confirmed and the total number of deaths surpassed one hundred with 125 deaths reported.<ref name=\"6april\">{{cite web|url= https://heraldodemexico.com.mx/pais/muertos-mexico-covid-19-casos-confirmados-coronavirus-corte-secretaria-salud-lunes-6-abril-2020/ | title= COVID-19 en M\u00e9xico: Ssa reporta 125 muertos y dos mil 439 casos confirmados |author= Redacci\u00f3n Digital El Heraldo de M\u00e9xico |work=El Heraldo de M\u00e9xico |language=es|date= April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[List of diplomatic missions of Mexico|Mexican Consulate]] in [[Shanghai]], China, announced on April 7 that the [[Aerom\u00e9xico]] ''Misionero de Paz,'' a [[Boeing 787 Dreamliner|Boeing 787-8]] filled with emergency medical supplies was en route to Mexico.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://mty.telediario.mx/nacional/avion-con-suministros-medicos-por-covid-19-se-dirige-mexico-desde-china |title= Avi\u00f3n con suministros m\u00e9dicos por covid-19 se dirige a M\u00e9xico desde China |author= Milenio Digital |date= April 7, 2020 |language=es |website= Telediario}}</ref> That same day, 2785 cases and 141 deaths related to COVID-19 were confirmed.<ref name=\"7april\" >{{cite web |url= https://heraldodemexico.com.mx/pais/coronavirus-covid-19-mexico-resumen-muertos-contagiados-secretaria-salud-martes-7-abril-2020/ |title= Coronavirus en M\u00e9xico: Resumen martes 7 de abril 2020 |author= Redacci\u00f3n Digital El Heraldo de M\u00e9xico |date= April 7, 2020 |language=es |website= El Heraldo de M\u00e9xico}}</ref>\n\nOn April 8, twenty medical and nursing schools withdrew their students from social service in hospitals due to the lack of adequate protection.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.jornada.com.mx/ultimas/politica/2020/04/08/anuies-se-une-al-ipn-y-a-unam-y-retira-sus-estudiantes-de-hospitales-7806.html |title= Veintena de universidades tambi\u00e9n retira estudiantes de hospitales |author= Jos\u00e9 Antonio Rom\u00e1n |date= April 8, 2020 |language=es |website= La Jornada}}</ref> [[Hugo L\u00f3pez-Gatell Ram\u00edrez]], head of the Undersecretariat of Prevention and Health Promotion at the Mexican Secretariat of Health, estimated there were unconfirmed 26,519 cases of COVID-19 in the country.<ref name=\"sentinela\">{{cite web |url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/mexicos-health-ministry-estimates-there-are-26000-covid-19-cases-country |title= Mexico's Health Ministry estimates there are 26,000 COVID-19 cases in the country|author= Teresa Moreno |date= April 8, 2020 |language=en |website= El Universal}}</ref> In the evening it was announced that Mexico surpassed the three thousand confirmed cases with 3,181 cases and 174 deaths.<ref name=\"8april\">{{cite web |url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/coronavirus-8-de-abril-mexico-ya-supera-los-3-mil-contagios-de-covid-19-contabiliza-174 |title= M\u00c9XICO YA SUPERA LOS 3 MIL CONTAGIOS DE CORONAVIRUS; CONTABILIZA 174 MUERTOS |author= Redacci\u00f3n |date= April 8, 2020 |language=es |website= El Universal}}</ref> The following day, 260 more cases and 20 more deaths were reported by Mexican authorities.<ref name=\"9april\">{{cite web |url= https://heraldodemexico.com.mx/pais/muertos-mexico-covid19-casos-confirmados-coronavirus-reporte-secretaria-de-salud-jueves-9-abril-2020/ |title= COVID-19 M\u00e9xico: SSa reporta 194 muertos y tres mil 441 casos confirmados |author= Redacci\u00f3n Digital El Heraldo de M\u00e9xico |date= April 9, 2020 |language=es |website= El Heraldo de M\u00e9xico}}</ref> Jos\u00e9 Ignacio Precaido Santos of the General Health Council announced that at least 146 private hospitals will make beds available to treat COVID-19 patients on a non-profit basis.<ref name=beds>[https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/mexican-government-will-use-private-hospitals-treat-covid-19-patients Mexican government will use private hospitals to treat COVID-19 patients] El Universal {{in lang|en}}, 8 Apr 2020</ref>\n\nTwo pregnant women are among the 119 deaths reported as of April 9. These are the first two cases of pregnant women in Mexico to die from COVID-19; both had problems with [[obesity]] and [[Diabetes and pregnancy|diabetes]].<ref>{{cite web |title=First deaths of pregnant women from COVID-19 reported in Mexico |url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/first-deaths-pregnant-women-covid-19-reported-mexico |website=El Universal |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |language=en |date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 10, the total confirmed deaths surpassed two hundred with 233 deaths and 3,844 cases confirmed by Mexican authorities.<ref name=\"10april\">{{cite web |url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/coronavirus-10-de-abril-mexico-supera-los-200-muertos-por-covid-19-llega-3-mil-844-contagios |title= M\u00c9XICO SUPERA LOS 200 MUERTOS POR COVID-19; LLEGA A 3 MIL 844 CONTAGIOS |author= Redacci\u00f3n |date= April 10, 2020 |language=es |website= El Universal}}</ref> The government of [[Baja California]] closed a plant belonging to the multinational giant [[Smiths Group]] after the firm refused to sell [[ventilator]]s to the Mexican government.<ref> {{cite web |url= https://apnews.com/685d5779e5a3607bcc56ac79b168701c |title= Mexico closes US owned plant for refusal to sell ventilators |author= |date= April 10, 2020 |language=en |website= AP}}</ref> On the same day, [[List of diplomatic missions of Mexico|Mexican consulates in the United States]] announced the deaths of 181 Mexican nationals due to the COVID-19 pandemic. One hundred forty-nine of those cases were in [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)|New York]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/covid-19-dozens-mexicans-have-died-us-coronavirus |title= COVID-19: dozens of Mexicans have died in the U.S. from coronavirus |author= |date= April 11, 2020 |language=en |website= El Universal}}</ref> The national network of women shelters reports a 60% increase in calls for help since the coronavirus pandemic began.<ref>{{cite web |title=Domestic abuse spikes in Mexico amid virus outbreak |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/domestic-abuse-spikes-mexico-virus-outbreak-200410143527001.html |website=www.aljazeera.com |accessdate=Apr 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 11, 375 more cases and 40 more deaths were confirmed.<ref name=\"11april\">{{cite web |url=https://www.elfinanciero.com.mx/salud/casos-confirmados-de-covid-19-suben-a-4-219-se-registran-273-muertes |title= CASOS CONFIRMADOS DE COVID-19 SUBEN A 4,219; SE REGISTRAN 273 MUERTES |author= Redacci\u00f3n |date= April 11, 2020 |language=es |website= El Financiero}}</ref> Nineteen Mexican agricultural workers in [[Kelowna]], British Columbia, Canada, have contracted the disease but none are reported as serious.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/19-mexican-agricultural-workers-have-contracted-covid-19-canada |title= 19 Mexican agricultural workers have contracted COVID-19 in Canada |author= |date= April 11, 2020 |language=en |website= El Universal}}</ref>\n\nOn April 12, the government established the \"National Contigency Center\" (CNC) to fight COVID-19. It will be led by the military and will have scientists and health technicians advising about steps to combat the pandemic.<ref name=cnc>{{cite web |url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/mexico-creates-national-contingency-center-fight-covid-19-pandemic |title= Mexico creates the National Contingency Center to fight the COVID-19 pandemic |author= |date= April 12, 2020 |language=en |website= El Universal}}</ref>\n\nOn April 13, the number of COVID-19 infections in the country passed 5,000; there were 332 deaths.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/nacion/coronavirus-13-de-abril-mexico-supera-los-5-mil-casos-de-covid-19-llega-332-muertos |title= M\u00e9xico supera los 5 mil casos de covid-19, llega 332 muertos |author= |date= April 13, 2020 |language=es |website= El Universal}}</ref> The [[Mexican Navy]] announced it would open ten voluntary self-isolation units to shelter 4,000 COVID-19 victims in Mexico City, Guerrero, Jalisco, Michoacan, Sinaloa, Tamaulipas and Veracruz.<ref name=voluntary>{{cite web |url= https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/mexico-will-open-10-voluntary-isolation-centers-amid-covid-19-pandemic |title= Mexico will open 10 voluntary isolation centers amid the COVID-19 pandemic |author= |date= April 13, 2020 |language=en |website= El Universal}}</ref> Sonora became the first state in the country to declare a curfrew.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.infobae.com/america/mexico/2020/04/14/coronavirus-en-mexico-sonora-es-el-primer-estado-en-decretar-el-confinamiento-obligatorio-con-sanciones/|title=Coronavirus in Mexico: Sonora is the first state to decree mandatory confinement with sanctions|last=|first=|date=|website=Infobae|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nOn April 14, Governor [[Antonio Echevarr\u00eda Garc\u00eda]] of Nayarit said he wanted to close the state's borders to visitors from Jalisco and Sinaloa, noting that young, apparently healthy people from other areas have visited their elderly relatives in the state. ''Y son las personas que han fallecido y estas personas que vienen del otro lado traen el virus, no presentan ning\u00fan s\u00edntoma y hacen la contaminadera,'' (\"And they are the people who have died and these people who come from the other side bring the virus, do not present any symptoms and cause the contamination\") said Echevarr\u00eda.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.informador.mx/mexico/Nayarit-busca-cerrar-fronteras-con-Jalisco-y-Sinaloa-20200414-0108.html |title= Nayarit busca cerrar fronteras con Jalisco y Sinaloa |author=SUN |date= April 14, 2020 |language=es |website= El Informador}}</ref> Oaxaca Governor [[Alejandro Murat Hinojosa]] reported the theft of more than 20 kits of medical supplies used for treatment of COVID-19 were stolen from the Aurelio Valdivieso General Hospital. A week earlier, seven ventilators had been stolen from the IMSS hospital.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://mexiconewsdaily.com/news/coronavirus/covid-19-treatment-equipment-stolen-in-oaxaca/ |title= Ventilators, other Covid-19 treatment equipment stolen in Oaxaca |author= |date= April 14, 2020 |language=es |website= Mexico News Daily}}</ref> Baja California Governor [[Jaime Bonilla Valdez]] said that doctors in Tijuana are \u201cfalling like flies\u201d as 21 medical workers at IMSS clinic #20 have been diagnosed with COVID-19 and 15 others are suspected of having it; one doctor at the IMSS general hospital has been infected and six have suspected cases.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://mexiconewsdaily.com/news/coronavirus/doctors-are-falling-like-flies-in-tijuana/ |title= Doctors are \u2018falling like flies\u2019 in Tijuana, Baja California governor warns |author= |date= April 14, 2020 |language=es |website= Mexico News Daily}}</ref> \n\nAn April 15 report by ''Quinto Elemento Lab'' showed that 30% of Mexicans cannot get local information about COVID-19 infections. [[Mexico City]] does not break down statistics for its 16 boroughs, and the [[State of Mexico]], [[Quer\u00e9taro]], [[Tlaxcala]], and [[Yucat\u00e1n]] do not reveal information on the municipal level. Governments said revealing the information would violate patients' privacy.<ref> {{cite web |url= https://mexiconewsdaily.com/news/coronavirus/local-level-stats-showing-covid-19-infection-are-secret/ |title= In 4 states and CDMX, local-level stats showing Covid-19 infection are secret |author= |date= April 15, 2020 |language=es |website= Mexico News Daily}}</ref> The [[National Guard (Mexico)|National Guard]] began providing security support for hospitals run by the IMSS in nineteen states on April 15.<ref>{{cite web |title=COVID-19: Mexico\u2019s National Guard steps in to protect IMSS hospitals |url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/covid-19-mexicos-national-guard-steps-protect-imss-hospitals |website=El Universal |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |language=en |date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== April 16 to 30 ====\n[[File:A clothing shop Tijuana's Plaza Rio shopping mall closed due to COVID-19..jpg|thumb|A [[Clothes shop|clothes store]] in [[Plaza R\u00edo Tijuana]] closed due to COVID-19.]]\n\nThe first death attributed to COVID-19 of a minor under 25 is reported in [[Tabasco]] on April 16, a two-year-old girl with [[Down syndrome]] and [[Congenital heart defect|congenital heart disease]].<ref>{{cite web |title=First COVID-19 death of minor registered in Mexico |url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/first-covid-19-death-minor-registered-mexico |website=El Universal |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |language=en |date=16 April 2020}}</ref> The government announced on April 16 that it will restrict transportation between areas of the country that are infected with COVID-19 (mostly large cities) and areas that are not infected, without specifying what areas are included or how it will be enforced.<ref name=travel>{{cite web|url= https://apnews.com/9e5bb61c8bb22aba3fe0557aa82f592e | title= Mexico to restrict mobility to areas less affected by virus |author= AP|work=AP|language=en|date= April 16, 2020}}</ref> President L\u00f3pez Obrador also said that based upon current projections, the 979 municipalities that have not had reported cases of coronavirus will be able to reopen schools and workplaces on May 17; the date is June 1 for the 463 municipalities that have. The elderly and other vulnerable groups will still be requested to stay home, and physical distancing should remain in place until May 30. It is expected that the pandemic will end in the metropolitan area on June 25.<ref name=reopen>{{cite web |title=COVID-19: Mexicans will return to work and school between May 17 and June 1 |url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/covid-19-mexicans-will-return-work-and-school-between-may-17-and-june-1 |website=El Universal |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |language=en |date=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[TV Azteca]] called for the public to ignore information and warnings from [[Hugo L\u00f3pez-Gatell Ram\u00edrez]]. {{quote|Como todas las noches, el subsecretario de Salud, Hugo L\u00f3pez-Gatell encabez\u00f3 la conferencia sobre el covid-19 en M\u00e9xico. Pero sus cifras y sus conferencias ya se volvieron irrelevantes. Es m\u00e1s, se lo decimos con todas sus palabras, ya no le haga caso a Hugo L\u00f3pez-Gatell\u201d ''(\u201cLike every night, the Undersecretary of Health, Hugo L\u00f3pez-Gatell led the conference on COVID-19 in Mexico. But his numbers and conferences have already become irrelevant. Moreover, we tell him with all his words, no longer pay attention to Hugo L\u00f3pez-Gatell\u201d)''}} was tweeted by TV Aztec on April 17.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tourliere |first1=Mathieu |title=TV Azteca llama a ya no hacerle caso a L\u00f3pez-Gatell |url=https://www.proceso.com.mx/626362/tv-azteca-llama-a-ya-no-hacerle-caso-a-lopez-gatell?fbclid=IwAR0dmgzfLY3P8LjekSLDrrphhVS7v9YqtSLn7nJOA4BZ_FIj4OsjHrEBcXU |website=Proceso portal de noticias |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |language=es-MX |date=18 April 2020|trans-title=TV Azteca calls to no longer pay attention to L\u00f3pez-Gatell}}</ref> President L\u00f3pez Obrador\u2032s proposal for a [[United Nations General Assembly]] resolution to prevent price gouging or hording of medical supplies by wealthy countries has 161 co-sponsors. The proposal was first made during a video conference of the G20.<ref>{{cite web |title=Apoyan 161 pa\u00edses PROPUESTA de M\u00c9XICO ante la ONU para EVITAR ACAPARAMIENTO de insumos contra el Covid-19 |url=https://www.sdpnoticias.com/internacional/propuesta-mexico-onu-insumos-contra-covid-19-amlo-juan-ramon-de-la-fuente.html?fbclid=IwAR3v9kiclsYKdw3qscD66glz1LmxIiq25vf2sauvNSst6qAx1nJEQtffAGg |website=SDPnoticias.com |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |language=spanish|trans-title=Mexico's proposal receives majority support among UN members}}</ref> [[Pemex]] reports 10 deaths, 92 cases, and 1,052 suspected cases of COVID-19. 17 have recovered.<ref>{{cite web |title=Pemex registers COVID-19 cases among its workers and beneficiaries |url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/pemex-registers-covid-19-cases-among-its-workers-and-beneficiaries-0 |website=El Universal |accessdate=April 18, 2020 |language=en |date=17 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn April 18, Alonso P\u00e9rez Rico, Health Secretary for Baja California, reported that at least 30 doctors in the state, principally in [[Mexicali Municipality|Mexicali]], have tested positive for COVID-19. None is critical.<ref>{{cite web |title=Reportan a 30 m\u00e9dicos con COVID-19 en BC |url=https://www.debate.com.mx/estados/Reportan-a-30-medicos-con-Covid-19-en-BC--20200417-0324.html |website=EL DEBATE |language=es-ES|trans-title=30 doctors in BC reported with COVID-19}}</ref>\n\nOn April 20 the [[Secretariat of National Defense (Mexico)|Secretariat of National Defense (Sedena)]] announced that it had hired 3,158 of the 4,572 health professionals it needs.<ref>{{cite web |title=La Sedena ha contratado tres mil 158 m\u00e9dicos y enfermeras por coronavirus |url=https://www.informador.mx/mexico/La-Sedena-ha-contratado-tres-mil-158-medicos-y-enfermeras-por-coronavirus-20200421-0094.html |website=El Informador :: Noticias de Jalisco, M\u00e9xico, Deportes & Entretenimiento |accessdate=Apr 21, 2020 |language=es-ES|trans-title=Sedena has hired 3,158 doctors and nurses for coronavirus}}</ref> A Venezuelan YouTuber residing in Mexico City broke quarantine after being diagnosed with COVID-19 on April 20. Authorities had to sanitize the grocery store he contaminated and his immigration status was being investigated. His girlfriend similarly broke quarantine a few days earlier.<ref>{{cite web |title=Venezuelan youtuber diagnosed with COVID-19 sparks outrage after he ignored isolation measures in Mexico City |url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/venezuelan-youtuber-diagnosed-covid-19-sparks-outrage-after-he-ignored-isolation-measures |website=El Universal {{in lang|en}} |accessdate=Apr 21, 2020 |language=en |date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nMexico entered Phase 3 of its contingency plan on April 21. 712 deaths and 8,772 confirmed cases were reported.<ref name=phase3>{{cite web |title=Mexico enters Phase 3 of its contingency plan to fight COVID-19 |url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/mexico-enters-phase-3-its-contingency-plan-fight-covid-19 |website=El Universal {{in lang|en}} |accessdate=Apr 21, 2020 |language=en |date=21 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nRecently{{When|date=April 2020}} it has come to media attention that the Mexican drug cartels, in an effort to boost their own popularity and in response to poor efforts by the Mexican presidency, have been distributing supplies to impoverished citizens in the street.<ref> https://www.businessinsider.com/mexican-cartels-are-giving-out-coronavirus-aid-to-elderly-residents-2020-4</ref> The president of Mexico has since called on the cartels to stop distributing supplies and \u201cend violence\u201d instead.<ref> https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/04/mexico-president-tells-gangs-stop-handing-coronavirus-aid-200421060420772.html</ref>\n\nThe number of coronavirus cases surges past 10,000 to 10,544 with 970 deaths on April 21.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus en M\u00e9xico: son 970 muertes y 10,544 casos confirmados |url=https://www.infobae.com/america/mexico/2020/04/23/coronavirus-en-mexico-son-970-muertes-y-10544-casos-confirmados/ |website=Infobae |accessdate=Apr 23, 2020 |language=es-ES|trans-title=Coronavirus en M\u00e9xico: son 970 muertes y 10,544 casos confirmados}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n\n=== [[Secretariat of Health (Mexico)|SALUD]] reported Mexico totals ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"display: inline-table; font-size:90%; text-align:right;\"\n|+ <big> As of April 22</big>\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"  style=\"text-align:left; width:140px;\"|State\n! style=\"width:60px;\"| Cumulative cases\n! style=\"width:60px;\"| Active cases\n! Deaths\n! Recoveries\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:right; padding-right:18px;\" scope=\"row\" | 10,544\n! style=\"text-align:right; padding-right:18px;\" scope=\"row\" | 3618\n! style=\"text-align:right; padding-right:18px;\" scope=\"row\" | 970\n! style=\"text-align:right; padding-right:18px;\" scope=\"row\" | 634\n|-\n!style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Mexico City}}\n||2815||1085||251||196\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|State of Mexico}}\n||1593||584||82||102\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Baja California}}\n||985||300||118||31\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Sinaloa}}\n||568||206||59||12\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Tabasco}}\n||510||226||60||36\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Quintana Roo}}\n||432||111||56||38\n|-\n! style=\"text-align:left\" |{{Flag2|Puebla}}\n||388||87||56||46\n|-\n! style=\"text-align: